c|time=show}} ([[BMT Fourth Avenue Line]])<br>{{NYCS Eastern west|time=show}} ([[IRT Eastern Parkway Line]])\n| [[Long Island Rail Road|LIRR]] [[Atlantic Branch]] at [[Atlantic Terminal (LIRR station)|Atlantic Terminal]]\n|-\n| align=center | {{NYCS SSI|alltimes}}\n| [[Seventh Avenue (BMT Brighton Line)|Seventh Avenue]]\n|\n| {{NYCS Brighton north|time=show|exclude=Q}}\n|\n|-\n| align=center | {{NYCS SSI|alltimes}}\n| [[Prospect Park (BMT Brighton Line)|Prospect Park]]\n| align=center | {{Access icon}}\n| {{NYCS Brighton north|time=show|exclude=Q}}<br>{{NYCS Franklin|time=show}} ([[BMT Franklin Avenue Line]])\n|\n|-\n| align=center | {{NYCS SSI|alltimes}}\n| [[Parkside Avenue (BMT Brighton Line)|Parkside Avenue]]\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n| align=center | {{NYCS SSI|alltimes}}\n| [[Church Avenue (BMT Brighton Line)|Church Avenue]]\n|\n| {{NYCS Brighton|time=show|exclude=Q}}\n|\n|-\n| align=center | {{NYCS SSI|alltimes}}\n| [[Beverley Road (BMT Brighton Line)|Beverley Road]]\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n| align=center | {{NYCS SSI|alltimes}}\n| [[Cortelyou Road (BMT Brighton Line)|Cortelyou Road]]\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n| align=center | {{NYCS SSI|alltimes}}\n| [[Newkirk Plaza (BMT Brighton Line)|Newkirk Plaza]]\n|\n| {{NYCS Brighton|time=show|exclude=Q}}\n|\n|-\n| align=center | {{NYCS SSI|alltimes}}\n| [[Avenue H (BMT Brighton Line)|Avenue H]]\n| align=center | {{Access icon}}&nbsp;\u2193\n|\n|Station is [[Americans with Disabilities Act of 1990|ADA-accessible]] in the southbound direction only\n|-\n| align=center | {{NYCS SSI|alltimes}}\n| [[Avenue J (BMT Brighton Line)|Avenue J]]\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n| align=center | {{NYCS SSI|alltimes}}\n| [[Avenue M (BMT Brighton Line)|Avenue M]]\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n| align=center | {{NYCS SSI|alltimes}}\n| [[Kings Highway (BMT Brighton Line)|Kings Highway]]\n| align=center | {{Access icon}}\n| {{NYCS Brighton|time=show|exclude=Q}}\n| [[B82 (New York City bus)|B82 Select Bus Service]]\n|-\n| align=center | {{NYCS SSI|alltimes}}\n| [[Avenue U (BMT Brighton Line)|Avenue U]]\n|\n|\n| \n|-\n| align=center | {{NYCS SSI|alltimes}}\n| [[Neck Road (BMT Brighton Line)|Neck Road]]\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n| align=center | {{NYCS SSI|alltimes}}\n| [[Sheepshead Bay (BMT Brighton Line)|Sheepshead Bay]]\n|\n| {{NYCS Brighton|time=show|exclude=Q}}\n|\n|-\n| align=center | {{NYCS SSI|alltimes}}\n| [[Brighton Beach (BMT Brighton Line)|Brighton Beach]]\n|\n| {{NYCS Brighton|time=show|exclude=Q}}\n|\n|-\n| align=center | {{NYCS SSI|alltimes}}\n| [[Ocean Parkway (BMT Brighton Line)|Ocean Parkway]]\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n| align=center | {{NYCS SSI|alltimes}}\n| [[West Eighth Street\u2013New York Aquarium (BMT Brighton Line)|West Eighth Street\u2013New York Aquarium]]\n|\n| {{NYCS Culver IND south|time=show}} ([[IND Culver Line]])\n|\n|-\n| align=center | {{NYCS SSI|alltimes}}\n| [[Coney Island\u2013Stillwell Avenue (BMT Brighton Line)|Coney Island\u2013Stillwell Avenue]]\n| align=center | {{Access icon}}\n| {{NYCS West End far south|time=show}} ([[BMT West End Line]])<br>{{NYCS Culver IND south|time=show}} ([[IND Culver Line]])<br>{{NYCS Sea Beach south|time=show}} ([[BMT Sea Beach Line]])\n|\n|}\n\n==Notes==\n{{Notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscat|Q (New York City Subway service)}}\n* [http://web.mta.info/nyct/service/qline.htm MTA NYC Transit \u2013 Q Broadway Express]\n* {{NYCS const|traintime|Q}}\n* {{NYCS const|timetable|q}}\n\n{{NYCS navbox}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Q (New York City Subway Service)}}\n[[Category:Brooklyn-Manhattan Transit Corporation|#]]\n[[Category:New York City Subway services]]\n", "name_user": "LRG5784", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200e1988\u20132001: Sixth Avenue service:punctuation", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Q_(New_York_City_Subway_service)"}
{"title_page": "Weezer (Blue Album)", "text_new": "{{Redirect|The World Has Turned and Left Me Here|the ''Vampire Diaries'' episode|The World Has Turned and Left Me Here (The Vampire Diaries)}}\n{{Redirect|No One Else|the showtune|Natasha, Pierre & the Great Comet of 1812}}\n{{short description|1994 album by Weezer}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2012}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Weezer\n| type       = studio\n| artist     = [[Weezer]]\n| cover      = Weezer - Blue Album.png\n| alt        =\n| released   = May 10, 1994\n| recorded   = August\u2013September 1993\n| studio     = [[Electric Lady Studios]], [[New York City]]\n| genre      = {{flatlist|\n* [[Alternative rock]]\n* [[power pop]]\n* [[pop punk]]\n* [[pop rock]]\n}}<!-- Genres sourced in article -->\n| length     = 41:26\n| label      = [[DGC Records|DGC]]\n| producer   = [[Ric Ocasek]]\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title = [[Pinkerton (album)|Pinkerton]]\n| next_year  = 1996\n| misc       = {{Singles\n | name        = Weezer\n | type        = studio\n | single1     = [[Undone \u2013 The Sweater Song]]\n | single1date = June 24, 1994\n | single2     = [[Buddy Holly (song)|Buddy Holly]]\n | single2date = September 7, 1994\n | single3     = [[Say It Ain't So]]\n | single3date = July 13, 1995\n}}\n}}\n\n'''''Weezer''''' (commonly known as the '''Blue Album''') is the eponymous debut [[studio album]] by American [[Rock music|rock]] band [[Weezer]], released on May 10, 1994 by [[DGC Records]]. The album came two years after the band's founding, after they initially struggled as an alternative to [[grunge|grunge music]], which was prevalent in [[Los Angeles]] during the early 1990s. It was almost entirely arranged and composed by frontman [[Rivers Cuomo]], who also anticipated to lead the band in self-producing the album. However, at the behest of DGC, the band was required to include a producer, and collectively opted for [[The Cars|Cars]] frontman [[Ric Ocasek]]. Most of the recording was conducted at [[Electric Lady Studios]] in [[New York City]] between August and September 1993, a period that coincided with founding guitarist [[Jason Cropper]] being fired and replaced by [[Brian Bell]].\n\nUnder Ocasek's direction, the band opted for a brighter sound, while bassist [[Matt Sharp]] collaborated with Cuomo to ensure that the album contained an overriding sonic concept of treating the guitars and bass as isolated ten-string instruments, thus maximizing its potential when united.<ref name=\"Pitchforklist\">{{cite web | last = DiCrescenzo | first = Brent | url = http://www.pitchforkmedia.com/article/feature/36737-staff-list-top-100-albums-of-the-1990s/page_8 | title = Top 100 Albums of the 1990s | publisher = [[Pitchfork Media|Pitchfork]] | accessdate = 2007-09-04 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071023195032/http://www.pitchforkmedia.com/article/feature/36737-staff-list-top-100-albums-of-the-1990s/page_8 | archivedate = October 23, 2007 | df = mdy-all }}</ref> Lyrically, ''Weezer'' focuses on outsiderdom and [[social awkwardness]], while also touching on melancholic themes of love, romance, and familial issues.<ref>https://www.udiscovermusic.com/stories/weezer-blue-album-power-pop/</ref> \n\n''Weezer'' was supported by the singles \"[[Undone \u2013 The Sweater Song]]\", \"[[Buddy Holly (song)|Buddy Holly]]\", and \"[[Say It Ain't So]]\", which, alongside their respective [[music video]]s, brought Weezer mainstream success. The album itself peaked at number sixteen on the [[Billboard 200|US ''Billboard'' 200]], and was certified [[RIAA certification|triple platinum]] by 1995. It is also the band's best-selling album, having sold at least 3.3 million copies in the U.S. and over fifteen million copies worldwide by 2009.<ref>{{cite web |first=Michael D.|last=Ayers| url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/267638/weezer-filled-with-raditude-this-fall | title=Weezer Filled With 'Raditude' This Fall | work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] | publisher=[[Eldridge Industries]] |location=Los Angeles, California| date=August 21, 2009 | accessdate=October 1, 2012}}</ref>\n\n== Background ==\nWeezer was formed on February 14, 1992, in Los Angeles by singer and guitarist [[Rivers Cuomo]], drummer [[Patrick Wilson (musician)|Patrick Wilson]], bassist [[Matt Sharp]], and guitarist [[Jason Cropper]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.upsetmagazine.com/features/weezer-interview-kings-of-the-world-white-album/|title=Weezer: Kings of the world {{!}} Interview {{!}} Upset|date=2016-05-06|language=en-US|access-date=2016-07-31}}</ref> Although they performed future hits including \"[[The Sweater Song]]\" and \"[[Say It Ain't So]]\", Cuomo said they struggled to engage audiences, who wanted to see [[grunge]] bands instead.<ref>{{harvnb|Luerssen|2004|p=67}}</ref> \n\nIn an effort to create buzz around LA, Weezer recorded a demo, ''[[The Kitchen Tape]]''.<ref>{{harvnb|Luerssen|2004|p=69}}</ref> This attracted attention from major-label A&R reps looking for alternative rock bands to perform on the same bill as [[That Dog]].<ref>{{harvnb|Luerssen|2004|p=76}}</ref> Weezer were signed to [[DGC Records]] on June 26, 1993, by Todd Sullivan, an A&R rep from [[Geffen Records]].<ref>{{harvnb|Luerssen|2004|p=82}}</ref>\n\n== Recording ==\nWhile preparing for the studio sessions, Weezer focused on their vocal interplay by practicing [[barbershop quartet]]-style songs, which helped Cuomo and Sharp feel more comfortable collaborating during rehearsals. Sharp, who had never sung before joining Weezer, developed his [[falsetto]]: \"I had to sing an octave higher than Rivers. After a lot of practice, I started to get it down.\"<ref>{{harvnb|Luerssen|2004|p=85}}</ref>\n\nWeezer rehearsed 15 songs in New York in preparation for the Electric Lady Studios recording sessions. Four songs from this rehearsal would not be attempted for the album: \"Lullaby for Wayne\", \"I Swear It's True\", \"Getting Up and Leaving\", and a reprise version of \"In the Garage\". The other song, an ode to two women who ran the Weezer fanclub called \"Mykel & Carli\", was attempted during the Electric Lady sessions, but was also abandoned (this recording was later released as a digital bonus track on the 2010 compilation ''[[Death to False Metal]]''). A later recording of \"Mykel & Carli\" was featured as a B-side on the \"[[Undone \u2013 The Sweater Song]]\" single.<ref>{{harvnb|Luerssen|2004|pp=88\u201391}}</ref>\n\nThe band considered self-producing, but were pressured by [[Geffen Records|Geffen]] to choose a producer. They decided on [[Ric Ocasek]], who had played with the [[The Cars|Cars]].<ref>{{harvnb|Luerssen|2004|p=87}}</ref> Ocasek convinced the band to change their [[Pick up (music technology)|guitar pickups]] from the neck to the bridge, resulting in a brighter sound.<ref>{{harvnb|Luerssen|2004|p=87}}</ref> Sharp and Cuomo imposed several rules on recording, banning [[Reverberation|reverb]] and insisting on all [[Downpicking|downstrokes]] on guitar.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-features/weezer-blue-album-25th-anniversary-877089/|title=The Strange Birth and Near Death of Weezer|last=Hiatt|first=Brian|last2=Hiatt|first2=Brian|date=2019-08-28|website=Rolling Stone|language=en-US|access-date=2019-08-30}}</ref> According to engineer Chris Shaw, the \"overriding concept\" was to treat the guitars and bass as a single, 10-string instrument, playing in unison. Weezer insisted that the guitars were mixed as loudly as those in the [[Radiohead]] song \"[[Creep (Radiohead song)|Creep]]\", burying some vocals.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nDuring the recording, Cropper learned that his girlfriend was pregnant and began acting erratically. Weezer collaborator Karl Koch said: \"He wasn't handling it well ... he always said he was fine, and then 20 minutes later he'd be up on the roof of Electric Lady screaming or something.\"<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=http://www.phawker.com/2014/10/02/excerpt-the-complete-oral-history-of-weezer/|title=EXCERPT: The Complete Oral History of Weezer|last=Valania|first=Jonathan|date=2 October 2014|work=Magnet|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180701140036/http://www.phawker.com/2014/10/02/excerpt-the-complete-oral-history-of-weezer/|archive-date=1 July 2018|url-status=dead|accessdate=22 May 2019}}</ref> According to Cropper, Cuomo told him he could not allow him to jeopardize the band's work and asked him to leave. In 2014, Cropper said Cuomo had made the right decision.<ref name=\":0\" /> Cropper was replaced by [[Brian Bell]].<ref>{{harvnb|Luerssen|2004|pp=88\u201391}}</ref> While Bell's vocals appear on some tracks,<ref>{{harvnb|Luerssen|2004|p=98}}</ref> Cuomo re-recorded all of Cropper's guitar parts.<ref>{{harvnb|Luerssen|2004|p=99}}</ref> Ocasek recalled: \"After [the album] was completely recorded, Rivers came in and said, 'I\u2019m firing the guitar player, and I\u2019m going to do all his guitar parts over.' I said, 'You can\u2019t do that!' But he did. In one take.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/rivers-cuomo-is-trying-to-be-all-right-167180/|title=Rivers Cuomo Is Trying to Be All Right|last=Vozick-Levinson|first=Simon|last2=Vozick-Levinson|first2=Simon|date=2014-09-23|website=Rolling Stone|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-22}}</ref> Bell is still credited for playing guitar in the liner notes. Cropper received a credit on \"[[My Name Is Jonas]]\" for writing the intro.<ref name=\"Luerssen 2004 61\">{{harvnb|Luerssen|2004|p=61}}</ref>\n\n== Artwork ==\nThe album artwork, photographed by American glamour photographer [[Peter Gowland]],<ref>{{cite web | url = http://uproxx.com/smokingsection/weezer-the-blue-album-cover-story-interview/ | title=\"Undone\": The Story Behind Weezer's Debut Album Cover| publisher = Uproxx| accessdate = 2016-02-26}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.weezerpedia.com/wiki/index.php?title=Karl%27s_Corner_-_01/22/2002| title = Karl's Corner \u2013 01/22/2002| publisher = Weezer.com| accessdate = 2016-02-26| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160312065114/http://www.weezerpedia.com/wiki/index.php?title=Karl%27s_Corner_-_01%2F22%2F2002| archive-date = March 12, 2016| url-status = dead| df = mdy-all}}</ref> features Wilson, Cuomo, Sharp, and Bell standing in front of a plain, blue background.<ref name=\"booklet\">''Weezer: Blue Album'' booklet and [[liner notes]]</ref> [[Adobe Photoshop]] was used to [[Photo manipulation|digitally alter]] the cover. Cuomo stated that, while the band liked the photo, Sharp was not happy with the way his head looked. The Geffen Art Director used Photoshop to swap out the head with one from another shot.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://students-adobe.com/NA#judgeHome3|title=Adobe Imagination Challenge \"Meet the Judges\"|publisher=Adobe|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110923153444/http://students-adobe.com/na#judgeHome3|archive-date=September 23, 2011|url-status=dead|accessdate=2011-08-11|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The image was used prominently in the advertising of the album.<ref name=\"Luerssen 2004 109\">{{harvnb|Luerssen|2004|p=109}}</ref> The cover received many comparisons to [[the Feelies]]' album ''[[Crazy Rhythms]]''.<ref name=\"Luerssen 2004 109\" />\n\nOn some vinyl pressings of the album, the cover does not crop off their feet. On the ''Deluxe Edition'' case the feet are presented on the back cover, and the band sold an official T-shirt with a shot of the band's feet after the deluxe edition release.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.weezer.com/info/tunes/index.html |title=Blue Album era releases (1982\u20131995) |accessdate=2007-08-31 |work=Weezer.com |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100813233431/http://www.weezer.com/info/tunes/index.html |archivedate=August 13, 2010 }}</ref>\n\nInside the album booklet, Cuomo pays tribute to his past [[Heavy metal music|metal]] influences with a photo taken in the group's garage on Amherst (this same garage would be featured in the \"Say It Ain't So\" music video). A poster of [[Judas Priest]]'s album ''[[British Steel (album)|British Steel]]'' is featured on the left side of the photo, while on the right a [[Quiet Riot]] concert poster is displayed. The ''Deluxe Edition'' features additional photographs of the band and hand-written lyrics for each song.<ref name=\"deluxeblue\">''Weezer: Blue Album (Deluxe Edition)'' booklet and [[liner notes]].</ref>\n\n== Promotion ==\nThe first single \"[[Undone \u2013 The Sweater Song]]\" was described by Cuomo as \"the feeling you get when the train stops and the little guy comes knockin' on your door. It was supposed to be a sad song, but everyone thinks it's hilarious.\"<ref name=\"Luerssen 2004 110\u2013111\">{{harvnb|Luerssen|2004|pp=110\u2013111}}</ref> The video marks one of the early directorial efforts of [[Spike Jonze]], whose pitch was simply \"A blue stage, a steadicam, a pack of wild dogs.\"<ref>{{harvnb|Luerssen|2004|p=120}}</ref> The video became an instant hit on MTV.<ref>{{harvnb|Luerssen|2004|p=121}}</ref> The final single, \"[[Say It Ain't So]]\", was inspired by Cuomo believing his parents split up when he was four because he thought his father was an [[alcoholic]].<ref name=\"Luerssen 2004 110\u2013111\" /> The music video, which was directed by [[Sophie Muller]], was less successful than the previous Spike Jonze-directed video. It featured the band performing in the garage of their former house, and the bandmates playing [[footbag|hacky sack]] in the backyard.<ref>{{harvnb|Luerssen|2004|pp=146\u2013147}}</ref>\n\n== Release ==\nThe Blue Album was released on May 10, 1994.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.altpress.com/features/entry/20_facts_you_may_not_know_about_weezers_blue_album|title=20 Facts You May Not Know About Weezer's Blue Album|last1=Heisel|first1=Scott|date=May 9, 2014|website=Alternative Press|publisher=Alternative Press|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150312051202/http://www.altpress.com/features/entry/20_facts_you_may_not_know_about_weezers_blue_album|archivedate=March 12, 2015|accessdate=February 10, 2016}}</ref> It was certified gold by the [[Recording Industry Association of America (RIAA)]] just under seven months later on December 1, 1994, and was certified platinum by the RIAA on January 13, 1995. The Blue Album was certified 2x platinum by the RIAA on August 8, 1995. The album was certified 3x platinum by the RIAA on November 13, 1998.{{Certification Cite Ref|title=Weezer|artist=Weezer|type=album|region=United States}} The album peaked at No. 16 on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]].<ref>https://web.archive.org/web/20130414042527/http://www.billboard.com/charts/1995-02-04/billboard-200</ref> As a single, \"Undone \u2013 The Sweater Song\" peaked at No. 35 on the [[UK Top 40]], and \"Buddy Holly\" and \"Say It Ain't So\" peaked at No. 12 and No. 37 on the UK Top 40 respectively.<ref name=\"everyhit singles\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.everyhit.com/|title=UK Top 40 Singles Chart|accessdate=2007-08-30|publisher=Everyhit.com}}</ref> In the U.S., \"Buddy Holly\" peaked at No. 17 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] Airplay chart.<ref name=\"billboardsinglesweez\">{{Allmusic |class=album |tab=charts-awards/billboard-single |id=r203105 |label=''Weezer (Blue Album)'' \u2013 Weezer > Charts & Awards > Billboard Singles |accessdate=2010-10-27|work=Billboard}}</ref>\n\nA \"deluxe edition\" of the album was released on March 23, 2004, including the original album and a second disc, ''Dusty Gems and Raw Nuggets'', containing B-sides and rarities.<ref name=\"allmusic_deluxe\">{{Allmusic |class=album |id=r683374 |accessdate=September 6, 2006 |label=Weezer ''Weezer (Blue Album)'' [Deluxe] |ref=allmusic_deluxe}}</ref> As of December 2007, the \"deluxe edition\" had sold 86,000 copies.<ref name=\"metalsludge\">{{cite web | url = http://www.metalsludge.tv/phpBB2/viewtopic.php?t=138043&highlight=sales&sid=4acc64c3baa32ccf36c5ac21049a232c | title = Album Sales | publisher = MetalSludge.tv | accessdate = 2007-04-22 }}{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n== Critical reception ==\n{{Album ratings\n| rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev1Score = {{Rating|5|5}}<ref name=\"allmusic\">{{cite web |url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/weezer-blue-album-mw0000329481 |title=Weezer [Blue Album] \u2013 Weezer |publisher=[[AllMusic]] |accessdate=November 16, 2015 |last=Erlewine |first=Stephen Thomas |authorlink=Stephen Thomas Erlewine}}</ref>\n| rev2 = ''[[Blender (magazine)|Blender]]''\n| rev2Score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref>{{cite journal |url=http://www.blender.com/reviews/review_2110.html |title=Weezer: Weezer |journal=[[Blender (magazine)|Blender]] |accessdate=July 6, 2016 |last=Greenwald |first=Andy |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040617064855/http://www.blender.com/reviews/review_2110.html |archivedate=June 17, 2004}}</ref>\n| rev3 = ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]''\n| rev3Score = {{Rating|3.5|4}}<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-4236668.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170815182425/https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-4236668.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=August 15, 2017 |title=Weezer, 'Weezer' (DGC) |work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]] |date=July 3, 1994 |accessdate=October 18, 2016 |last=DeRogatis |first=Jim |authorlink=Jim DeRogatis |url-access=subscription }}</ref>\n| rev4 = ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''\n| rev4Score = B {{small|(1994)}}<ref name=\"EW1994\">{{cite journal |url=http://www.ew.com/article/1994/10/14/album-review-weezer |title=Weezer |journal=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |issue=244 |date=October 14, 1994 |accessdate=October 27, 2011 |last=Flaherty |first=Mike}}</ref><br />A+ {{small|(2014)}}<ref name=EW2014>{{cite journal |url=http://www.ew.com/article/2014/06/18/weezers-debut-turns-20 |title=Weezer's Debut Turns 20 |journal=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |date=May 21, 2014 |accessdate=May 26, 2014 |last=Anderson |first=Kyle}}</ref>\n| rev5 = ''[[NME]]''\n| rev5Score = 7/10<ref>{{cite journal |title=Weezer: Weezer |journal=[[NME]] |date=February 25, 1995 |page=39}}</ref>\n| rev6 = ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]''\n| rev6Score = 10/10<ref>{{cite web |url=http://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/22858-weezer-blue-album/ |title=Weezer: Weezer (Blue Album) |work=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]] |date=February 26, 2017 |accessdate=February 26, 2017 |last=Mapes |first=Jillian}}</ref>\n| rev7 = ''[[Q (magazine)|Q]]''\n| rev7Score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref>{{cite journal |title=Weezer: Weezer |journal=[[Q (magazine)|Q]] |issue=102 |date=March 1995 |page=106}}</ref>\n| rev8 = ''[[Rolling Stone]]''\n| rev8Score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref name=RS2004>{{cite journal |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/albumreviews/weezer-deluxe-edition-20040419 |title=Geek Deluxe |journal=[[Rolling Stone]] |issue=947 |date=April 29, 2004 |accessdate=October 27, 2011 |page=82 |last=Hoard |first=Christian}}</ref>\n| rev9 = ''[[The Rolling Stone Album Guide]]''\n| rev9Score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref>{{cite book |chapter=Weezer |last=Sheffield |first=Rob |authorlink=Rob Sheffield |title=The New Rolling Stone Album Guide |editor1-last=Brackett |editor1-first=Nathan |editor2-last=Hoard |editor2-first=Christian |publisher=[[Simon & Schuster]] |edition=4th |year=2004 |isbn=0-7432-0169-8 |pages=[https://archive.org/details/newrollingstonea00brac/page/865 865\u201366] |title-link=The Rolling Stone Album Guide }}</ref>\n| rev10 = ''[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]''\n| rev10Score = A<ref>{{cite journal |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mOL9JKjjbdcC&pg=PA87 |title=Rhapsody in Blue |journal=[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]] |volume=20 |issue=4 |date=April 2004 |accessdate=November 16, 2015 |last=Pappademas |first=Alex |pages=87\u201388}}</ref>\n}}\n\nThe Blue Album was well received by critics.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.tower.com/details/details.cfm?wapi=105768419|title=Weezer (1994)|accessdate=2007-09-04|publisher=[[Tower Records (music retailer)|Tower Records]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927210559/http://www.tower.com/details/details.cfm?wapi=105768419|archive-date=September 27, 2007|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' praised the album in their year-end review, saying \"Weezer's Rivers Cuomo is great at sketching vignettes (the ''[[Dungeons and Dragons]]'' games and [[Kiss (band)|Kiss]] posters that inspire the hapless daydreamer of 'In the Garage'), and with sweet inspiration like the waltz tempo of 'My Name Is Jonas' and the self-deprecating humor of lines like \"I look just like Buddy Holly / And you're Mary Tyler Moore\", his songs easily ingratiate.\"<ref name=\"RS1994\">{{cite news |newspaper=[[Rolling Stone]] |issue=698/699 |date=December 29, 1994 \u2013 January 12, 1995 |page=169 |last=Evans |first=Paul |title=The Year In Recordings: ''Weezer'' |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/albumreviews/weezer-19980202 | accessdate = 2007-09-04 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071002120219/http://www.rollingstone.com/artists/weezer/albums/album/98380/review/6067707/weezer |archivedate=October 2, 2007}} Posted on February 2, 1998.</ref> [[Robert Christgau]] of ''[[The Village Voice]]'' was less complimentary and awarded the album a \"neither\" rating.<ref>{{cite book |chapter-url=http://www.robertchristgau.com/get_album.php?id=9248 |chapter=Weezer: Weezer |accessdate=May 3, 2012 |last=Christgau |first=Robert |authorlink=Robert Christgau |title=Christgau's Consumer Guide: Albums of the '90s |publisher=[[Macmillan Publishers]] |year=2000 |isbn=0-312-24560-2|title-link=Christgau's Consumer Guide: Albums of the '90s }}</ref> The \"Buddy Holly\" video won four awards at the 1995 ''[[MTV Video Music Awards]]'', including prizes for [[MTV Video Music Award \u2013 Breakthrough Video|Breakthrough Video]] and [[MTV Video Music Award for Best Alternative Video|Best Alternative Video]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rockonthenet.com/archive/1995/mtvvmas.htm|title=1995 MTV Video Music Awards|work=Rock on the Net|accessdate=2007-09-07}}</ref> It was ranked number 299 on ''Rolling Stone''<nowiki/>'s list of [[Rolling Stone's 500 Greatest Albums of All Time|The 500 Greatest Albums of All Time]].\n\n== Legacy ==\nThe Blue Album has become one of the most highly regarded albums of the 1990s, appearing on many \"Best-of\" lists. In 2003, ''Rolling Stone'' ranked the album number 297 on their list of the [[Rolling Stone's 500 Greatest Albums of All Time|500 Greatest Albums of All Time]],<ref name=\"RS1234\">{{cite book |chapter=297 &#124; Weezer (Blue Album) \u2013 Weezer |chapterurl= https://www.rollingstone.com/music/lists/500-greatest-albums-of-all-time-19691231/weezer-blue-album-weezer-19691231 |last1=Levy |first1=Joe |first2= Steven| last2= Van Zandt |title=Rolling Stone's 500 Greatest Albums of All Time |origyear=2005 |edition=3rd |year=2006 |publisher=Turnaround |location=London |isbn=1-932958-61-4 |oclc=70672814 |ref=RS1234|title-link=Rolling Stone's 500 Greatest Albums of All Time }}</ref> and 299 in a 2012 revised list.<ref>{{cite web| url= https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-lists/500-greatest-albums-of-all-time-156826/weezer-weezer-32008/| year=2012| title=500 Greatest Albums of All Time| work= Rolling Stone | accessdate= September 9, 2019}}</ref>  In 2002, the readers of ''Rolling Stone'' ranked the album the 21st greatest of all time,<ref name=\"RS90s\">{{cite web | url = http://www.rocklist.net/rstone.html#Recordings%20of%20the%20%E2%80%9890s | title = 'Rolling Stone Readers 100, 2002 at Rocklist.net | accessdate = 2007-09-04}}</ref> and 299 in a 2012 revised list.{{cn|date=November 2019}} ''[[Blender (magazine)|Blender]]'' named the Blue Album among the \"500 CDs You Must Own\", calling the album \"Absolute geek-rock, out and proud.\"<ref name=\"Blender\">{{cite web|url=http://www.blender.com/guide/67144/500-cds-you-must-own-alternative-rock.html |title=500 CDs You Must Own: Alternative Rock at Blender.com |accessdate=2007-09-04 |url-status=dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090430064926/http://www.blender.com/guide/67144/500-cds-you-must-own-alternative-rock.html |archivedate=April 30, 2009 }}</ref> Non-U.S. publications have acclaimed the album as well: New Zealand's ''The Movement'' placed it at number 39 on a list of \"The 101 Best Albums of the 90s\",<ref>{{cite web | url = http://acclaimedmusic.net/Current/movement.htm | title = The 101 Best Albums of the 90s | publisher = The Movement | accessdate = 2007-09-04 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160303182831/http://acclaimedmusic.net/Current/movement.htm | archive-date = March 3, 2016 | url-status = dead | df = mdy-all }}</ref> and Visions of Germany ranked it number 32 on a list of \"The Most Important Albums of the 90s.\"<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.poplist.de/poplist.php?l=474 | title = The Most Important Albums of the 90s | publisher = Visions| accessdate = 2007-09-04}}</ref> In November 2011, the Blue Album was ranked number three on ''[[Guitar World]]'' magazine's top ten list of guitar albums of 1994, with [[Bad Religion]]'s ''[[Stranger than Fiction (Bad Religion album)|Stranger than Fiction]]'' and [[The Offspring]]'s ''[[Smash (The Offspring album)|Smash]]'' in first and second place respectively.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.guitarworld.com/readers-poll-results-top-10-guitar-albums-1994 |title=Photo Gallery: The Top 10 Guitar Albums of 1994 |author=Grassi, Tony |publisher=[[Guitar World|GuitarWorld.com]] |accessdate=2011-11-08}}</ref> The album also peaked at number 25 on ''Guitar World'''s \"Superunknown: 50 Iconic Albums That Defined 1994\" list.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.guitarworld.com/superunknown-50-iconic-albums-defined-1994 |title=Superunknown: 50 Iconic Albums That Defined 1994 |date=July 14, 2014 |work=[[Guitar World|GuitarWorld.com]] |accessdate=July 14, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20140715053900/http://www.guitarworld.com/superunknown-50-iconic-albums-defined-1994 |archivedate=July 15, 2014 }}</ref>\n\nReviews of the album when its deluxe edition was released have reflected its rise in stature continuing to be positive. In 2004, ''[[PopMatters]]'' gave the album a very positive review, saying \"I'd go so far to declare the 'Blue Album' one of the greatest records of the last 20 years.\"<ref name=\"times\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.popmatters.com/pm/music/reviews/29385/weezer-bluedeluxe/|title=Weezer (Blue Album) [Deluxe Edition]|accessdate=2007-09-04|work=[[Popmatters]]}}</ref> And ''Rolling Stone'' reiterated their original positive review by further describing it as \"big, vibrant pop-rock that would inspire thousands of emo kids.\"<ref name=\"RS2004\" /> [[Blogcritics|Blogcritics Magazine]] gave the album a score of 10/10 and asserted that \"this is one of the most important debut albums of the last ten years.\"<ref>{{cite web | url = http://blogcritics.org/archives/2004/07/01/180332.php | title = Review: Weezer-The Blue Album (Deluxe Edition) | publisher = Blogcritics Magazine | accessdate = 2007-09-04 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080321032555/http://blogcritics.org/archives/2004/07/01/180332.php | archivedate = March 21, 2008 | df = mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn naming ''Weezer'' the 26th best album of the 1990s, ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]'' summed up the album's critical recognition:\n{{quote|An album so substantial the band misguidedly attempted to tap into its resonance through cover graphics a mere two releases later. In 1994, 70s rock had come to mean either a bastardized version of [[Led Zeppelin]] or a bullshit reconstruction of [[punk rock]]. As guitar nerds, Weezer sought influence there but found true inspiration in forgotten bubblegum power-pop like [[Cheap Trick]], [[Raspberries (band)|Raspberries]], [[20/20 (band)|20/20]], and [[The Quick (U.S. band)|The Quick]]. Most impressively, Rivers Cuomo rescued the thrilling guitar solo from finger-tapping metal and disregarding grunge/punk. A decade later air-guitaring to the album feels far less embarrassing than singing along. With the help of [[Spike Jonze]], Weezer kept joy alive in [[arena rock]], making the critical repositioning of Weezer as some emo touchstone even more absentminded. They called themselves Weezer, knowingly, for chrissakes.<ref name=\"Pitchforklist\">{{cite web | last = DiCrescenzo | first = Brent | url = http://www.pitchforkmedia.com/article/feature/36737-staff-list-top-100-albums-of-the-1990s/page_8 | title = Top 100 Albums of the 1990s | publisher = [[Pitchfork Media|Pitchfork]] | accessdate = 2007-09-04 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071023195032/http://www.pitchforkmedia.com/article/feature/36737-staff-list-top-100-albums-of-the-1990s/page_8 | archivedate = October 23, 2007 | df = mdy-all }}</ref>|sign=|source=}}\n\n''[[NME]]'' claimed that the album \"pretty much invented emo's melodic wing\".<ref>{{cite web| last= Lewis| first= Luke| url= http://www.nme.com/reviews/weezer/10951 |title= Album review: Weezer \u2013 'Raditude'| website= [[NME]].com| date= November 2, 2009| access-date= March 6, 2011.</ref> [[AllMusic|AllMusic's]] Stephen Thomas Erlewine gave the album a full 5/5 stars, explaining \"What makes the band so enjoyable is their charming geekiness; instead of singing about despair, they sing about love, which is kind of refreshing in the gloom-drenched world of '90s guitar-pop.\"<ref name=\"allmusic\" />\n\n=== Accolades ===\nSince its release, the Blue Album has featured heavily in various \"must have\" lists compiled by the music media. Some of the more prominent of these lists to feature the Blue Album are shown below; this information is adapted from [[Acclaimed Music]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.acclaimedmusic.net/Current/A930.htm|title=List of Blue Album Accolades|accessdate=2007-02-05|publisher=[[Acclaimed Music]]|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20170905113004/http://www.acclaimedmusic.net/Current/A930.htm|archive-date=September 5, 2017|url-status= dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n{|class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"|Publication\n! scope=\"col\"|Country\n! scope=\"col\"|Accolade\n! scope=\"col\"|Year\n! scope=\"col\"|Rank\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"|''[[Blender (magazine)|Blender]]''\n| USA\n| 500 CDs You Must Own Before You Die<ref name=\"Blender\" />\n| 2003\n| *\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"|Music Underwater\n| USA\n| Top 100 Albums 1990\u20132003<ref>{{cite web | url = http://pub37.bravenet.com/forum/3172289350/show/479624 | title = Top 100 Albums 1990\u20132003 | publisher =Music Underwater | accessdate = 2007-02-05}}</ref>\n| 2004\n| No. 10\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"|[[Stylus Magazine|''Stylus'' Magazine]]\n| USA\n| Top 101\u2013200 Albums of All Time<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.stylusmagazine.com/articles/weekly_article/top-101-200-favourite-albums-ever-the-stylus-magazine-list.htm | title = Top 101\u2013200 Albums of All Time | work=Stylus Magazine | accessdate = 2007-02-05}}</ref>\n| 2004\n| No. 177\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"|''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork Media]]''\n| USA\n| Top 100 Albums of the 1990s<ref name=\"Pitchforklist\" />\n| 2003\n| No. 26\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"|''[[Rolling Stone]]''\n| USA\n| The 500 Greatest Albums of All Time<ref name=\"RS1234\" />\n| 2005\n| No. 299\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"|''Rolling Stone''\n| USA\n| The 100 Best Debut Albums of All Time<ref name=\"RSDebut\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/lists/the-100-greatest-debut-albums-of-all-time-20130322/weezer-19691231 |title=The 100 Best Debut Albums of All Time: 'Weezer' |work=Rolling Stone |accessdate=2013-05-15}}</ref>\n| 2013\n| No. 35\n|}\n\n<small>( * ) designates lists which are unordered.</small>\n\n== Track listing ==\n{{tracklist| all_writing   = [[Rivers Cuomo]], except where noted\n| title1        = [[My Name Is Jonas]]\n| writer1       = Cuomo, [[Patrick Wilson (musician)|Patrick Wilson]], [[Jason Cropper]]\n| length1       = 3:23\n| title2        = No One Else\n| length2       = 3:14\n| title3        = The World Has Turned and Left Me Here\n| writer3       = Cuomo, Wilson\n| length3       = 4:26\n| title4        = [[Buddy Holly (song)|Buddy Holly]]\n| length4       = 2:40\n| title5        = [[Undone \u2013 The Sweater Song]]\n| length5       = 4:55\n| title6        = Surf Wax America\n| writer6       = Cuomo, Wilson\n| length6       = 3:04\n| title7        = [[Say It Ain't So]]\n| length7       = 4:18\n| title8        = In the Garage\n| length8       = 3:56\n| title9        = Holiday\n| length9       = 3:26\n| title10       = [[Only in Dreams (song)|Only in Dreams]]\n| length10      = 7:59\n| total_length  = 41:26\n}}\n\n=== Deluxe edition bonus disc ===\nThe 2004 deluxe edition included a bonus disc, ''Dusty Gems and Raw Nuggets''.\n{{tracklist| title1      = Mykel & Carli\n| length1     = 2:53\n| title2      = Susanne\n| note2       = remix\n| length2     = 2:47\n| title3      = My Evaline\n| length3     = 0:44\n| title4      = Jamie\n| length4     = 4:19\n| title5      = [[My Name Is Jonas]]\n| note5       = live\n| writer5     = Cuomo, Wilson, Cropper\n| length5     = 3:39\n| title6      = Surf Wax America\n| note6       = live\n| writer6     = Cuomo, Wilson\n| length6     = 4:01\n| title7      = Jamie\n| note7       = acoustic live\n| length7     = 4:03\n| title8      = No One Else\n| note8       = acoustic live\n| length8     = 3:23\n| title9      = [[Undone \u2013 The Sweater Song|Undone (The Sweater Song)]]\n| note9       = demo\n| length9     = 5:33\n| title10     = Paperface\n| length10    = 3:01\n| title11     = [[Only in Dreams (song)|Only in Dreams]]\n| note11      = demo\n| length11    = 5:47\n| title12     = Lullaby for Wayne\n| writer12    = Cuomo, Wilson\n| length12    = 3:36\n| title13     = I Swear It's True\n| length13    = 2:57\n| title14     = [[Say It Ain't So]]\n| note14      = original album mix\n| length14    = 4:16\n| total_length = 50:59\n}}\n\nThe tracks on the bonus disc originally appeared on the following releases:<ref name=\"deluxeblue\" />\n* Tracks 1 and 3 from \"[[Undone \u2013 The Sweater Song]]\" single (1994)\n* Track 2 is from the soundtrack to ''[[Mallrats]]''; an earlier mix of the same song was included on the \"Undone\" single\n* Track 4 from ''[[DGC Rarities Vol. 1|DGC Rarities]]'' compilation (1994)\n* Tracks 5 and 6 from \"[[Buddy Holly (song)|Buddy Holly]]\" single (1994)\n* Tracks 7 and 8 from \"[[Say It Ain't So]]\" single (1995)\n* Tracks 9\u201311 previously unreleased, and part of ''[[The Kitchen Tapes (Weezer)|Kitchen Tape]]'' demo (1992)\n* Tracks 12 and 13 previously unreleased, pre-production recordings done with Ric Ocasek just prior to ''Weezer'''s recording (1993)\n* Track 14 is the version featured on the original release of the album. The mix was changed for the single and was later added to newer versions of the album. The single mix is the version included on Disc 1 of this Deluxe Edition.\n\n== Personnel ==\n'''Weezer'''\n\n* [[Rivers Cuomo]] \u2013 lead vocals, lead and rhythm guitar, keyboards, harmonica\n* [[Brian Bell]] \u2013 rhythm guitar (credited), backing vocals\n* [[Matt Sharp]] \u2013 bass, backing vocals\n* [[Patrick Wilson (musician)|Patrick Wilson]] \u2013 drums\n\n'''Additional musicians'''\n\n* Mykel Allan \u2013 spoken intermission on \"Undone \u2013 The Sweater Song\"\n* Karl Koch \u2013 dialogue, [[piano]] outro on \"Undone \u2013 The Sweater Song\"\n* [[Jason Cropper]] \u2013 guitar, backing vocals on \"Jamie\"\n\n'''Production'''\n\n* [[Ric Ocasek]] \u2013 producer\n* Chris Shaw \u2013 [[Audio engineering|engineer]]\n* Hal Belknap \u2013 assistant engineer\n* Peter Gowland, Peter Orth \u2014 photographer\n* Karl Koch \u2014 designer\n* Todd Sullivan \u2014 [[Artists and repertoire|A&R]]\n* George Marino \u2014 mastering\n\n== Charts ==\n\n=== Album ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Chart (1995\u201396)\n!Peak<br />position\n|-\n{{albumchart|Austria|47|artist=Weezer|album=Weezer (The Green Album)|accessdate=20 May 2016}}\n|-\n{{albumchart|Flanders|19|artist=Weezer|album=Weezer (The Blue Album)|accessdate=19 May 2016}}\n|-\n{{albumchart|Wallonia|40|artist=Weezer|album=Weezer (The Blue Album)|accessdate=19 May 2016}}\n|-\n{{albumchart|Canada|10|chartid=8012|artist=Weezer|album=Weezer (The Blue Album)|accessdate=19 May 2016}}\n|-\n{{albumchart|Netherlands|48|artist=Weezer|album=Weezer (The Blue Album)|accessdate=19 May 2016}}\n|-\n{{albumchart|Finland|22|artist=Weezer|album=Weezer (The Blue Album)|accessdate=19 May 2016|refname=finland}}\n|-\n{{albumchart|Germany3|61|artist=Weezer|album=Weezer (The Blue Album)|accessdate=19 May 2016}}\n|-\n{{albumchart|New Zealand|6|artist=Weezer|album=Weezer (The Blue Album)|accessdate=19 May 2016|refname=nzalbum}}\n|-\n{{albumchart|Norway|35|artist=Weezer|album=Weezer (The Blue Album)|accessdate=19 May 2016}}\n|-\n{{albumchart|UK|23|artist=Weezer|album=Weezer (The Blue Album)|date=1995-05-14|accessdate=19 May 2016|refname=ukcharts}}\n|-\n{{albumchart|Billboard200|16|M|title=Billboard 200 : Feb 04, 1995| url= https://web.archive.org/web/20130414042527/http://www.billboard.com/charts/1995-02-04/billboard-200| work= Billboard |refname= billboard| artist=Weezer|album=Weezer}}\n|}\n\n=== Singles ===\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n!rowspan=\"2\"| Year\n!rowspan=\"2\"| Song\n!colspan=\"6\"| Peak positions\n|-style=\"font-size:85%;line-height:1.3;vertical-align:top\"\n! style=\"width:4em\" | [[Modern Rock Tracks|US Modern Rock]]<br /><ref name=\"billboardsinglesweez\" />\n! style=\"width:4em\" | [[Billboard Hot 100|US<br />Bill-<br />board<br />Hot 100]]<br /><ref name=\"billboardsinglesweez\" />\n! style=\"width:4em\" | [[Hot 100 Airplay|US<br />Hot 100<br />Airplay]]<br /><ref name=\"billboardsinglesweez\" />\n! style=\"width:4em\" | [[UK Singles Chart|UK<br />Top 40]]<br /><ref name=\"ukcharts\" />\n! style=\"width:4em\" | Sweden<br /><ref name=\"swedenalbum\">{{Cite web|url=http://hitparad.se/showitem.asp?interpret=Weezer&titel=Weezer&cat=a|title=Swedish album chart archives|accessdate=2007-08-30|publisher=hitparad.se}}</ref>\n! style=\"width:4em\" | Nether-<br />lands<br /><ref name=\"NetherlandsCharts\">{{Cite web|url=http://dutchcharts.nl/showitem.asp?interpret=Weezer&titel=Weezer&cat=a|title=Netherland Charts|accessdate=2007-08-30|publisher=dutchcharts.com}}</ref>\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"| 1994\n| \"[[Undone \u2013 The Sweater Song]]\"\n|align=\"center\"| 6\n|align=\"center\"| 57\n|align=\"center\"| 74\n|align=\"center\"| 35\n|align=\"center\"| \u2013\n|align=\"center\"| \u2013\n|-\n| \"[[Buddy Holly (song)|Buddy Holly]]\"\n|align=\"center\"| 2\n|align=\"center\"| \u2013\n|align=\"center\"| 18\n|align=\"center\"| 12\n|align=\"center\"| 14\n|align=\"center\"| 27\n|-\n| 1995\n| \"[[Say It Ain't So]]\"\n|align=\"center\"| 7\n|align=\"center\"| \u2013\n|align=\"center\"| 51\n|align=\"center\"| 37\n|align=\"center\"| \u2013\n|align=\"center\"| \u2013\n|}\n\n== References ==\n'''Notes'''\n{{reflist}}\n\n'''Bibliography'''\n* {{cite book|last=Luerssen|first=John D.|title=Rivers' Edge: The Weezer Story|publisher=ECW Press|date=2004|isbn=1-55022-619-3|ref=harv}}\n\n== External links ==\n<!-- This is a licensed stream for the album, which is allowed under Wikipedia polices -->\n* [https://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PLC2qC-e5Yikf9drCiyhM0Vrur8INw7Ngd ''Weezer''] at [[YouTube]] (streamed copy where licensed)\n* {{MusicBrainz release|mbid=1e477f68-c407-4eae-ad01-518528cedc2c|name=Weezer (The Blue Album)}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20111005231838/http://weezer-lyrics.com/weezer-the-blue-album/ Lyrics for Weezer \u2013 The Blue Album]\n\n{{Weezer}}\n{{good article}}\n\n[[Category:Weezer albums]]\n[[Category:1994 debut albums]]\n[[Category:Geffen Records albums]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Ric Ocasek]]\n[[Category:Albums recorded at Electric Lady Studios]]\n", "text_old": "{{Redirect|The World Has Turned and Left Me Here|the ''Vampire Diaries'' episode|The World Has Turned and Left Me Here (The Vampire Diaries)}}\n{{Redirect|No One Else|the showtune|Natasha, Pierre & the Great Comet of 1812}}\n{{short description|1994 album by Weezer}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2012}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Weezer\n| type       = studio\n| artist     = [[Weezer]]\n| cover      = Weezer - Blue Album.png\n| alt        =\n| released   = May 10, 1994\n| recorded   = August\u2013September 1993\n| studio     = [[Electric Lady Studios]], [[New York City]]\n| genre      = {{flatlist|\n* [[Alternative rock]]\n* [[power pop]]\n* [[pop punk]]\n* [[pop rock]]\n}}<!-- Genres sourced in article -->\n| length     = 41:26\n| label      = [[DGC Records|DGC]]\n| producer   = [[Ric Ocasek]]\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title = [[Pinkerton (album)|Pinkerton]]\n| next_year  = 1996\n| misc       = {{Singles\n | name        = Weezer\n | type        = studio\n | single1     = [[Undone \u2013 The Sweater Song]]\n | single1date = June 24, 1994\n | single2     = [[Buddy Holly (song)|Buddy Holly]]\n | single2date = September 7, 1994\n | single3     = [[Say It Ain't So]]\n | single3date = July 13, 1995\n}}\n}}\n\n'''''Weezer''''' (commonly known as the '''Blue Album''') is the eponymous debut [[studio album]] by American [[Rock music|rock]] band [[Weezer]], released on May 10, 1994 by [[DGC Records]]. The album came two years after the band's founding, after they initially struggled as an alternative to [[grunge|grunge music]], which was prevalent in [[Los Angeles]] during the early 1990s. It was almost entirely arranged and composed by frontman [[Rivers Cuomo]], who also anticipated to lead the band in self-producing the album. However, at the behest of DGC, the band was required to include a producer, and collectively opted for [[The Cars|Cars]] frontman [[Ric Ocasek]]. Most of the recording was conducted at [[Electric Lady Studios]] in [[New York City]] between August and September 1993, a period that coincided with founding guitarist [[Jason Cropper]] being fired and replaced by [[Brian Bell]].\n\nUnder Ocasek's direction, the band opted for a brighter sound, while bassist [[Matt Sharp]] collaborated with Cuomo to ensure that the album contained an overriding sonic concept of treating the guitars and bass as isolated ten-string instruments, thus maximizing its potential when united.<ref name=\"Pitchforklist\">{{cite web | last = DiCrescenzo | first = Brent | url = http://www.pitchforkmedia.com/article/feature/36737-staff-list-top-100-albums-of-the-1990s/page_8 | title = Top 100 Albums of the 1990s | publisher = [[Pitchfork Media|Pitchfork]] | accessdate = 2007-09-04 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071023195032/http://www.pitchforkmedia.com/article/feature/36737-staff-list-top-100-albums-of-the-1990s/page_8 | archivedate = October 23, 2007 | df = mdy-all }}</ref> Lyrically, ''Weezer'' focuses on outsiderdom and [[social awkwardness]], while also touching on melancholic themes of love, romance, and familial issues.<ref>https://www.udiscovermusic.com/stories/weezer-blue-album-power-pop/</ref> \n\n''Weezer'' was supported by the singles \"[[Undone \u2013 The Sweater Song]]\", \"[[Buddy Holly (song)|Buddy Holly]]\", and \"[[Say It Ain't So]]\", which, alongside their respective [[music video]]s, brought Weezer mainstream success. The album itself peaked at number sixteen on the [[Billboard 200|US ''Billboard'' 200]], and was certified [[RIAA certification|triple platinum]] by 1995. It is also the band's best-selling album, having sold at least 3.3 million copies in the U.S. and over fifteen million copies worldwide by 2009.<ref>{{cite web |first=Michael D.|last=Ayers| url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/267638/weezer-filled-with-raditude-this-fall | title=Weezer Filled With 'Raditude' This Fall | work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] | publisher=[[Eldridge Industries]] |location=Los Angeles, California| date=August 21, 2009 | accessdate=October 1, 2012}}</ref>\n\n== Background ==\nWeezer was formed on February 14, 1992, in Los Angeles by singer and guitarist [[Rivers Cuomo]], drummer [[Patrick Wilson (musician)|Patrick Wilson]], bassist [[Matt Sharp]], and guitarist [[Jason Cropper]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.upsetmagazine.com/features/weezer-interview-kings-of-the-world-white-album/|title=Weezer: Kings of the world {{!}} Interview {{!}} Upset|date=2016-05-06|language=en-US|access-date=2016-07-31}}</ref> Although they performed future hits including \"[[The Sweater Song]]\" and \"[[Say It Ain't So]]\", Cuomo said they struggled to engage audiences, who wanted to see [[grunge]] bands instead.<ref>{{harvnb|Luerssen|2004|p=67}}</ref> \n\nIn an effort to create buzz around LA, Weezer recorded a demo, ''[[The Kitchen Tape]]''.<ref>{{harvnb|Luerssen|2004|p=69}}</ref> This attracted attention from major-label A&R reps looking for alternative rock bands to perform on the same bill as [[That Dog]].<ref>{{harvnb|Luerssen|2004|p=76}}</ref> Weezer were signed to [[DGC Records]] on June 26, 1993, by Todd Sullivan, an A&R rep from [[Geffen Records]].<ref>{{harvnb|Luerssen|2004|p=82}}</ref>\n\n== Recording ==\nWhile preparing for the studio sessions, Weezer focused on their vocal interplay by practicing [[barbershop quartet]]-style songs, which helped Cuomo and Sharp feel more comfortable collaborating during rehearsals. Sharp, who had never sung before joining Weezer, developed his [[falsetto]]: \"I had to sing an octave higher than Rivers. After a lot of practice, I started to get it down.\"<ref>{{harvnb|Luerssen|2004|p=85}}</ref>\n\nWeezer rehearsed 15 songs in New York in preparation for the Electric Lady Studios recording sessions. Four songs from this rehearsal would not be attempted for the album: \"Lullaby for Wayne\", \"I Swear It's True\", \"Getting Up and Leaving\", and a reprise version of \"In the Garage\". The other song, an ode to two women who ran the Weezer fanclub called \"Mykel & Carli\", was attempted during the Electric Lady sessions, but was also abandoned (this recording was later released as a digital bonus track on the 2010 compilation ''[[Death to False Metal]]''). A later recording of \"Mykel & Carli\" was featured as a B-side on the \"[[Undone \u2013 The Sweater Song]]\" single.<ref>{{harvnb|Luerssen|2004|pp=88\u201391}}</ref>\n\nThe band considered self-producing, but were pressured by [[Geffen Records|Geffen]] to choose a producer. They decided on [[Ric Ocasek]], who had played with the [[The Cars|Cars]].<ref>{{harvnb|Luerssen|2004|p=87}}</ref> Ocasek convinced the band to change their [[Pick up (music technology)|guitar pickups]] from the neck to the bridge, resulting in a brighter sound.<ref>{{harvnb|Luerssen|2004|p=87}}</ref> Sharp and Cuomo imposed several rules on recording, banning [[Reverberation|reverb]] and insisting on all [[Downpicking|downstrokes]] on guitar.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-features/weezer-blue-album-25th-anniversary-877089/|title=The Strange Birth and Near Death of Weezer|last=Hiatt|first=Brian|last2=Hiatt|first2=Brian|date=2019-08-28|website=Rolling Stone|language=en-US|access-date=2019-08-30}}</ref> According to engineer Chris Shaw, the \"overriding concept\" was to treat the guitars and bass as a single, 10-string instrument, playing in unison. Weezer insisted that the guitars were mixed as loudly as those in the [[Radiohead]] song \"[[Creep (Radiohead song)|Creep]]\", burying some vocals.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nDuring the recording, Cropper learned that his girlfriend was pregnant and began acting erratically. Weezer collaborator Karl Koch said: \"He wasn't handling it well ... he always said he was fine, and then 20 minutes later he'd be up on the roof of Electric Lady screaming or something.\"<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=http://www.phawker.com/2014/10/02/excerpt-the-complete-oral-history-of-weezer/|title=EXCERPT: The Complete Oral History of Weezer|last=Valania|first=Jonathan|date=2 October 2014|work=Magnet|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180701140036/http://www.phawker.com/2014/10/02/excerpt-the-complete-oral-history-of-weezer/|archive-date=1 July 2018|url-status=dead|accessdate=22 May 2019}}</ref> According to Cropper, Cuomo told him he could not allow him to jeopardize the band's work and asked him to leave. In 2014, Cropper said Cuomo had made the right decision.<ref name=\":0\" /> Cropper was replaced by [[Brian Bell]].<ref>{{harvnb|Luerssen|2004|88\u201391}}</ref> While Bell's vocals appear on some tracks,<ref>{{harvnb|Luerssen|2004|p=98}}</ref> Cuomo re-recorded all of Cropper's guitar parts.<ref>{{harvnb|Luerssen|2004|p=99}}</ref> Ocasek recalled: \"After [the album] was completely recorded, Rivers came in and said, 'I\u2019m firing the guitar player, and I\u2019m going to do all his guitar parts over.' I said, 'You can\u2019t do that!' But he did. In one take.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/rivers-cuomo-is-trying-to-be-all-right-167180/|title=Rivers Cuomo Is Trying to Be All Right|last=Vozick-Levinson|first=Simon|last2=Vozick-Levinson|first2=Simon|date=2014-09-23|website=Rolling Stone|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-22}}</ref> Bell is still credited for playing guitar in the liner notes. Cropper received a credit on \"[[My Name Is Jonas]]\" for writing the intro.<ref name=\"Luerssen 2004 61\">{{harvnb|Luerssen|2004|p=61}}</ref>\n\n== Artwork ==\nThe album artwork, photographed by American glamour photographer [[Peter Gowland]],<ref>{{cite web | url = http://uproxx.com/smokingsection/weezer-the-blue-album-cover-story-interview/ | title=\"Undone\": The Story Behind Weezer's Debut Album Cover| publisher = Uproxx| accessdate = 2016-02-26}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.weezerpedia.com/wiki/index.php?title=Karl%27s_Corner_-_01/22/2002| title = Karl's Corner \u2013 01/22/2002| publisher = Weezer.com| accessdate = 2016-02-26| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160312065114/http://www.weezerpedia.com/wiki/index.php?title=Karl%27s_Corner_-_01%2F22%2F2002| archive-date = March 12, 2016| url-status = dead| df = mdy-all}}</ref> features Wilson, Cuomo, Sharp, and Bell standing in front of a plain, blue background.<ref name=\"booklet\">''Weezer: Blue Album'' booklet and [[liner notes]]</ref> [[Adobe Photoshop]] was used to [[Photo manipulation|digitally alter]] the cover. Cuomo stated that, while the band liked the photo, Sharp was not happy with the way his head looked. The Geffen Art Director used Photoshop to swap out the head with one from another shot.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://students-adobe.com/NA#judgeHome3|title=Adobe Imagination Challenge \"Meet the Judges\"|publisher=Adobe|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110923153444/http://students-adobe.com/na#judgeHome3|archive-date=September 23, 2011|url-status=dead|accessdate=2011-08-11|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The image was used prominently in the advertising of the album.<ref name=\"Luerssen 2004 109\">{{harvnb|Luerssen|2004|p=109}}</ref> The cover received many comparisons to [[the Feelies]]' album ''[[Crazy Rhythms]]''.<ref name=\"Luerssen 2004 109\" />\n\nOn some vinyl pressings of the album, the cover does not crop off their feet. On the ''Deluxe Edition'' case the feet are presented on the back cover, and the band sold an official T-shirt with a shot of the band's feet after the deluxe edition release.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.weezer.com/info/tunes/index.html |title=Blue Album era releases (1982\u20131995) |accessdate=2007-08-31 |work=Weezer.com |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100813233431/http://www.weezer.com/info/tunes/index.html |archivedate=August 13, 2010 }}</ref>\n\nInside the album booklet, Cuomo pays tribute to his past [[Heavy metal music|metal]] influences with a photo taken in the group's garage on Amherst (this same garage would be featured in the \"Say It Ain't So\" music video). A poster of [[Judas Priest]]'s album ''[[British Steel (album)|British Steel]]'' is featured on the left side of the photo, while on the right a [[Quiet Riot]] concert poster is displayed. The ''Deluxe Edition'' features additional photographs of the band and hand-written lyrics for each song.<ref name=\"deluxeblue\">''Weezer: Blue Album (Deluxe Edition)'' booklet and [[liner notes]].</ref>\n\n== Promotion ==\nThe first single \"[[Undone \u2013 The Sweater Song]]\" was described by Cuomo as \"the feeling you get when the train stops and the little guy comes knockin' on your door. It was supposed to be a sad song, but everyone thinks it's hilarious.\"<ref name=\"Luerssen 2004 110\u2013111\">{{harvnb|Luerssen|2004|pp=110\u2013111}}</ref> The video marks one of the early directorial efforts of [[Spike Jonze]], whose pitch was simply \"A blue stage, a steadicam, a pack of wild dogs.\"<ref>{{harvnb|Luerssen|2004|p=120}}</ref> The video became an instant hit on MTV.<ref>{{harvnb|Luerssen|2004|p=121}}</ref> The final single, \"[[Say It Ain't So]]\", was inspired by Cuomo believing his parents split up when he was four because he thought his father was an [[alcoholic]].<ref name=\"Luerssen 2004 110\u2013111\" /> The music video, which was directed by [[Sophie Muller]], was less successful than the previous Spike Jonze-directed video. It featured the band performing in the garage of their former house, and the bandmates playing [[footbag|hacky sack]] in the backyard.<ref>{{harvnb|Luerssen|2004|pp=146\u2013147}}</ref>\n\n== Release ==\nThe Blue Album was released on May 10, 1994.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.altpress.com/features/entry/20_facts_you_may_not_know_about_weezers_blue_album|title=20 Facts You May Not Know About Weezer's Blue Album|last1=Heisel|first1=Scott|date=May 9, 2014|website=Alternative Press|publisher=Alternative Press|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150312051202/http://www.altpress.com/features/entry/20_facts_you_may_not_know_about_weezers_blue_album|archivedate=March 12, 2015|accessdate=February 10, 2016}}</ref> It was certified gold by the [[Recording Industry Association of America (RIAA)]] just under seven months later on December 1, 1994, and was certified platinum by the RIAA on January 13, 1995. The Blue Album was certified 2x platinum by the RIAA on August 8, 1995. The album was certified 3x platinum by the RIAA on November 13, 1998.{{Certification Cite Ref|title=Weezer|artist=Weezer|type=album|region=United States}} The album peaked at No. 16 on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]].<ref>https://web.archive.org/web/20130414042527/http://www.billboard.com/charts/1995-02-04/billboard-200</ref> As a single, \"Undone \u2013 The Sweater Song\" peaked at No. 35 on the [[UK Top 40]], and \"Buddy Holly\" and \"Say It Ain't So\" peaked at No. 12 and No. 37 on the UK Top 40 respectively.<ref name=\"everyhit singles\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.everyhit.com/|title=UK Top 40 Singles Chart|accessdate=2007-08-30|publisher=Everyhit.com}}</ref> In the U.S., \"Buddy Holly\" peaked at No. 17 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] Airplay chart.<ref name=\"billboardsinglesweez\">{{Allmusic |class=album |tab=charts-awards/billboard-single |id=r203105 |label=''Weezer (Blue Album)'' \u2013 Weezer > Charts & Awards > Billboard Singles |accessdate=2010-10-27|work=Billboard}}</ref>\n\nA \"deluxe edition\" of the album was released on March 23, 2004, including the original album and a second disc, ''Dusty Gems and Raw Nuggets'', containing B-sides and rarities.<ref name=\"allmusic_deluxe\">{{Allmusic |class=album |id=r683374 |accessdate=September 6, 2006 |label=Weezer ''Weezer (Blue Album)'' [Deluxe] |ref=allmusic_deluxe}}</ref> As of December 2007, the \"deluxe edition\" had sold 86,000 copies.<ref name=\"metalsludge\">{{cite web | url = http://www.metalsludge.tv/phpBB2/viewtopic.php?t=138043&highlight=sales&sid=4acc64c3baa32ccf36c5ac21049a232c | title = Album Sales | publisher = MetalSludge.tv | accessdate = 2007-04-22 }}{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n== Critical reception ==\n{{Album ratings\n| rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev1Score = {{Rating|5|5}}<ref name=\"allmusic\">{{cite web |url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/weezer-blue-album-mw0000329481 |title=Weezer [Blue Album] \u2013 Weezer |publisher=[[AllMusic]] |accessdate=November 16, 2015 |last=Erlewine |first=Stephen Thomas |authorlink=Stephen Thomas Erlewine}}</ref>\n| rev2 = ''[[Blender (magazine)|Blender]]''\n| rev2Score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref>{{cite journal |url=http://www.blender.com/reviews/review_2110.html |title=Weezer: Weezer |journal=[[Blender (magazine)|Blender]] |accessdate=July 6, 2016 |last=Greenwald |first=Andy |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040617064855/http://www.blender.com/reviews/review_2110.html |archivedate=June 17, 2004}}</ref>\n| rev3 = ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]''\n| rev3Score = {{Rating|3.5|4}}<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-4236668.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170815182425/https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-4236668.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=August 15, 2017 |title=Weezer, 'Weezer' (DGC) |work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]] |date=July 3, 1994 |accessdate=October 18, 2016 |last=DeRogatis |first=Jim |authorlink=Jim DeRogatis |url-access=subscription }}</ref>\n| rev4 = ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''\n| rev4Score = B {{small|(1994)}}<ref name=\"EW1994\">{{cite journal |url=http://www.ew.com/article/1994/10/14/album-review-weezer |title=Weezer |journal=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |issue=244 |date=October 14, 1994 |accessdate=October 27, 2011 |last=Flaherty |first=Mike}}</ref><br />A+ {{small|(2014)}}<ref name=EW2014>{{cite journal |url=http://www.ew.com/article/2014/06/18/weezers-debut-turns-20 |title=Weezer's Debut Turns 20 |journal=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |date=May 21, 2014 |accessdate=May 26, 2014 |last=Anderson |first=Kyle}}</ref>\n| rev5 = ''[[NME]]''\n| rev5Score = 7/10<ref>{{cite journal |title=Weezer: Weezer |journal=[[NME]] |date=February 25, 1995 |page=39}}</ref>\n| rev6 = ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]''\n| rev6Score = 10/10<ref>{{cite web |url=http://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/22858-weezer-blue-album/ |title=Weezer: Weezer (Blue Album) |work=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]] |date=February 26, 2017 |accessdate=February 26, 2017 |last=Mapes |first=Jillian}}</ref>\n| rev7 = ''[[Q (magazine)|Q]]''\n| rev7Score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref>{{cite journal |title=Weezer: Weezer |journal=[[Q (magazine)|Q]] |issue=102 |date=March 1995 |page=106}}</ref>\n| rev8 = ''[[Rolling Stone]]''\n| rev8Score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref name=RS2004>{{cite journal |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/albumreviews/weezer-deluxe-edition-20040419 |title=Geek Deluxe |journal=[[Rolling Stone]] |issue=947 |date=April 29, 2004 |accessdate=October 27, 2011 |page=82 |last=Hoard |first=Christian}}</ref>\n| rev9 = ''[[The Rolling Stone Album Guide]]''\n| rev9Score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref>{{cite book |chapter=Weezer |last=Sheffield |first=Rob |authorlink=Rob Sheffield |title=The New Rolling Stone Album Guide |editor1-last=Brackett |editor1-first=Nathan |editor2-last=Hoard |editor2-first=Christian |publisher=[[Simon & Schuster]] |edition=4th |year=2004 |isbn=0-7432-0169-8 |pages=[https://archive.org/details/newrollingstonea00brac/page/865 865\u201366] |title-link=The Rolling Stone Album Guide }}</ref>\n| rev10 = ''[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]''\n| rev10Score = A<ref>{{cite journal |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mOL9JKjjbdcC&pg=PA87 |title=Rhapsody in Blue |journal=[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]] |volume=20 |issue=4 |date=April 2004 |accessdate=November 16, 2015 |last=Pappademas |first=Alex |pages=87\u201388}}</ref>\n}}\n\nThe Blue Album was well received by critics.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.tower.com/details/details.cfm?wapi=105768419|title=Weezer (1994)|accessdate=2007-09-04|publisher=[[Tower Records (music retailer)|Tower Records]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927210559/http://www.tower.com/details/details.cfm?wapi=105768419|archive-date=September 27, 2007|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' praised the album in their year-end review, saying \"Weezer's Rivers Cuomo is great at sketching vignettes (the ''[[Dungeons and Dragons]]'' games and [[Kiss (band)|Kiss]] posters that inspire the hapless daydreamer of 'In the Garage'), and with sweet inspiration like the waltz tempo of 'My Name Is Jonas' and the self-deprecating humor of lines like \"I look just like Buddy Holly / And you're Mary Tyler Moore\", his songs easily ingratiate.\"<ref name=\"RS1994\">{{cite news |newspaper=[[Rolling Stone]] |issue=698/699 |date=December 29, 1994 \u2013 January 12, 1995 |page=169 |last=Evans |first=Paul |title=The Year In Recordings: ''Weezer'' |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/albumreviews/weezer-19980202 | accessdate = 2007-09-04 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071002120219/http://www.rollingstone.com/artists/weezer/albums/album/98380/review/6067707/weezer |archivedate=October 2, 2007}} Posted on February 2, 1998.</ref> [[Robert Christgau]] of ''[[The Village Voice]]'' was less complimentary and awarded the album a \"neither\" rating.<ref>{{cite book |chapter-url=http://www.robertchristgau.com/get_album.php?id=9248 |chapter=Weezer: Weezer |accessdate=May 3, 2012 |last=Christgau |first=Robert |authorlink=Robert Christgau |title=Christgau's Consumer Guide: Albums of the '90s |publisher=[[Macmillan Publishers]] |year=2000 |isbn=0-312-24560-2|title-link=Christgau's Consumer Guide: Albums of the '90s }}</ref> The \"Buddy Holly\" video won four awards at the 1995 ''[[MTV Video Music Awards]]'', including prizes for [[MTV Video Music Award \u2013 Breakthrough Video|Breakthrough Video]] and [[MTV Video Music Award for Best Alternative Video|Best Alternative Video]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rockonthenet.com/archive/1995/mtvvmas.htm|title=1995 MTV Video Music Awards|work=Rock on the Net|accessdate=2007-09-07}}</ref> It was ranked number 299 on ''Rolling Stone''<nowiki/>'s list of [[Rolling Stone's 500 Greatest Albums of All Time|The 500 Greatest Albums of All Time]].\n\n== Legacy ==\nThe Blue Album has become one of the most highly regarded albums of the 1990s, appearing on many \"Best-of\" lists. In 2003, ''Rolling Stone'' ranked the album number 297 on their list of the [[Rolling Stone's 500 Greatest Albums of All Time|500 Greatest Albums of All Time]],<ref name=\"RS1234\">{{cite book |chapter=297 &#124; Weezer (Blue Album) \u2013 Weezer |chapterurl= https://www.rollingstone.com/music/lists/500-greatest-albums-of-all-time-19691231/weezer-blue-album-weezer-19691231 |last1=Levy |first1=Joe |first2= Steven| last2= Van Zandt |title=Rolling Stone's 500 Greatest Albums of All Time |origyear=2005 |edition=3rd |year=2006 |publisher=Turnaround |location=London |isbn=1-932958-61-4 |oclc=70672814 |ref=RS1234|title-link=Rolling Stone's 500 Greatest Albums of All Time }}</ref> and 299 in a 2012 revised list.<ref>{{cite web| url= https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-lists/500-greatest-albums-of-all-time-156826/weezer-weezer-32008/| year=2012| title=500 Greatest Albums of All Time| work= Rolling Stone | accessdate= September 9, 2019}}</ref>  In 2002, the readers of ''Rolling Stone'' ranked the album the 21st greatest of all time,<ref name=\"RS90s\">{{cite web | url = http://www.rocklist.net/rstone.html#Recordings%20of%20the%20%E2%80%9890s | title = 'Rolling Stone Readers 100, 2002 at Rocklist.net | accessdate = 2007-09-04}}</ref> and 299 in a 2012 revised list.{{cn|date=November 2019}} ''[[Blender (magazine)|Blender]]'' named the Blue Album among the \"500 CDs You Must Own\", calling the album \"Absolute geek-rock, out and proud.\"<ref name=\"Blender\">{{cite web|url=http://www.blender.com/guide/67144/500-cds-you-must-own-alternative-rock.html |title=500 CDs You Must Own: Alternative Rock at Blender.com |accessdate=2007-09-04 |url-status=dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090430064926/http://www.blender.com/guide/67144/500-cds-you-must-own-alternative-rock.html |archivedate=April 30, 2009 }}</ref> Non-U.S. publications have acclaimed the album as well: New Zealand's ''The Movement'' placed it at number 39 on a list of \"The 101 Best Albums of the 90s\",<ref>{{cite web | url = http://acclaimedmusic.net/Current/movement.htm | title = The 101 Best Albums of the 90s | publisher = The Movement | accessdate = 2007-09-04 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160303182831/http://acclaimedmusic.net/Current/movement.htm | archive-date = March 3, 2016 | url-status = dead | df = mdy-all }}</ref> and Visions of Germany ranked it number 32 on a list of \"The Most Important Albums of the 90s.\"<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.poplist.de/poplist.php?l=474 | title = The Most Important Albums of the 90s | publisher = Visions| accessdate = 2007-09-04}}</ref> In November 2011, the Blue Album was ranked number three on ''[[Guitar World]]'' magazine's top ten list of guitar albums of 1994, with [[Bad Religion]]'s ''[[Stranger than Fiction (Bad Religion album)|Stranger than Fiction]]'' and [[The Offspring]]'s ''[[Smash (The Offspring album)|Smash]]'' in first and second place respectively.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.guitarworld.com/readers-poll-results-top-10-guitar-albums-1994 |title=Photo Gallery: The Top 10 Guitar Albums of 1994 |author=Grassi, Tony |publisher=[[Guitar World|GuitarWorld.com]] |accessdate=2011-11-08}}</ref> The album also peaked at number 25 on ''Guitar World'''s \"Superunknown: 50 Iconic Albums That Defined 1994\" list.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.guitarworld.com/superunknown-50-iconic-albums-defined-1994 |title=Superunknown: 50 Iconic Albums That Defined 1994 |date=July 14, 2014 |work=[[Guitar World|GuitarWorld.com]] |accessdate=July 14, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20140715053900/http://www.guitarworld.com/superunknown-50-iconic-albums-defined-1994 |archivedate=July 15, 2014 }}</ref>\n\nReviews of the album when its deluxe edition was released have reflected its rise in stature continuing to be positive. In 2004, ''[[PopMatters]]'' gave the album a very positive review, saying \"I'd go so far to declare the 'Blue Album' one of the greatest records of the last 20 years.\"<ref name=\"times\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.popmatters.com/pm/music/reviews/29385/weezer-bluedeluxe/|title=Weezer (Blue Album) [Deluxe Edition]|accessdate=2007-09-04|work=[[Popmatters]]}}</ref> And ''Rolling Stone'' reiterated their original positive review by further describing it as \"big, vibrant pop-rock that would inspire thousands of emo kids.\"<ref name=\"RS2004\" /> [[Blogcritics|Blogcritics Magazine]] gave the album a score of 10/10 and asserted that \"this is one of the most important debut albums of the last ten years.\"<ref>{{cite web | url = http://blogcritics.org/archives/2004/07/01/180332.php | title = Review: Weezer-The Blue Album (Deluxe Edition) | publisher = Blogcritics Magazine | accessdate = 2007-09-04 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080321032555/http://blogcritics.org/archives/2004/07/01/180332.php | archivedate = March 21, 2008 | df = mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn naming ''Weezer'' the 26th best album of the 1990s, ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]'' summed up the album's critical recognition:\n{{quote|An album so substantial the band misguidedly attempted to tap into its resonance through cover graphics a mere two releases later. In 1994, 70s rock had come to mean either a bastardized version of [[Led Zeppelin]] or a bullshit reconstruction of [[punk rock]]. As guitar nerds, Weezer sought influence there but found true inspiration in forgotten bubblegum power-pop like [[Cheap Trick]], [[Raspberries (band)|Raspberries]], [[20/20 (band)|20/20]], and [[The Quick (U.S. band)|The Quick]]. Most impressively, Rivers Cuomo rescued the thrilling guitar solo from finger-tapping metal and disregarding grunge/punk. A decade later air-guitaring to the album feels far less embarrassing than singing along. With the help of [[Spike Jonze]], Weezer kept joy alive in [[arena rock]], making the critical repositioning of Weezer as some emo touchstone even more absentminded. They called themselves Weezer, knowingly, for chrissakes.<ref name=\"Pitchforklist\">{{cite web | last = DiCrescenzo | first = Brent | url = http://www.pitchforkmedia.com/article/feature/36737-staff-list-top-100-albums-of-the-1990s/page_8 | title = Top 100 Albums of the 1990s | publisher = [[Pitchfork Media|Pitchfork]] | accessdate = 2007-09-04 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071023195032/http://www.pitchforkmedia.com/article/feature/36737-staff-list-top-100-albums-of-the-1990s/page_8 | archivedate = October 23, 2007 | df = mdy-all }}</ref>|sign=|source=}}\n\n''[[NME]]'' claimed that the album \"pretty much invented emo's melodic wing\".<ref>{{cite web| last= Lewis| first= Luke| url= http://www.nme.com/reviews/weezer/10951 |title= Album review: Weezer \u2013 'Raditude'| website= [[NME]].com| date= November 2, 2009| access-date= March 6, 2011.</ref> [[AllMusic|AllMusic's]] Stephen Thomas Erlewine gave the album a full 5/5 stars, explaining \"What makes the band so enjoyable is their charming geekiness; instead of singing about despair, they sing about love, which is kind of refreshing in the gloom-drenched world of '90s guitar-pop.\"<ref name=\"allmusic\" />\n\n=== Accolades ===\nSince its release, the Blue Album has featured heavily in various \"must have\" lists compiled by the music media. Some of the more prominent of these lists to feature the Blue Album are shown below; this information is adapted from [[Acclaimed Music]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.acclaimedmusic.net/Current/A930.htm|title=List of Blue Album Accolades|accessdate=2007-02-05|publisher=[[Acclaimed Music]]|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20170905113004/http://www.acclaimedmusic.net/Current/A930.htm|archive-date=September 5, 2017|url-status= dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n{|class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"|Publication\n! scope=\"col\"|Country\n! scope=\"col\"|Accolade\n! scope=\"col\"|Year\n! scope=\"col\"|Rank\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"|''[[Blender (magazine)|Blender]]''\n| USA\n| 500 CDs You Must Own Before You Die<ref name=\"Blender\" />\n| 2003\n| *\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"|Music Underwater\n| USA\n| Top 100 Albums 1990\u20132003<ref>{{cite web | url = http://pub37.bravenet.com/forum/3172289350/show/479624 | title = Top 100 Albums 1990\u20132003 | publisher =Music Underwater | accessdate = 2007-02-05}}</ref>\n| 2004\n| No. 10\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"|[[Stylus Magazine|''Stylus'' Magazine]]\n| USA\n| Top 101\u2013200 Albums of All Time<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.stylusmagazine.com/articles/weekly_article/top-101-200-favourite-albums-ever-the-stylus-magazine-list.htm | title = Top 101\u2013200 Albums of All Time | work=Stylus Magazine | accessdate = 2007-02-05}}</ref>\n| 2004\n| No. 177\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"|''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork Media]]''\n| USA\n| Top 100 Albums of the 1990s<ref name=\"Pitchforklist\" />\n| 2003\n| No. 26\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"|''[[Rolling Stone]]''\n| USA\n| The 500 Greatest Albums of All Time<ref name=\"RS1234\" />\n| 2005\n| No. 299\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"|''Rolling Stone''\n| USA\n| The 100 Best Debut Albums of All Time<ref name=\"RSDebut\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/lists/the-100-greatest-debut-albums-of-all-time-20130322/weezer-19691231 |title=The 100 Best Debut Albums of All Time: 'Weezer' |work=Rolling Stone |accessdate=2013-05-15}}</ref>\n| 2013\n| No. 35\n|}\n\n<small>( * ) designates lists which are unordered.</small>\n\n== Track listing ==\n{{tracklist| all_writing   = [[Rivers Cuomo]], except where noted\n| title1        = [[My Name Is Jonas]]\n| writer1       = Cuomo, [[Patrick Wilson (musician)|Patrick Wilson]], [[Jason Cropper]]\n| length1       = 3:23\n| title2        = No One Else\n| length2       = 3:14\n| title3        = The World Has Turned and Left Me Here\n| writer3       = Cuomo, Wilson\n| length3       = 4:26\n| title4        = [[Buddy Holly (song)|Buddy Holly]]\n| length4       = 2:40\n| title5        = [[Undone \u2013 The Sweater Song]]\n| length5       = 4:55\n| title6        = Surf Wax America\n| writer6       = Cuomo, Wilson\n| length6       = 3:04\n| title7        = [[Say It Ain't So]]\n| length7       = 4:18\n| title8        = In the Garage\n| length8       = 3:56\n| title9        = Holiday\n| length9       = 3:26\n| title10       = [[Only in Dreams (song)|Only in Dreams]]\n| length10      = 7:59\n| total_length  = 41:26\n}}\n\n=== Deluxe edition bonus disc ===\nThe 2004 deluxe edition included a bonus disc, ''Dusty Gems and Raw Nuggets''.\n{{tracklist| title1      = Mykel & Carli\n| length1     = 2:53\n| title2      = Susanne\n| note2       = remix\n| length2     = 2:47\n| title3      = My Evaline\n| length3     = 0:44\n| title4      = Jamie\n| length4     = 4:19\n| title5      = [[My Name Is Jonas]]\n| note5       = live\n| writer5     = Cuomo, Wilson, Cropper\n| length5     = 3:39\n| title6      = Surf Wax America\n| note6       = live\n| writer6     = Cuomo, Wilson\n| length6     = 4:01\n| title7      = Jamie\n| note7       = acoustic live\n| length7     = 4:03\n| title8      = No One Else\n| note8       = acoustic live\n| length8     = 3:23\n| title9      = [[Undone \u2013 The Sweater Song|Undone (The Sweater Song)]]\n| note9       = demo\n| length9     = 5:33\n| title10     = Paperface\n| length10    = 3:01\n| title11     = [[Only in Dreams (song)|Only in Dreams]]\n| note11      = demo\n| length11    = 5:47\n| title12     = Lullaby for Wayne\n| writer12    = Cuomo, Wilson\n| length12    = 3:36\n| title13     = I Swear It's True\n| length13    = 2:57\n| title14     = [[Say It Ain't So]]\n| note14      = original album mix\n| length14    = 4:16\n| total_length = 50:59\n}}\n\nThe tracks on the bonus disc originally appeared on the following releases:<ref name=\"deluxeblue\" />\n* Tracks 1 and 3 from \"[[Undone \u2013 The Sweater Song]]\" single (1994)\n* Track 2 is from the soundtrack to ''[[Mallrats]]''; an earlier mix of the same song was included on the \"Undone\" single\n* Track 4 from ''[[DGC Rarities Vol. 1|DGC Rarities]]'' compilation (1994)\n* Tracks 5 and 6 from \"[[Buddy Holly (song)|Buddy Holly]]\" single (1994)\n* Tracks 7 and 8 from \"[[Say It Ain't So]]\" single (1995)\n* Tracks 9\u201311 previously unreleased, and part of ''[[The Kitchen Tapes (Weezer)|Kitchen Tape]]'' demo (1992)\n* Tracks 12 and 13 previously unreleased, pre-production recordings done with Ric Ocasek just prior to ''Weezer'''s recording (1993)\n* Track 14 is the version featured on the original release of the album. The mix was changed for the single and was later added to newer versions of the album. The single mix is the version included on Disc 1 of this Deluxe Edition.\n\n== Personnel ==\n'''Weezer'''\n\n* [[Rivers Cuomo]] \u2013 lead vocals, lead and rhythm guitar, keyboards, harmonica\n* [[Brian Bell]] \u2013 rhythm guitar (credited), backing vocals\n* [[Matt Sharp]] \u2013 bass, backing vocals\n* [[Patrick Wilson (musician)|Patrick Wilson]] \u2013 drums\n\n'''Additional musicians'''\n\n* Mykel Allan \u2013 spoken intermission on \"Undone \u2013 The Sweater Song\"\n* Karl Koch \u2013 dialogue, [[piano]] outro on \"Undone \u2013 The Sweater Song\"\n* [[Jason Cropper]] \u2013 guitar, backing vocals on \"Jamie\"\n\n'''Production'''\n\n* [[Ric Ocasek]] \u2013 producer\n* Chris Shaw \u2013 [[Audio engineering|engineer]]\n* Hal Belknap \u2013 assistant engineer\n* Peter Gowland, Peter Orth \u2014 photographer\n* Karl Koch \u2014 designer\n* Todd Sullivan \u2014 [[Artists and repertoire|A&R]]\n* George Marino \u2014 mastering\n\n== Charts ==\n\n=== Album ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Chart (1995\u201396)\n!Peak<br />position\n|-\n{{albumchart|Austria|47|artist=Weezer|album=Weezer (The Green Album)|accessdate=20 May 2016}}\n|-\n{{albumchart|Flanders|19|artist=Weezer|album=Weezer (The Blue Album)|accessdate=19 May 2016}}\n|-\n{{albumchart|Wallonia|40|artist=Weezer|album=Weezer (The Blue Album)|accessdate=19 May 2016}}\n|-\n{{albumchart|Canada|10|chartid=8012|artist=Weezer|album=Weezer (The Blue Album)|accessdate=19 May 2016}}\n|-\n{{albumchart|Netherlands|48|artist=Weezer|album=Weezer (The Blue Album)|accessdate=19 May 2016}}\n|-\n{{albumchart|Finland|22|artist=Weezer|album=Weezer (The Blue Album)|accessdate=19 May 2016|refname=finland}}\n|-\n{{albumchart|Germany3|61|artist=Weezer|album=Weezer (The Blue Album)|accessdate=19 May 2016}}\n|-\n{{albumchart|New Zealand|6|artist=Weezer|album=Weezer (The Blue Album)|accessdate=19 May 2016|refname=nzalbum}}\n|-\n{{albumchart|Norway|35|artist=Weezer|album=Weezer (The Blue Album)|accessdate=19 May 2016}}\n|-\n{{albumchart|UK|23|artist=Weezer|album=Weezer (The Blue Album)|date=1995-05-14|accessdate=19 May 2016|refname=ukcharts}}\n|-\n{{albumchart|Billboard200|16|M|title=Billboard 200 : Feb 04, 1995| url= https://web.archive.org/web/20130414042527/http://www.billboard.com/charts/1995-02-04/billboard-200| work= Billboard |refname= billboard| artist=Weezer|album=Weezer}}\n|}\n\n=== Singles ===\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n!rowspan=\"2\"| Year\n!rowspan=\"2\"| Song\n!colspan=\"6\"| Peak positions\n|-style=\"font-size:85%;line-height:1.3;vertical-align:top\"\n! style=\"width:4em\" | [[Modern Rock Tracks|US Modern Rock]]<br /><ref name=\"billboardsinglesweez\" />\n! style=\"width:4em\" | [[Billboard Hot 100|US<br />Bill-<br />board<br />Hot 100]]<br /><ref name=\"billboardsinglesweez\" />\n! style=\"width:4em\" | [[Hot 100 Airplay|US<br />Hot 100<br />Airplay]]<br /><ref name=\"billboardsinglesweez\" />\n! style=\"width:4em\" | [[UK Singles Chart|UK<br />Top 40]]<br /><ref name=\"ukcharts\" />\n! style=\"width:4em\" | Sweden<br /><ref name=\"swedenalbum\">{{Cite web|url=http://hitparad.se/showitem.asp?interpret=Weezer&titel=Weezer&cat=a|title=Swedish album chart archives|accessda