{"title_page": "Jeff Schneider (artist)", "text_new": "[[File:Jeff Schneider.jpg|thumb|Jeff Schneider]]\n\n'''Jeff Schneider''' (born 1960, Bethesda, Maryland) is an [[United States|American]] artist.\n\n== Life and work ==\n\nEarly on, Schneider showed a keen interest in photography often shooting and processing up to one hundred feet of black & white film a week. Growing increasingly tired of the representational aspects of photography, through darkroom manipulations, Schneider began to essentially abstract the \"objectivity\" of the camera lens. One of his professors at the [[University of South Florida]] suggested he enroll in a figure drawing and art theory class.  Not long after these initial steps into fine art, Schneider attended the 1980 Picasso Retrospective at the [[Museum of Modern Art]] in New York City. This exhibition confirmed his desire to become an artist.<ref>{{cite web|title=Bring up the bodies \u2013 and have a good look at them Visual arts round-up|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/culture/art-and-design/visual-art/bring-up-the-bodies-and-have-a-good-look-at-them-visual-arts-round-up-1.2230719|publisher=The Irish Times|accessdate=4 June 2015}}</ref>\n\nAfter he received his BFA in 1983 from [[Miami University]], he worked as an Art Director in commercial design with the John K. Howe Company, painting at night in garages and basements until he acquired a studio in downtown Cincinnati. Soon after, he received a scholarship to the graduate painting program at the [[University of Cincinnati]]. Working with Robert Knipschild and Frank Herrmann he received his master's degree of Fine Art in 1989. Schneider moved to New York City in 1990 to pursue his career in art and quickly became an integral part of the vibrant painting scene there.\n\nEarly in New York, Schneider worked as a studio assistant for many of New York's most recognized artists, notably [[Moira Dryer]], [[Ron Gorchov]], [[Dorothea Rockburne]], [[Janet Fish]], [[Chuck Close]] and [[David Salle]]. By taking advantage of their generational perspectives, this allowed the young artist to see first hand the inner workings of not only their relevant studios but also the gallery system that these artist\u2019s worked within.<ref>{{cite web|title=Up For Grabs|url=http://allenprojectsonline.com/exhibits6.html}}</ref>\n\nHis early exhibitions included \"Presentational Painting\" curated by Sanford Wumfeld and Eileen Roaman at [[Hunter College]] and the \u201cEast-West Cultural Studies\u201d painting show curated by [[Robert Storr (art academic)|Robert Storr]], a relationship that led to numerous projects with Storr at the Museum of Modern Art.\nAs scenes shifted, Schneider began to show his work with a gallery in Williamsburg, Brooklyn formed by Leah Stuhltrager and Cris Dam, which would lead to three group exhibitions. Schneider\u2019s work was seen as \u201cA blending of male androgyny and American pop cultural\u201d his reference to the \"Cowboy Philosopher\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://artforum.com/inprint/issue=198603&id=32473|title=artforum.com / in print|work=artforum.com|accessdate=6 April 2015}}</ref>  \"...reinforced the patriarchal power dynamic juxtaposed with the sometimes vulnerable and otherwise unassuming female character.\u201d His canvases, \"...Sophisticatedly staged by the artist, draw on inferences through association in our society and culture.\" The narratives struck an accord in the Brooklyn art scene as Schneider continued to exhibit throughout the borough as well as, Manhattan. The relationship with the Dam Stuhltrager Gallery led to his first international exhibition in Madrid, Spain. Schneider, along with [[Loren Munk]], Cris Dam and [[William Powhida]] exhibited at Galeria ArteVeintiuno, curated by Javier Duero from the Museo Reina Sofia.<ref>{{cite web|title=Familiarity can breed surprise and delight|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/culture/art-and-design/visual-art/familiarity-can-breed-surprise-and-delight-1.752427|publisher=The Irish Times}}</ref>\n\nAfter the exhibition in Madrid Schneider continued to focus on the European art scene which led to numerous exhibitions with Hillsboro Fine Art in Dublin, Ireland. [[Aidan Dunne]] of the [[Irish Times]] declared Schneider\u2019s work as \u201clively explorations of the mythology of the cowboy-gunslinger, treated humorously and with deftness of touch.\u201d Schneider has continued to exhibit in art fairs and galleries throughout Europe, as well as, exhibitions in Chicago, Miami and New York. He has exhibited with noted artists, [[Julian Schnabel]], [[Ross Bleckner]] and [[Donald Baechler]] as well as other New York artists and has lectured on his work at Hunter College in New York and the Dun Laoghaire Institute of Art in Dublin.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.damstuhltrager.com/thesedays_pages/onlinegallerypressrelease.htm |title=www.damstuhltrageronline.com |work=damstuhltrager.com |accessdate=6 April 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070917143900/http://www.damstuhltrager.com/thesedays_pages/onlinegallerypressrelease.htm |archivedate=17 September 2007 }}</ref>\n\nThe Oliver Sears Gallery represents Schneider\u2019s work in Europe and in the United States.<ref>{{cite web|title=Jeff Schneider & Nest Design|url=http://www.oliversearsgallery.com/exhibitions/jeff-schneider-and-nest-design/|publisher=Oliver Sears Gallery|accessdate=4 June 2015}}</ref>\n\nSchneider currently resides and works in [[New York City]].\n\n=== Selected exhibitions ===\n* 2020 Oliver Sears Gallery / The Time of our Lives / Dublin, Ireland\n* 2019 VUE art fair / Oliver Sears Gallery / Dublin, Ireland\n* 2019 Mosaic ArtSpace / Solo Exhibition / Queens, New York\n* 2019 SO Fine Art Editions / Summer Group Show / Dublin, Ireland\n* 2019 Oliver Sears Gallery / In Living Memory at Emo Court / County Laois / Ireland\n* 2019 Oliver Sears Gallery / Press Play / Dublin, Ireland\n* 2018 VUE art fair / Oliver Sears Gallery / Dublin, Ireland\n* 2018 Oliver Sears Gallery / Salon, Selected works / Dublin Ireland \n* 2018 The Factory LIC / Summer Exhibition 2018 / Long Island City, NY\n* 2017 ArtProv Gallery / Figure & Form / Providence, RI\n* 2016 Oliver Sears Gallery / London Art Fair / London, UK\n* 2015 ArtProv Gallery / Art Basel Miami Beach / Miami FL\n* 2015 Oliver Sears Gallery / In Residence / London, UK\n* 2015 ArtProv Gallery / Clothing Optional / Providence, RI\n* 2015 One Art Space / Williamsburg on Warren / New York, New York\n* 2015 Royal Hibernian Academy 185th Annual Exhibition / Dublin, Ireland\n* 2015 Oliver Sears Gallery / Jeff Schneider & Nest Design / Dublin, Ireland\n* 2014 ArtProv Gallery / Patterns and Perspectives / Providence, RI\n* 2013\tSo Fine Art Editions / National Contemporary Art Fair 2013 / Dublin, Ireland\n* 2012\tRoyal Hibernian Academy  ''182 Annual Exhibition ('''invited artist''')''\t/ Dublin, Ireland\n* 2011 Hillsboro Fine Art / New York Paintings / Ross Bleckner and Jeff Schneider / Dublin, Ireland\n* 2011\tAllen Gallery / Brooklyn Academy of Music / Annual Benefit Auction / Brooklyn, New York\n* 2010\tAllen Gallery / Brooklyn Academy of Music / Annual Benefit Auction / Brooklyn, New York\n* 2009\tHillsboro Fine Art / New York Contemporary / Donald Baechler, Ross Bleckner, Julian Schnabel, Jeff Schneider / Dublin, Ireland\n* 2009\tAllen Gallery / Private ROOM / New York, New York \n* 2008\tAllen Gallery / Up For Grabs / New York, New York\n* 2008 Dam Stuhltrager Gallery / Palette-Poles / Brooklyn, New York\n* 2006\tGaleria ArteVeintiuno /  Swap-Americana / Madrid, Spain\n* 2005\tDam Stuhltrager Gallery / These Days / Brooklyn, New York\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.jeffschneidernyc.com www.jeffschneidernyc.com]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Schneider, Jeff}}\n[[Category:American artists]]\n[[Category:1960 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Jeff Schneider.jpg|thumb|Jeff Schneider]]\n\n'''Jeff Schneider''' (born 1960, Bethesda, Maryland) is an [[United States|American]] artist.\n\n== Life and work ==\n\nEarly on, Schneider showed a keen interest in photography often shooting and processing up to one hundred feet of black & white film a week. Growing increasingly tired of the representational aspects of photography, through darkroom manipulations, Schneider began to essentially abstract the \"objectivity\" of the camera lens. One of his professors at the [[University of South Florida]] suggested he enroll in a figure drawing and art theory class.  Not long after these initial steps into fine art, Schneider attended the 1980 Picasso Retrospective at the [[Museum of Modern Art]] in New York City. This exhibition confirmed his desire to become an artist.<ref>{{cite web|title=Bring up the bodies \u2013 and have a good look at them Visual arts round-up|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/culture/art-and-design/visual-art/bring-up-the-bodies-and-have-a-good-look-at-them-visual-arts-round-up-1.2230719|publisher=The Irish Times|accessdate=4 June 2015}}</ref>\n\nAfter he received his BFA in 1983 from [[Miami University]], he worked as an Art Director in commercial design with the John K. Howe Company, painting at night in garages and basements until he acquired a studio in downtown Cincinnati. Soon after, he received a scholarship to the graduate painting program at the [[University of Cincinnati]]. Working with Robert Knipschild and Frank Herrmann he received his master's degree of Fine Art in 1989. Schneider moved to New York City in 1990 to pursue his career in art and quickly became an integral part of the vibrant painting scene there.\n\nEarly in New York, Schneider worked as a studio assistant for many of New York's most recognized artists, notably [[Moira Dryer]], [[Ron Gorchov]], [[Dorothea Rockburne]], [[Janet Fish]], [[Chuck Close]] and [[David Salle]]. By taking advantage of their generational perspectives, this allowed the young artist to see first hand the inner workings of not only their relevant studios but also the gallery system that these artist\u2019s worked within.<ref>{{cite web|title=Up For Grabs|url=http://allenprojectsonline.com/exhibits6.html}}</ref>\n\nHis early exhibitions included \"Presentational Painting\" curated by Sanford Wumfeld and Eileen Roaman at [[Hunter College]] and the \u201cEast-West Cultural Studies\u201d painting show curated by [[Robert Storr (art academic)|Robert Storr]], a relationship that led to numerous projects with Storr at the Museum of Modern Art.\nAs scenes shifted, Schneider began to show his work with a gallery in Williamsburg, Brooklyn formed by Leah Stuhltrager and Cris Dam, which would lead to three group exhibitions. Schneider\u2019s work was seen as \u201cA blending of male androgyny and American pop cultural\u201d his reference to the \"Cowboy Philosopher\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://artforum.com/inprint/issue=198603&id=32473|title=artforum.com / in print|work=artforum.com|accessdate=6 April 2015}}</ref>  \"...reinforced the patriarchal power dynamic juxtaposed with the sometimes vulnerable and otherwise unassuming female character.\u201d His canvases, \"...Sophisticatedly staged by the artist, draw on inferences through association in our society and culture.\" The narratives struck an accord in the Brooklyn art scene as Schneider continued to exhibit throughout the borough as well as, Manhattan. The relationship with the Dam Stuhltrager Gallery led to his first international exhibition in Madrid, Spain. Schneider, along with [[Loren Munk]], Cris Dam and [[William Powhida]] exhibited at Galeria ArteVeintiuno, curated by Javier Duero from the Museo Reina Sofia.<ref>{{cite web|title=Familiarity can breed surprise and delight|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/culture/art-and-design/visual-art/familiarity-can-breed-surprise-and-delight-1.752427|publisher=The Irish Times}}</ref>\n\nAfter the exhibition in Madrid Schneider continued to focus on the European art scene which led to numerous exhibitions with Hillsboro Fine Art in Dublin, Ireland. [[Aidan Dunne]] of the [[Irish Times]] declared Schneider\u2019s work as \u201clively explorations of the mythology of the cowboy-gunslinger, treated humorously and with deftness of touch.\u201d Schneider has continued to exhibit in art fairs and galleries throughout Europe, as well as, exhibitions in Chicago, Miami and New York. He has exhibited with noted artists, [[Julian Schnabel]], [[Ross Bleckner]] and [[Donald Baechler]] as well as other New York artists and has lectured on his work at Hunter College in New York and the Dun Laoghaire Institute of Art in Dublin.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.damstuhltrager.com/thesedays_pages/onlinegallerypressrelease.htm |title=www.damstuhltrageronline.com |work=damstuhltrager.com |accessdate=6 April 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070917143900/http://www.damstuhltrager.com/thesedays_pages/onlinegallerypressrelease.htm |archivedate=17 September 2007 }}</ref>\n\nThe Oliver Sears Gallery represents Schneider\u2019s work in Europe and in the United States.<ref>{{cite web|title=Jeff Schneider & Nest Design|url=http://www.oliversearsgallery.com/exhibitions/jeff-schneider-and-nest-design/|publisher=Oliver Sears Gallery|accessdate=4 June 2015}}</ref>\n\nSchneider currently resides and works in [[New York City]].\n\n=== Selected exhibitions ===\n* 2019 VUE art fair / Oliver Sears Gallery / Dublin, Ireland\n* 2019 Mosaic ArtSpace / Solo Exhibition / Queens, New York\n* 2019 SO Fine Art Editions / Summer Group Show / Dublin, Ireland\n* 2019 Oliver Sears Gallery / In Living Memory at Emo Court / County Laois / Ireland\n* 2019 Oliver Sears Gallery / Press Play / Dublin, Ireland\n* 2018 VUE art fair / Oliver Sears Gallery / Dublin, Ireland\n* 2018 Oliver Sears Gallery / Salon, Selected works / Dublin Ireland \n* 2018 The Factory LIC / Summer Exhibition 2018 / Long Island City, NY\n* 2017 ArtProv Gallery / Figure & Form / Providence, RI\n* 2016 Oliver Sears Gallery / London Art Fair / London, UK\n* 2015 ArtProv Gallery / Art Basel Miami Beach / Miami FL\n* 2015 Oliver Sears Gallery / In Residence / London, UK\n* 2015 ArtProv Gallery / Clothing Optional / Providence, RI\n* 2015 One Art Space / Williamsburg on Warren / New York, New York\n* 2015 Royal Hibernian Academy 185th Annual Exhibition / Dublin, Ireland\n* 2015 Oliver Sears Gallery / Jeff Schneider & Nest Design / Dublin, Ireland\n* 2014 ArtProv Gallery / Patterns and Perspectives / Providence, RI\n* 2013\tSo Fine Art Editions / National Contemporary Art Fair 2013 / Dublin, Ireland\n* 2012\tRoyal Hibernian Academy  ''182 Annual Exhibition ('''invited artist''')''\t/ Dublin, Ireland\n* 2011 Hillsboro Fine Art / New York Paintings / Ross Bleckner and Jeff Schneider / Dublin, Ireland\n* 2011\tAllen Gallery / Brooklyn Academy of Music / Annual Benefit Auction / Brooklyn, New York\n* 2010\tAllen Gallery / Brooklyn Academy of Music / Annual Benefit Auction / Brooklyn, New York\n* 2009\tHillsboro Fine Art / New York Contemporary / Donald Baechler, Ross Bleckner, Julian Schnabel, Jeff Schneider / Dublin, Ireland\n* 2009\tAllen Gallery / Private ROOM / New York, New York \n* 2008\tAllen Gallery / Up For Grabs / New York, New York\n* 2008 Dam Stuhltrager Gallery / Palette-Poles / Brooklyn, New York\n* 2006\tGaleria ArteVeintiuno /  Swap-Americana / Madrid, Spain\n* 2005\tDam Stuhltrager Gallery / These Days / Brooklyn, New York\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.jeffschneidernyc.com www.jeffschneidernyc.com]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Schneider, Jeff}}\n[[Category:American artists]]\n[[Category:1960 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "name_user": "Camus312", "label": "safe", "comment": "update", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jeff_Schneider_(artist)"}
{"title_page": "Molang", "text_new": "{{Infobox television\n| show_name                = Molang\n| image                    = [[File:Molang Logo.png|300px]]\n| image_size               = 3px\n| image_alt                = \n| caption                  = \n}}\n| director                 = Marie-Caroline Villand\n| composer                 = {{Plainlist|\n* Nicholas Varley\n}}\n| country                  = France\n| num_seasons              = 4\n| num_episodes             = 209\n| list_episodes            = \n| producer                 = [[Roch Lener]]\n| runtime                  = Season 1 \u2014 52x3'30<br>Season 2 \u2014 52x3'30<br>Season 3 \u2014 52x3'30<br>TV Specials \u2014 9x7'\n| company                  = [[Millimages]]\n| network                  = [[Canal+ Family]]<br>[[RT\u00c9jr]]<br>[[Pop (British and Irish TV channel)|Pop]]<br>[[Tiny Pop]]\n| channel                  = \n| picture_format           = 1080i HDTV\n| first_run                = January 2, 2016\n| released                 = \n| first_aired              = January 2, 2016\n}}\n\n'''''Molang''''' ({{IPAc-en|m|o\u028a|l|\u00e6|\u014b}}) is an American/British/French children's animated television series created by the animation studio [[Millimages]], [[HIT Entertainment]] and [[Disney Junior]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.animationmagazine.net/tv/millimages-preps-molang-debut-at-mip/|title=Millimages Preps 'Molang' Debut at MIP|last=McLean|first=Tom|date=2014-04-01|website=Animation Magazine|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-15}}</ref> The titular character, Molang, was designed by the Korean illustrator [[Hye-Ji Yoon]], on the platform [[KakaoTalk]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.jeanmarcmorandini.com/article-392720-le-dessin-anime-molang-qui-connait-un-grand-succes-en-france-s-exporte-desormais-en-chine-annonce-son-producteur.html|title=Le dessin anim\u00e9 \"Molang\", qui conna\u00eet un grand succ\u00e8s en France, s'exporte d\u00e9sormais en Chine, annonce son producteur|website=www.jeanmarcmorandini.com|language=fr|access-date=2019-05-15}}</ref>\n\n{{As of|2019}}, Molang's TV exposure extends to more than 190 countries and has become a cross-media franchise: TV series, merchandising, GIFs, digital series, music videos, stickers, etc.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.animationmagazine.net/licensing/molang-spreads-happiness-with-new-agents-licensees/|title='Molang' Spreads Happiness with New Agents & Licensees|last=Milligan|first=Mercedes|date=2016-11-29|website=Animation Magazine|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-15}}</ref>\n\n== Plot ==\nThe series features the \"offbeat friendship\" between main characters Molang and Piu Piu as they humorously confront everyday problems.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.animationmagazine.net/tv/millimages-sells-molang-to-tf1-season-3-on-track/|title=Millimages Sells \u2018Molang\u2019 to TF1, Season 3 on Track|last=Milligan|first=Mercedes|date=2017-09-07|website=Animation Magazine|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-14}}</ref>\n\n== Characters ==\nMolang is a big, round, white rabbit, and Piu Piu is a little yellow chicken. They speak an unknown,strange language, but are easy to understand. Their dialogue consists in easily recognizable expressions of surprise, approbation, gratitude, and congratulations. When one of the characters expresses a specific thought, a bubble with a drawing inside it appears above its head.\n\n== Broadcast ==\nThe series is shown in [[Cartoonito (UK & Ireland)|Cartoonito]] and [[Tiny Pop]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.licensingsource.net/molang-to-make-tiny-pop-debut-in-the-uk/|title=Molang to make Tiny POP debut in the UK|access-date=2019-01-22}}</ref>  in United Kingdom, [[Canal+ Family]] in France,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.highfun.com/blog/?p=2742|title=\" Molang \" est \u00e0 retrouver tous les jours sur Piwi+ et Canal+ Family {{!}} Le Blog de Claudia|last=claudia|language=fr-FR|access-date=2019-01-22}}</ref> [[Disney Junior]] in United States,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.animationmagazine.net/tv/more-molang-coming-to-disney-junior-us/|title=More \u2018Molang\u2019 Coming to Disney Junior US|last=Milligan|first=Mercedes|date=2018-05-21|website=Animation Magazine|language=en-US|access-date=2019-01-22}}</ref> and [[Rai YoYo]] in Italy,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://kidscreen.com/2017/12/11/millimages-molang-hops-onto-rai-italy/|title=Millimages\u2019 Molang hops onto Rai Italy|access-date=2019-01-22}}</ref> and [[Niki Junior]]<ref>{{cite web | url=http://niki.ua/project/molang/| title=\u041c\u043e\u043b\u0430\u043d\u0433 - Niki |website=niki.ua|language=uk|access-date=2019-04-12}}</ref> in Ukraine, and Netflix.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/MolangOfficialPage/posts/2551033164947649|title=Molang official Facebook page|date=June 28, 2019|website=www.facebook.com|language=en|access-date=2019-08-13}}</ref>\n\n== Merchandising ==\n\nAs a merchandising brand, Molang uses \"My Best Friend\" as a universal signature for all worldwide licensees, on all packagings. It now represents two master toy licensees (Tomy & Jazwares), over 50 licensees worldwide, and more than 700 different products, including kids and adults apparels, children's books and magazines, stationery, magnets, stickers, underwear, sleepwear, etc.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.awn.com/news/millimages-scores-mulitiple-deals-china|title=Millimages Scores Mulitiple Deals in China|website=Animation World Network|language=en|access-date=2019-05-15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.animationmagazine.net/events/license-to-profit/|title=License to Profit|last=Magazine|first=Animation|date=2016-06-12|website=Animation Magazine|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2018/06/camsing-alibaba-travel-frog-nordisk-film-sweden-1202401680/|title=Camsing & Alibaba Team For Chinese Theme Park, Nordisk Film Sweden Hire \u2014 Global Briefs|last=Wiseman|first=Andreas|last2=Wiseman|first2=Andreas|date=2018-06-01|website=Deadline|language=en|access-date=2019-05-15}}</ref>\n\n=== Books ===\nIn November 2016, the French publisher [[Flammarion Publishing|Flammarion]] launched a collection of four little square books based on the series episodes and one big album. On Easter 2017, seven new books were released. They were specially promoted by the broadcaster. Among them, four little square books and one album but also two flap books in which children have to search for hidden characters and animals.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2018/tv/global/france-televisions-unveils-dozens-of-new-animated-series-features-at-annecy-1202844520/|title=France Televisions Unveils Dozens of New Animated Series, Features at Annecy|last=Keslassy|first=Elsa|last2=Keslassy|first2=Elsa|date=2018-06-13|website=Variety|language=en|access-date=2019-05-15}}</ref>\n\nScholastic Inc., the world's largest publisher of children's books, have published 4 8x8 books and one album. All the books include stickers and the album contains a sticker storybook with more than 25 stickers and 4 pages to decorate. They are available to all national retailers, independents, special market channels and through Scholastic Reading Club and Scholastic Book Fairs.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nIn October 2018, the Italien publisher Gribaudo has launched 6 activity books with games, colouring pages, stickers and different activities.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nThe publisher Nelson Verlag will launch a range of their mini books dedicated to Molang early 2020 in Germany.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n=== DVDs<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://kidscreen.com/2019/01/17/kidstream-launches-new-content/|title=Kidstream launches new content|access-date=2019-05-15}}</ref>===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Title\n!Region\n!Release date\n|-\n|Molang \u2014 Season 1 as seen on Disney Junior\n| rowspan=\"2\" |United States\n|January 17, 2017\n|-\n|Molang \u2014 Season 1 as seen on Disney Junior\n|August 7, 2018\n|-\n|Molang \u2014 Season 1\n| rowspan=\"2\" |North America\n|August 15, 2017\n|-\n|Molang \u2014 Season 2\n|April 3, 2018\n|-\n|Molang Season 1 \u2014 Nel Bosco\n| rowspan=\"3\" |Italy\n|September 6, 2018\n|-\n|Molang Season 1 \u2014 Super Star\n|September 6, 2018\n|-\n|Molang Season 2 \u2014 Safari\n|2019\n|-\n|Molang Season 1 \u2014 Vol 1 \u2014 The Party\n| rowspan=\"2\" |Nordics\n|June 11, 2018\n|-\n|Molang Season 1 \u2014 Vol 2 \u2014 The Party\n|June 11, 2019\n|-\n|Molang Season 1 \u2014 Vol 1\n| rowspan=\"2\" |United Kingdom\n|TBA\n|-\n|Molang Season 1 \u2014 Vol 2\n|TBA\n|}\n\n==List of episodes==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n!Season\n!Title\n!Description\n|-\n|1\n|The Party\n|Molang and Piu Piu are invited to a party!\n|-\n|1\n|The Christmas Tree\n|After accidentally destroying their original tree, Molang and Piu Piu search for a new Christmas tree!\n|-\n|1\n|The Goldfish\n|Molang and Piu Piu try to play with their unamused goldfish!\n|-\n|1\n|The Sleepless Night\n|Molang and Piu Piu have trouble falling asleep!\n|-\n|1\n|Skiing\n|Molang and Piu Piu go skiing!\n|-\n|1\n|A Restless Night\n|After watching a scary movie, Piu Piu is too afraid to sleep!\n|-\n|1\n|The Suitcase\n|Molang and Piu Piu overpack their suitcase to paradise!\n|-\n|1\n|The Surprise\n|Piu Piu creates a surprise for Molang!\n|-\n|1\n|The Firemen\n|After dressing up for a costume party, Molang and Piu Piu are mistaken for firefighters.\n|-\n|1\n|The Guest\n|Molang must protect his home after he invites a clumsy guest over.\n|-\n|1\n|The Butterfly\n|During a picnic, Molang and Piu Piu try and catch a butterfly.\n|-\n|1\n|The Rescuers\n|While at the beach, Molang and Piu Piu learn to be lifeguards.\n|-\n|1\n|The Fishing Trip\n|Molang and Piu Piu learn the best way to catch fish!\n|-\n|1\n|The Extras\n|While traveling in Hollywood, Molang and Piu Piu wander onto a movie set and try to help the film!\n|-\n|1\n|The Camel\n|While taking a tour, Molang and Piu Piu try to ride a troublesome camel.\n|-\n|1\n|The Car\n|When Piu Piu gets a new car, he and Molang s