r a birthday present to a friend but they miss the mailman and so must chase him down.\n|-\n|2\n|The Side Car\n|Molang and Piu Piu help a friend try to win a sidecar by finding a missing puzzle piece.\n|-\n|2\n|The Competition\n|Piu Piu competes in a watermelon competition but his watermelon is too big to carry!\n|-\n|2\n|The Aquarium\n|After they get a flat tire, Molang and Piu Piu discover an aquarium that doesn't have any visitors.\n|-\n|2\n|The Soccer Match\n|When their goalie gets injured, Piu Piu steps in to help Molang's soccer team.\n|-\n|2\n|The Sled\n|After accidentally breaking his sled, Molang tries to find a way to fix it.\n|-\n|2\n|MC Molang\n|After Molang and Piu Piu take up DJing, they decide to throw a concert in the country.\n|-\n|2\n|At the Circus\n|While at the circus, Molang is mistaken for a clown and sent into the ring!\n|-\n|2\n|The Highland Games\n|While in Scotland, Molang and Piu Piu stumble onto a tree trunk tossing competition and decide to compete!\n|-\n|2\n|The Food Truck\n|After winning an old truck in a raffle, Molang and Piu Piu decide to turn it into a food truck.\n|-\n|2\n|Cupcake\n|When Molang and Piu Piu find a cupcake restaurant, they try to help the owner by bringing in more customers.\n|-\n|2\n|Safari\n|When Molang and Piu Piu's car breaks down in the middle of the savannah, they search for a signal to call their friends for help.\n|-\n|2\n|The Golf\n|In order to use the electric golf carts, Molang and Piu Piu decide to go golfing.\n|-\n|2\n|The Climbing Rope\n|Molang and Piu Piu go hiking with a guide in the mountains but things go wrong when Molang starts yodeling.\n|-\n|2\n|The Piano\n|After attending a piano concert, Molang and Piu Piu try to play the instrument but accidentally break it!\n|-\n|2\n|Unlucky\n|When Molang and Piu Piu try to throw a costume party, bad luck causes everything to go wrong!\n|-\n|2\n|Fanfare\n|Molang and Piu Piu try to join a brass marching band but struggle to find the perfect instrument for Piu Piu to play.\n|-\n|2\n|The Ghost Train\n|While on a ghost train ride at an amusement park, Molang and Piu Piu get so scared they accidentally destroy the ride as they try to flee!\n|-\n|2\n|Holiday Home\n|Molang and Piu Piu rent a vacation home in the forest but the place doesn't look like it does in the brochure!\n|-\n|2\n|The Acrobats\n|When Molang and Piu Piu go to the circus, they try to convince the ringmaster to let them be a part of the show!\n|-\n|2\n|Rainy Day\n|Molang and Piu Piu go on a fishing trip but rain threatens to ruin their vacation!\n|-\n|2\n|The Boomerang\n|While in Australia, Molang and Piu Piu try out a friend's boomerang but a group of kangaroos won't give it back!\n|-\n|2\n|The Salesman\n|When a door to door salesman visits, Molang ends up buying too many useless objects!\n|-\n|2\n|The Shooting Stars\n|Molang and Piu Piu buy a telescope to look at shooting stars but unexpectedly spy something else!\n|-\n|2\n|The Kung Fu\n|When Molang and Piu Piu struggle to make crepes, a mysterious pal offers to teach them kung fu to help.\n|-\n|2\n|The Vegetable Garden\n|Molang and Piu Piu try to plant a vegetable garden but birds keep eating all their seeds!\n|-\n|2\n|The Robinson\n|After their ship sinks and they wash up on shore of a deserted island, Molang and Piu Piu turn the island into their own paradise!\n|-\n|2\n|The Farm\n|While visiting a farmer friend, Molang and Piu Piu help him get his cow ready for a competition at the fair.\n|-\n|2\n|The Casting\n|While auditioning for a film, Molang and Piu Piu's casting sessions keep ending in mishaps!\n|-\n|2\n|The Jam Jar\n|Molang and Piu Piu make their own jam but the next morning, discover they can't open any of the jars!\n|-\n|2\n|The Little Monkey\n|After helping an injured monkey heal, Molang, Piu Piu and a vet must convince it to return to the wild.\n|-\n|2\n|The Parrot\n|Molang and Piu Piu look after a friend's parrot named Coco but she manages to escape!\n|-\n|2\n|A Gust of Wind\n|While trying to play volleyball at the beach, Molang and Piu Piu's game is interrupted by a strong wind!\n|-\n|2\n|The Monster Under the Bed\n|After seeing a horror movie, Piu Piu thinks there's a monster hiding in the house and Molang has to find a way to reassure him.\n|-\n|2\n|The Incredible Animal\n|While on safari, Piu Piu sees a white rhino and searches to find him again to show Molang and their guide.\n|-\n|2\n|The Jungle Friend\n|Molang and Piu Piu search for a rare flower in the jungle and get some help from a new friend!\n|-\n|2\n|Flash Mob\n|When Piu Piu thinks Molang is hiding something from him, he follows his friend to the train station and discovers a surprise!\n|-\n|2\n|A Bottle at Sea\n|When Molang and Piu Piu find a bottle with a map inside, they realize it's a treasure map and decide to set sail for adventure!\n|-\n|2\n|The Supporters\n|Molang and Piu Piu join a bus full of basketball fans at a game but Piu Piu can't stop sneezing!\n|-\n|2\n|Little Peckish\n|While helping an archaeologist friend on a dig, Piu Piu's stolen sandwich leads to a remarkable discovery!\n|-\n|2\n|The Brioche\n|After winning a TV show contest, Molang becomes a star but struggles to find time to spend with Piu Piu!\n|-\n|2\n|The Ibex\n|While picnicking in the mountains, Molang accidentally gets their house keys stuck on a mountain sheep's horn!\n|-\n|2\n|Mr. Muscles\n|Molang and Piu Piu help a circus performer named Mr. Muscles overcome his fear of mice.\n|-\n|2\n|Alone on the Ice Pack\n|After meeting a lonely astronomer, Molang and Piu Piu try to find a way to get others to visit him.\n|-\n|2\n|The Mouse\n|While searching for cheese, a little mouse creates big problems for Molang and Piu Piu in a mountain chalet.\n|-\n|2\n|Ski School\n|Molang and Piu Piu prove to be too clumsy during their skiing lessons!\n|-\n|3\n|The Instructions\n|While trying to build a covered verandah in their garden, Molang and Piu Piu lose the building instructions!\n|-\n|3\n|The Rock Band\n|While at a rock band audition, Molang and Piu Piu's enthusiastic friend tries his hardest to join the group but causes small catatrophes instead!\n|-\n|3\n|The Delivery Men\n|While hiking in the mountains, Molang and Piu Piu try to help their friend the delivery man who doesn't realize he's dropping his cargo behind him!\n|-\n|3\n|Firefighters!\n|Molang and Piu Piu want to become firemen and take several tests to become part of the team at the station.\n|-\n|3\n|The Box\n|After a friend fails to throw out a cardboard box, Molang and Piu Piu mistaken it as something he wants to keep and tries to return it to him.\n|-\n|3\n|Santa\n|After Santa accidentally gets knocked out by their Christmas tree, Molang and Piu Piu decide to do his job for him.\n|-\n|3\n|The Mule\n|While traveling in Peru, there aren't enough llamas for the whole group so Molang and Piu Piu get a mule!\n|-\n|3\n|The Magic Lamp\n|After getting stuck in the desert, Molang and Piu Piu discover a lamp and hope a genie can help them in their dire situation!\n|-\n|3\n|The Yeti\n|While in Tibet, Molang and Piu Piu want to go hiking in the mountains but are warned by the villagers that there's a yeti up there!\n|-\n|3\n|At the Fair\n|While strolling through a funfair, Molang spots a pretty, pink unicorn stuffed animal and Piu Piu tries to win it for him.\n|-\n|3\n|The Rescue\n|A giant wave beaches a whale and Molang and Piu Piu comes to its rescue!\n|-\n|3\n|The Detectives\n|When it's obvious Piu Piu has amazing abilities to find lost objects, he and Molang decide to become private detectives!\n|-\n|3\n|Super Molang\n|Molang puts on a real superhero's costume and gains the ability to fly and incredible strength!\n|-\n|3\n|The Choir\n|Right before the Christmas concert, Piu Piu hurts his voice before his solo and Molang comes up with a clever way to help.\n|-\n|3\n|The Ghost\n|Molang and Piu Piu's house is haunted by a phantom saxophonist!\n|-\n|3\n|The Alien\n|After an alien crash lands in their garden, Molang and Piu Piu try to hide him from their friends by pretending the party their hosting is a costume party!\n|-\n|3\n|Shuuuuush!\n|When Molang and Piu Piu discover their new neighbor is a famous pianist, they try their hardest to make sure they don't make a single sound so he can concentrate.\n|-\n|3\n|Top Model\n|While Molang tries to be a top model, a designer fixates upon Piu Piu instead!\n|-\n|3\n|The Space Friends\n|Extraterrestrials teleport Molang and Piu Piu onto their spaceship so they can teach them the meaning of laughter!\n|-\n|3\n|The Knight\n|After unfreezing a knight trapped in a block of ice, Molang and Piu Piu try to recreate his world to keep him from going into shock!\n|-\n|3\n|A New Friend\n|Piu Piu wins a goldfish at the funfair for Molang but soon becomes jealous of his friend's closeness to the fish!\n|-\n|3\n|The Haunted House\n|Molang and Piu Piu decide to spend the night in a castle hotel even after learning it's haunted!\n|-\n|3\n|The Whale\n|Molang and Piu Piu try to save a whale trapped in the ice!\n|-\n|3\n|The Spider\n|After being unable to chase a spider out of the house, Molang and Piu Piu learn martial arts to defend themselves!\n|-\n|3\n|The Broom\n|Molang tries to clean with a witch's broom but it wakes up and a magical rodeo ensues!\n|-\n|3\n|The Sorcerer's Apprentices\n|Molang and Piu Piu find a sorcerer's hut!\n|-\n|3\n|The Easter Eggs\n|Piu Piu trains for the annual Easter Egg hunt but then on the big day, becomes so overexcited, he can't find a single egg!\n|-\n|3\n|The Turtle\n|Molang and Piu Piu try to help a turtle whose flipper is stuck in a plastic bag.\n|-\n|3\n|The Birdling\n|Molang and Piu Piu help hatch and care for a baby bird so well that it doesn't want to leave and join its fellow birds!\n|-\n|3\n|The Condor\n|A mama Condor mistakes Piu Piu for her baby!\n|-\n|3\n|The Dancers\n|While watching a dance performance, a choreographer asks for Piu Piu's help performing a particular dance move: a lift!\n|-\n|3\n|Mega Piu Piu\n|After Piu Piu struggles with being so small, Molang has an inventor friend help Piu Piu grow to the same size as Molang.\n|-\n|3\n|The Frog\n|Molang and Piu Piu nurse a frog back to health.\n|-\n|3\n|The Storm\n|Molang and Piu Piu try to help all the animals during a windstorm.\n|-\n|3\n|The Panda\n|While trying to spot pandas in China, Molang and Piu Piu must save a baby panda after it falls into a ravine!\n|-\n|3\n|The Call of the Forest\n|After discovering an abandoned pup, Molang and Piu Piu train it to be a sled dog.\n|-\n|3\n|Elves\n|After falling into a secret tunnel, Piu Piu discovers Santa's elves and like him and becomes their leader!\n|-\n|3\n|The Long Trip\n|Molang and Piu Piu are out flying kites when they disturb a flock of migrating storks!\n|-\n|3\n|Skate Molang\n|Molang tries to ride a skateboard.\n|-\n|3\n|The Sand Statue\n|After making a sculpture of themselves out of sand, Molang and Piu Piu try to keep the tide from destroying it.\n|-\n|3\n|The Bodyguards\n|Molang and Piu Piu go to a pop star's concert and become the star's bodyguards!\n|-\n|3\n|The Competition\n|Molang and Piu Piu participate in strength challenges but Piu Piu is made fun of for his size.\n|-\n|3\n|The Cap\n|After accidentally ruining Piu Piu's new cap, Molang learns he may need to travel to Peru to get a replacement.\n|-\n|3\n|Electro Molang\n|After a lightning storm, Molang gains a strange power: when he presses his stomach, he lights up like a lamp!\n|-\n|3\n|Watch Out\n|Molang and Piu Piu stand in as waiters but struggle with the restaurant's swinging door.\n|-\n|3\n|Actor Molang\n|Molang sturggles with his line as the lead in a play!\n|-\n|3\n|Mini Molang\n|Molang and Piu Piu are accidentally shrunk!\n|-\n|3\n|The Dragon\n|While looking after a friend's sheep, Molang and Piu Piu accidentally hatch a dragon and struggle to make it get along with the flock!\n|-\n|3\n|The Flying Carpet\n|After riding a camel makes them sick, Molang and Piu Piu search the desert for a flying carpet to ride instead.\n|-\n|3\n|The Husky\n|While exploring the Canadian wilderness, a husky steals Molang and Piu Piu's snowmobile keys and they chase him to get them back!\n|-\n|3\n|Into the Wild\n|Molang and Piu Piu bring a friend hiking in the mountains but he's missing all the sites because he's too busy with the technology he's brought!\n|-\n|3\n|The Pullover\n|Piu Piu knits a sweater for Molang but it's too itchy!\n|-\n|4\n|To the Shelter\n|Molang and Piu Piu search for a new shelter after a mammoth crashes into theirs.\n|-\n|4\n|The Saber Tooth Kitten\n|In Prehistory, when you meet a sabre tooth tiger, you run for your life. But Molang and Piu Piu just can't resist the cuteness of this baby tiger...\n|-\n|4\n|The Wig\n|Molang and Piu Piu create a splendid wig for the king, but nobody realizes that Piu Piu has fallen inside!\n|-\n|4\n|The Berries\n|When Molang and Piu Piu go berry picking, an extraordinary adventure unfolds before them.\n|-\n|4\n|All the Colors\n|Molang and Piu Piu are Merlin's apprentices, but are forbidden from using the magic wand.\n|-\n|4\n|The River\n|Molang and Piu Piu find themselves unfortunately separated, each one on a different river bank.\n|-\n|4\n|The Tourney\n|In the Middle Ages, Molang and Piu Piu are coming to deliver the bread at the village market when Molang swoons and falls in front of some lances.\n|-\n|4\n|The New World\n|Molang and Pui Pui are walking along a port when they come across a young navigator searching for a crew to go on the discovery of uncharted lands.\n|-\n|4\n|The Labyrinth\n|Molang and Piu Piu are shepherds. But Kiki, their little goat has the urge to freely run about. Escaping from the pen, she leads them to a strange maze.\n|-\n|4\n|Knights and Dragons\n|When some knights attempt to fight a dragon, Molang and Piu Piu are instructed to prepare some food for them.\n|-\n|4\n|The Great Laundry\n|The king is going to give a dancing show and Molang and Piu Piu are in charge of his costume.\n|-\n|4\n|The Wooden Egg\n|Washed up on an island, Molang and Piu Piu discover an inhabited fort with many Piu Pius.\n|-\n|4\n|Cyclops\n|Molang and Piu Piu are shipwrecked and their raft washes up on an island. Relieved, they go in search of friends but they are about to make an extraordinary meeting.\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:2010s American animated television series]]\n[[Category:2010s British animated television series]]\n[[Category:2010s French animated television series]]\n[[Category:American children's animated television series]]\n[[Category:British children's animated television programmes]]\n[[Category:French children's animated television series]]\n[[Category:Animated television series about rabbits and hares]]\n[[Category:Television series about chickens]]\n[[Category:Television series by Mattel Creations]]\n", "name_user": "Liselecoco", "label": "safe", "comment": "Maj Info box", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Molang"}
{"title_page": "George Stovin Venables", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=September 2016}}\n'''George Stovin Venables''' (1810&ndash;1888), born in [[Wales]], was a journalist and a [[barrister]] at the English bar.\n\nHis father was Richard Venables, vicar of [[Nantmel]] and then [[archdeacon]] of [[Carmarthen]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://biography.wales/article/s-DILL-DIL-1650 |title=DILLWYN DILLWYN-LLEWELYN, (DILLWYN) VENABLES-LLEWELYN|work=[[Dictionary of Welsh Biography]]|publisher=The National Library of Wales|location=Aberystwyth |date=1959|accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref> He was educated at [[Eton College]], [[Charterhouse School]], and [[Jesus College, Cambridge]].<ref>{{acad|id=VNBS828GS|name=Venables, George Stovin}}</ref> At Cambridge, he won the [[Chancellor's Gold Medal]] for poetry in 1831,<ref>{{cite book|title=A Complete Collection of the English Poems which Have Obtained the Chancellor's Gold Medal in the University of Cambridge|publisher=MacMillan & Co|location=London|url=https://archive.org/details/acompletecollec00cambgoog|author= |format=PDF|year=1859|accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref> and was a [[Cambridge Apostle]] from 1832.<ref>[http://www.modern-humanities.info/groups/apostles.htm The Apostles<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{dead link|date=April 2020}}</ref> He became a Fellow of Jesus College.\n\nHe was [[called to the Bar]] at the [[Inner Temple]] in 1836, and was in practice for over 40 years. He also wrote much journalism from the mid-1850s, as a leader writer for ''[[The Times]]'' and the ''[[Saturday Review (London)|Saturday Review]]''.<ref name = \"Carroll\">David Carroll, ''George Eliot: The Critical Heritage'' (1995), p. 224.</ref>\n\nHis literary connections included time at Charterhouse with [[William Makepeace Thackeray]] (they fought); the character George Warrington in ''[[Pendennis]]'' is said to be based on Venables.<ref name = Carroll/><ref>[http://www.online-literature.com/anthony-trollope/thackeray/1/ In [[Anthony Trollope]]'s biography (online)].</ref> A friendship with [[Alfred, Lord Tennyson]] arose from Cambridge days.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://carlyleletters.dukejournals.org/cgi/content/full/12/1/lt-18401209-TC-WDC-01 |title=The Carlyle Letters Online<!-- Bot generated title --> |accessdate=28 October 2007 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110721213342/http://carlyleletters.dukejournals.org/cgi/content/full/12/1/lt-18401209-TC-WDC-01 |archivedate=21 July 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> He wrote an anonymous book of verse ''Joint Compositions'' (1848) with [[Henry Lushington]]. He was an early and favourable reviewer of [[Thomas Carlyle]], another friend.<ref>Jules Paul Seigel, ''Thomas Carlyle: The Critical Heritage'' (1995), p. 467.</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==References==\n*''Concise Dictionary of National Biography''\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Venables, George Stovin}}\n[[Category:1810 births]]\n[[Category:1888 deaths]]\n[[Category:People educated at Eton College]]\n[[Category:People educated at Charterhouse School]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Jesus College, Cambridge]]\n[[Category:Fellows of Jesus College, Cambridge]]\n[[Category:Members of the Inner Temple]]\n[[Category:Welsh barristers]]\n[[Category:British male journalists]]\n[[Category:19th-century journalists]]\n[[Category:Male journalists]]\n[[Category:19th-century British male writers]]\n\n\n{{UK-law-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=September 2016}}\n'''George Stovin Venables''' (1810&ndash;1888), born in [[Wales]], was a journalist and a [[barrister]] at the English bar.\n\nHis father was Richard Venables, vicar of [[Nantmel]] and then [[archdeacon]] of [[Carmarthen]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://biography.wales/article/s-DILL-DIL-1650 |title=DILLWYN DILLWYN-LLEWELYN, (DILLWYN) VENABLES-LLEWELYN|work=[[Dictionary of Welsh Biography]]|publisher=The National Library of Wales|location=Aberystwyth |date=1959|accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref> He was educated at [[Eton College]], [[Charterhouse School]], and [[Jesus College, Cambridge]].<ref>{{acad|id=VNBS828GS|name=Venables, George Stovin}}</ref> At Cambridge, he won the [[Chancellor's Gold Medal]] for poetry in 1831,<ref>{{cite book|title=A Complete Collection of the English Poems which Have Obtained the Chancellor's Gold Medal in the University of Cambridge|publisher=MacMillan & Co|location=London|url=https://archive.org/details/acompletecollec00cambgoog|author= |format=PDF|year=1859|accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref> and was a [[Cambridge Apostle]] from 1832.<ref>[http://www.modern-humanities.info/groups/apostles.htm The Apostles<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{dead link|date=April 2020}}</ref> He became a Fellow of Jesus College.\n\nHe was [[called to the Bar]] at the [[Inner Temple]] in 1836, and was in practice for over 40 years. He also wrote much journalism from the mid-1850s, as a leader writer for ''[[The Times]]'' and the ''[[Saturday Review (London)|Saturday Review]]''.<ref name = \"Carroll\">David Carroll, ''George Eliot: The Critical Heritage'' (1995), p. 224.</ref>\n\nHis literary connections included time at Charterhouse with [[William Makepeace Thackeray]] (they fought); the character George Warrington in ''[[Pendennis]]'' is said to be based on Venables.<ref name = Carroll/><ref>[http://www.online-literature.com/anthony-trollope/thackeray/1/ In [[Anthony Trollope]]'s biography (online)].</ref> A friendship with [[Alfred, Lord Tennyson]] arose from Cambridge days.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://carlyleletters.dukejournals.org/cgi/content/full/12/1/lt-18401209-TC-WDC-01 |title=The Carlyle Letters Online<!-- Bot generated title --> |accessdate=28 October 2007 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110721213342/http://carlyleletters.dukejournals.org/cgi/content/full/12/1/lt-18401209-TC-WDC-01 |archivedate=21 July 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> He wrote an anonymous book of verse ''Joint Compositions'' (1848) with [[Henry Lushington]]. He was an early and favourable reviewer of [[Thomas Carlyle]], another friend.<ref>Jules Paul Seigel, ''Thomas Carlyle: The Critical Heritage'' (1995), p. 467.</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==References==\n*''Concise Dictionary of National Biography''\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Venables, George Stovin}}\n[[Category:1810 births]]\n[[Category:1888 deaths]]\n[[Category:People educated at Eton College]]\n[[Category:People educated at Charterhouse School]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Jesus College, Cambridge]]\n[[Category:Fellows of Jesus College, Cambridge]]\n[[Category:Members of the Inner Temple]]\n[[Category:Welsh barristers]]\n[[Category:British male journalists]]\n[[Category:19th-century journalists]]\n[[Category:Male journalists]]\n[[Category:19th-century British male writers]]\n\n\n{{UK-law-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/George_Stovin_Venables"}
{"title_page": "George Stone (politician)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=September 2016}}\n'''George Stone''' (1907\u20132001) was a [[British people|British]] [[socialist]] [[journalist]].\n\nBorn in [[Fulham]],<ref name=\"obit\">Harry Conroy, \"[http://www.heraldscotland.com/sport/spl/aberdeen/george-stone-1.195769 George Stone]\", ''[[Glasgow Herald]]'', 9 March 2001</ref> Stone studied at the [[London School of Economics]]<ref name=\"times\">''The Times House of Commons 1955'', p.213</ref> and joined the [[Independent Labour Party]] (ILP).  During [[World War II]], he worked for the [[Aeronautical Inspection Department]], and he subsequently moved to [[Glasgow]].<ref name=\"obit\" />  In 1947, he became joint editor with [[Frank Ridley]] of the party's weekly newspaper, the ''[[Socialist Leader]]'' and, when Ridley resigned the following year, he continued as sole editor.<ref>David H. Tribe, ''100 Years of Freethought'', p.166</ref>\n\nStone stood for the ILP in [[Glasgow Bridgeton (UK Parliament constituency)|Glasgow Bridgeton]] at the [[1955 United Kingdom general election|1955 general election]], taking only 7.4% of the vote in a seat the party had held until 1947.<ref name=\"times\" />  He stood again at the [[1961 Glasgow Bridgeton by-election]], his vote declining further to only 3.1%.<ref>[http://www.by-elections.co.uk/61.html 1961 By Elections] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120325000000/http://www.by-elections.co.uk/61.html |date=25 March 2012 }}</ref>  By this point, he was also Chairman of the Scottish Divisional Council of the ILP.<ref>\"I.L.P. May Contest Bridgeton\", ''[[Glasgow Herald]]'', 7 June 1961, p.7</ref>  Soon afterwards, he began working as a sub-editor with the ''[[Glasgow Herald]]'', quickly becoming Father of the Chapel of the [[National Union of Journalists]] (NUJ).  In 1966, he was appointed as the full-time NUJ official for Scotland and Northern England, serving until 1975.<ref name=\"obit\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-media}}\n{{succession box\n  | title  = Editor of the ''[[Labour Leader|Socialist Leader]]''<br/><small>with [[Frank Ridley]], 1947\u20131948</small>\n  | years  = 1947\u20131960\n  | before = [[Fenner Brockway]]\n  | after  = Wilfred Wigham\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Stone, George}}\n[[Category:1907 births]]\n[[Category:2001 deaths]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the London School of Economics]]\n[[Category:British male journalists]]\n[[Category:British newspaper editors]]\n[[Category:British trade unionists]]\n[[Category:Independent Labour Party National Administrative Committee members]]\n[[Category:People from Fulham]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=September 2016}}\n'''George Stone''' (1907\u20132001) was a [[British people|British]] [[socialist]] [[journalist]].\n\nBorn in [[Fulham]],<ref name=\"obit\">Harry Conroy, \"[http://www.heraldscotland.com/sport/spl/aberdeen/george-stone-1.195769 George Stone]\", ''[[Glasgow Herald]]'', 9 March 2001</ref> Stone studied at the [[London School of Economics]]<ref name=\"times\">''The Times House of Commons 1955'', p.213</ref> and joined the [[Independent Labour Party]] (ILP).  During [[World War II]], he worked for the [[Aeronautical Inspection Department]], and he subsequently moved to [[Glasgow]].<ref name=\"obit\" />  In 1947, he became joint editor with [[Frank Ridley]] of the party's weekly newspaper, the ''[[Socialist Leader]]'' and, when Ridley resigned the following year, he continued as sole editor.<ref>David H. Tribe, ''100 Years of Freethought'', p.166</ref>\n\nStone stood for the ILP in [[Glasgow Bridgeton (UK Parliament constituency)|Glasgow Bridgeton]] at the [[1955 United Kingdom general election|1955 general election]], taking only 7.4% of the vote in a seat the party had held until 1947.<ref name=\"times\" />  He stood again at the [[1961 Glasgow Bridgeton by-election]], his vote declining further to only 3.1%.<ref>[http://www.by-elections.co.uk/61.html 1961 By Elections] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120325000000/http://www.by-elections.co.uk/61.html |date=25 March 2012 }}</ref>  By this point, he was also Chairman of the Scottish Divisional Council of the ILP.<ref>\"I.L.P. May Contest Bridgeton\", ''[[Glasgow Herald]]'', 7 June 1961, p.7</ref>  Soon afterwards, he began working as a sub-editor with the ''[[Glasgow Herald]]'', quickly becoming Father of the Chapel of the [[National Union of Journalists]] (NUJ).  In 1966, he was appointed as the full-time NUJ official for Scotland and Northern England, serving until 1975.<ref name=\"obit\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-media}}\n{{succession box\n  | title  = Editor of the ''[[Labour Leader|Socialist Leader]]''<br/><small>with [[Frank Ridley]], 1947\u20131948</small>\n  | years  = 1947\u20131960\n  | before = [[Fenner Brockway]]\n  | after  = Wilfred Wigham\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Stone, George}}\n[[Category:1907 births]]\n[[Category:2001 deaths]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the London School of Economics]]\n[[Category:British male journalists]]\n[[Category:British newspaper editors]]\n[[Category:British trade unionists]]\n[[Category:Independent Labour Party National Administrative Committee members]]\n[[Category:People from Fulham]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/George_Stone_(politician)"}
{"title_page": "Milo\u0161 Zeman", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2016}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = Milo\u0161 Zeman\n| image = Zeman_M_1.JPG\n| office = [[President of the Czech Republic]]\n| primeminister = [[Petr Ne\u010das]]<br />[[Ji\u0159\u00ed Rusnok]]<br />[[Bohuslav Sobotka]]<br />[[Andrej Babi\u0161]]\n| term_start = 8 March 2013\n| term_end = \n| predecessor = [[V\u00e1clav Klaus]]\n| successor = \n| office1 = 3rd [[Prime Minister of the Czech Republic]]\n| president1 = [[V\u00e1clav Havel]]\n| term_start1 = 22 July 1998\n| term_end1 = 15 July 2002\n| predecessor1 = [[Josef To\u0161ovsk\u00fd]]\n| successor1 = [[Vladim\u00edr \u0160pidla]]\n| office2 = 2nd [[Speaker of the Chamber of Deputies (Czech Republic)|Speaker of the Chamber of Deputies]]\n| president2 = [[V\u00e1clav Havel]]\n| term_start2 = 27 June 1996\n| term_end2 = 17 July 1998\n| predecessor2 = [[Milan Uhde]]\n| successor2 = [[V\u00e1clav Klaus]]\n| office3 = Leader of the [[Czech Social Democratic Party|Social Democratic Party]]\n| term_start3 = 28 February 1993\n| term_end3 = 7 April 2001\n| predecessor3 = [[Ji\u0159\u00ed Hor\u00e1k]]\n| successor3 = [[Vladim\u00edr \u0160pidla]]\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1944|9|28}}\n| birth_place = [[Kol\u00edn]], [[Protectorate of Bohemia and Moravia]]<br />{{small|(now [[Czech Republic]])}}\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| spouse = Blanka Zemanov\u00e1  <br />{{small|(1971\u20131978, divorced)}}<br />[[Ivana Zemanov\u00e1|Ivana Bednar\u010d\u00edkov\u00e1]] <br />{{small|(1993\u2013present)}}\n| children = David<br />Kate\u0159ina\n| party = [[Communist Party of Czechoslovakia|Communist Party]] <br />{{small|(1968\u20131970)}}<br />[[Civic Forum]] <br />{{small|(1990\u20131991)}}<br />[[Civic Movement]] <br />{{small|(1991\u20131992)}}<br />[[Czech Social Democratic Party|Social Democratic Party]] <br />{{small|(1992\u20132007)}}<br />[[Party of Civic Rights]] <br />{{small|(2009\u20132013)}}<br />[[Independent politician|Independent]] <br />{{small|(2013\u2013present)}}\n| alma_mater = [[University of Economics, Prague]]\n| website = {{url|zemanmilos.cz|Official website}}\n| signature = Milo\u0161 Zeman Signature black.png\n}}\n'''Milo\u0161 Zeman''' ({{IPA-cs|\u02c8m\u026alo\u0283 \u02c8z\u025bman|-|Cs-Milos Zeman.ogg}}; born 28 September 1944) is a Czech politician serving as the [[List of Presidents of the Czech Republic|third]] and current [[President of the Czech Republic]] since 8 March 2013. He previously served as [[Prime Minister of the Czech Republic]] from 1998 to 2002. As Leader of the [[Czech Social Democratic Party]] during the 1990s, he transformed his party into one of the country's major political forces. Zeman was [[Speaker of the Chamber of Deputies (Czech Republic)|Speaker of the Chamber of Deputies]], the lower house of the [[Parliament of the Czech Republic|Czech parliament]], from 1996 until he became Prime Minister two years later in 1998. \n\nIn January 2013, Zeman was [[2013 Czech presidential election|elected]] President of the Czech Republic. He is the first directly elected President in Czech history; both of his predecessors, [[V\u00e1clav Havel]] and [[V\u00e1clav Klaus]], were elected by the [[Parliament of the Czech Republic|Czech Parliament]]. In 2018, he was [[2018 Czech presidential election|re-elected]] for a second term. HIS FAVORITE WORD IS: BECHEROVKA. And he also drinks so much that he can\u00b4t walk huh\n\n==Early years==\nZeman was born in [[Kol\u00edn]].<ref name=\"novinky\"/> His parents divorced when he was two years old and he was raised by his mother, who was a teacher.<ref name=\"novinky\"/><ref name=\"horakova\">{{cite news |last1=Hor\u00e1kov\u00e1 |first1=Pavla |title=Milos Zeman - Outgoing Prime Minister |url=https://www.radio.cz/en/section/czechstoday/milos-zeman-outgoing-prime-minister |accessdate=30 August 2018 |work=Radio Prague |date=19 June 2002}}</ref> He studied at a high school in Kol\u00edn, then from 1965 he studied at the [[University of Economics, Prague|University of Economics in Prague]], graduating in 1969.<ref name=\"novinky\">{{cite web |url= http://tema.novinky.cz/milos-zeman |title=Milo\u0161 Zeman |publisher=novinky.cz |language=cs |accessdate=27 January 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn 1968, during the [[Prague Spring]],<ref name=\"horakova\"/> he became a member of the [[Communist Party of Czechoslovakia]], but was expelled in 1970 due to his opposition to the [[Warsaw Pact invasion of Czechoslovakia]].<ref name=\"horakova\"/><ref name = MF >{{cite web |url= http://zpravy.idnes.cz/on-line-chat-milos-zeman-0sh-/domaci.aspx?c=A130102_150857_domaci_jw|title=Neud\u011bloval bych ani milosti, ani amnestie, napsal \u010dten\u00e1\u0159\u016fm Zeman |last=Wirnitzer |first=Jan |date=3 January 2013 |work=[[Mlad\u00e1 fronta DNES]] |language=cs |accessdate=27 January 2013 |quotation=Milo\u0161 Zeman byl \u010dlenem KS\u010c v letech 1968-1970. \"Je\u0161t\u011b kr\u00e1tce po okupaci byla nad\u011bje, \u017ee demokratiza\u010dn\u00ed proces v tehdej\u0161\u00edm \u010ceskoslovensku bude pokra\u010dovat. Tato nad\u011bje vyhasla a\u017e pr\u00e1v\u011b v roce 1970,\" vysv\u011btlil to politik, '''kter\u00e9ho vylou\u010dili pr\u00e1v\u011b pro nesouhlas s okupac\u00ed'''.}}</ref> He was dismissed from his job and spent more than ten years working for the sports organisation Sportpropag (1971\u201384).<ref name=\"mladiMZ\">{{cite web |first=Marcela |last=Jurkov\u00e1 |url= http://zpravy.ihned.cz/politika/c1-59177640-zeman-kandidat-prezident |title=Profil mlad\u00e9ho Zemana: Inteligentn\u00ed samot\u00e1\u0159, kter\u00fd se v\u017edy r\u00e1d poslouchal |trans-title=Profile of the young Zeman: an intelligent loner, who always liked to listen |work=Hospod\u00e1\u0159sk\u00e9 noviny |accessdate=4 May 2017 |date=24 January 2013}}</ref> From 1984, he worked at the company Agrodat, but he lost his job again in 1989, as a result of a critical article he had written in ''Technick\u00fd'' magazine in August 1989, entitled \"Prognostika a p\u0159estavba\" (Forecasting and Perestroika).<ref name=\"novinky\"/><ref>{{cite web |url= http://aktualne.centrum.cz/domaci/clanek.phtml?id=653326 |title=Byl mu\u017eem revoluce. 20 let pot\u00e9 Zemana nikam nepozvali |publisher=Aktu\u00e1ln\u011b.cz |language=cs}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://milos.chytrak.cz/1989/zeman-tm.php |first=Milo\u0161 |last=Zeman |title=Prognostika a p\u0159estavba |work=Technick\u00fd magaz\u00edn |date=August 1989 |access-date=24 April 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070206065008/http://milos.chytrak.cz/1989/zeman-tm.php |archive-date=6 February 2007 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Political activities before presidency==\nIn summer 1989, he appeared on [[Czechoslovak Television]] criticising the poor state of the Czechoslovak economy. His speech caused a scandal, but his views helped him join the leaders of the [[Civic Forum]] a few months later, during the [[Velvet Revolution]].<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.ceskatelevize.cz/ct24/exkluzivne-na-ct24/62717-jisty-prognostik-si-dovolil-kritizovat-komunisticke-hospodarstvi/ |title=\"Jist\u00fd prognostik\" si dovolil kritizovat komunistick\u00e9 hospod\u00e1\u0159stv\u00ed |date=3 August 2010 |publisher=[[\u010cesk\u00e1 televize]] |language=cs |accessdate=27 January 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn 1990 Zeman became a member of the House of the Nations of the Czechoslovak [[Federal Assembly (Czechoslovakia)|Federal Assembly]]. In 1992, he ran successfully for the House of the People of the Federal Assembly, already as a member of the [[Czech Social Democratic Party|Czechoslovak Social Democracy]] (\u010cSSD), which he joined the same year. In 1993, he was elected chairman of the party,<ref name=\"novinky\"/> and in the following years he transformed it into one of the country's major parties.\n\nThe success of \u010cSSD in the [[1996 Czech legislative election|1996 legislative election]] allowed him to prevent his rival [[V\u00e1clav Klaus]] and his [[Civic Democratic Party (Czech Republic)|Civic Democratic Party]] (ODS) from forming a [[majority government]]. Zeman became the [[Speaker of the Chamber of Deputies (Czech Republic)|Speaker of the Chamber of Deputies]] and held this post until the [[1998 Czech legislative election|early election in 1998]].\n\nIn 1998, \u010cSSD won the election and Zeman became [[Prime Minister of the Czech Republic|Prime Minister]] of a [[minority government]], which he led for the next four years. In April 2001, he was replaced as leader by [[Vladim\u00edr \u0160pidla]].<ref>{{cite web |url= http://tema.novinky.cz/milos-zeman |title=Milo\u0161 Zeman |publisher=[[novinky.cz]] |accessdate=22 January 2013 |language=cs}}</ref> Zeman then retired and moved to live in the countryside in the [[Vyso\u010dina Region]]. He won [[Czech Social Democratic Party presidential primaries, 2002|a presidential primary in 2002]] to become the \u010cSSD nominee for president, but lost the [[2003 Czech presidential election|2003 presidential election]] to [[V\u00e1clav Klaus]], due to party disunity. Zeman became an outspoken critic of his former party's leaders. He left \u010cSSD on 21 March 2007, due to conflicts with the party leader and chairman, [[Ji\u0159\u00ed Paroubek]].<ref>{{cite web |url= http://zpravy.ihned.cz/cesko/c1-20717420-zeman-ukoncil-clenstvi-v-cssd-kvuli-kauze-altner |title=Zeman ukon\u010dil \u010dlenstv\u00ed v \u010cSSD kv\u016fli kauze Altner |date=21 March 2007 |work=[[Hospod\u00e1\u0159sk\u00e9 noviny]] |language=cs |accessdate=31 January 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2009, he founded a new party, [[Party of Civic Rights \u2013 Zemanovci]].<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.lidovky.cz/zeman-miri-zpatky-do-politiky-ve-volbach-nastoupi-proti-paroubkovi-114-/zpravy-domov.aspx?c=A091231_105142_ln_domov_tai |title=Zeman m\u00ed\u0159\u00ed zp\u00e1tky do politiky. Ve volb\u00e1ch nastoup\u00ed proti Paroubkovi |date=31 December 2009 |work=[[Lidov\u00e9 noviny]] |language=cs |accessdate=31 January 2013}}</ref> The party did not win any seats in the [[2010 Czech legislative election|2010]], [[2013 Czech legislative election|2013]] or [[2017 Czech legislative election|2017]] legislative elections.\n\n==Presidency==\n{{See also|2013 Czech presidential election||2018 Czech presidential election}}\n[[File:Milo\u0161 Zeman Senate of Poland.JPG|thumb|Zeman in the [[Senate of Poland]], 24 May 2013]]\nIn February 2012 Milo\u0161 Zeman announced his return to politics and intention to run in the [[2013 Czech presidential election|first direct presidential election in the Czech Republic]].<ref>{{cite web |url= http://aktualne.centrum.cz/domaci/politika/clanek.phtml?id=733055 |title=Milo\u0161 Zeman: Se\u017ee\u0148te podpisy a pokus\u00edm se znovu o Hrad |date=14 February 2012 |publisher=aktu\u00e1ln\u011b.cz |language=cs |accessdate=22 January 2013}}</ref> Polls indicated that he was one of the two strongest candidates in the election, alongside [[Jan Fischer (politician)|Jan Fischer]].<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.ceskenoviny.cz/news/zpravy/fischer-zeman-favourites-of-czech-presidential-election-poll/833014 |title=Fischer, Zeman favourites of Czech presidential election \u2013 poll |date=27 August 2012 |publisher=[[\u010cTK]] |accessdate=30 December 2012}}</ref> Zeman narrowly won the first round of the elections and progressed to the second round to face [[Karel Schwarzenberg]], winning by a clearer margin.<ref>{{cite web |last=Wirnitzer |first=Jan |title=Rozhodnuto. Zeman vyhr\u00e1l, nezm\u011bn\u00ed to u\u017e ani velk\u00e1 m\u011bsta |url= http://zpravy.idnes.cz/volba-prezidenta-0ej-/domaci.aspx?c=A130126_130102_domaci_jw |work=Mlad\u00e1 fronta DNES |accessdate=26 January 2013}}</ref> His term began in March 2013.\n\nZeman's alleged excessive alcohol consumption became a subject of public discussion and media attention on several occasions. Many Czechs believed he was drunk during his appearances at [[Czech TV]] headquarters, shortly after his victory in the 2013 presidential election, and during the exhibition of the [[Bohemian Crown Jewels]].<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/worldviews/wp/2013/05/13/video-of-czech-president-staggering-through-ceremony-has-many-wondering-if-he-was-drunk/ |title=Video of Czech president staggering through ceremony has many wondering if he was drunk |last=Fisher |first=Max |date=13 May 2013 |work=[[The Washington Post]] |accessdate=28 May 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2013, Zeman refused to grant a tenured professorship to [[literary historian]] [[Martin C. Putna]], due to Putna's appearance at 2011 Prague [[Pride parade|Gay Pride]].<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.ibtimes.co.uk/articles/469206/20130520/zeman-putna-czech-gay-university.htm |title=Czech Gay Pride Row Flares over President Milos Zeman's Snub of University Appointment |last=Bacchi |first=Umberto |date=20 May 2013 |work=[[International Business Times]] |accessdate=31 May 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2013, the [[Petr Ne\u010das' Cabinet|coalition government]] led by [[Petr Ne\u010das]] collapsed due to a [[2013 Czech political corruption scandal|corruption and spying scandal]]. Zeman, ignoring the political balance of power in the [[Czech Parliament]], appointed his friend and long-term ally [[Ji\u0159\u00ed Rusnok]] as [[Prime Minister of the Czech Republic|Prime Minister]], and tasked him with forming a [[Ji\u0159\u00ed Rusnok's Cabinet|new government]]. This was described in parts of the Czech and foreign media as a political power grab, undermining [[parliamentary democracy]] and expanding his powers.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.reuters.com/article/2013/07/08/us-czech-zeman-idUSBRE9670NT20130708 |title=Czech president angers parties with power grab |last=Lopatka |first=Jan |date=8 July 2013 |agency=[[Reuters]] |accessdate=22 July 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-23258228|title=Jiri Rusnok, new Czech PM, faces instant opposition |last=Cameron |first=Rob |date=10 July 2013 |publisher=[[BBC News]] |accessdate=22 July 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.nytimes.com/2013/07/11/world/europe/czech-president-swears-in-government-led-by-ally.html?ref=miloszeman&_r=0 |title=Czech Leader Swears in Interim Government |last=Bilefsky |first=Dan |date=10 July 2013 |work=[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=23 July 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.economist.com/blogs/easternapproaches/2013/06/czech-politics-2 |title=Zeman's coup |date=26 June 2013 |publisher=[[The Economist]] |accessdate=21 November 2013}}</ref> On 10 July, during the appointment of Rusnok's cabinet, Zeman advised the new cabinet members not to \"let yourself get annoyed by media criticism from jealous fools who have never in their lives done anything useful\".<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.lidovky.cz/nenechte-se-otravit-zavistivymi-hlupaky-popral-zeman-nove-vlade-ph5-/zpravy-domov.aspx?c=A130710_114000_ln_domov_khu |title=Nenechte se otr\u00e1vit z\u00e1vistiv\u00fdmi hlup\u00e1ky, pop\u0159\u00e1l Zeman nov\u00e9 vl\u00e1d\u011b |date=10 July 2013 |work=Lidov\u00e9 noviny |language=cs |accessdate=22 July 2013}} (''\"Nenechte se otr\u00e1vit medi\u00e1ln\u00ed kritikou z\u00e1vistiv\u00fdch hlup\u00e1k\u016f, kte\u0159\u00ed nikdy nic sami nedok\u00e1zali\"'')</ref> Rusnok's government was short-lived, and resigned after losing a vote of confidence.\n\nZeman played an important role in a scandal that occurred in October 2013, shortly after the [[2013 Czech legislative election|Czech legislative election]]. \u010cSSD First Deputy Chairman [[Michal Ha\u0161ek]] and his allies in the party called for chairman [[Bohuslav Sobotka]] to resign following the party's poor election result, and excluded him from the team negotiating the next government. However, it subsequently emerged that Ha\u0161ek and his allies had attended a secret post-election meeting with Zeman, where they were rumoured to have negotiated a 'coup' in \u010cSSD. Ha\u0161ek initially denied the accusations, stating on [[\u010cesk\u00e1 televize|Czech Television]] that \"there was no meeting\". However, his allies (deputies [[Milan Chovanec]], [[Zden\u011bk \u0160kromach]], Jeron\u00fdm Tejc and Ji\u0159\u00ed Zimola) later admitted that the meeting took place. The event sparked public protests in the country and eventually led to Ha\u0161ek apologising and resigning his position in the party.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.ceskenoviny.cz/zpravy/sobotka-s-rival-hasek-leaves-czech-social-democrat-leadership/1005734 |title=Sobotka's rival Hasek leaves Czech Social Democrat leadership |date=8 November 2013 |work=[[\u010cTK]] |publisher=\u010cesk\u00e9 noviny |accessdate=21 November 2013}}</ref> Zeman denied having initiated the meeting. His [[Party of Civic Rights \u2013 Zemanovci]] (SPOZ) received 1.5% of the vote in the election, winning no seats.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.volby.cz/pls/ps2013/ps2?xjazyk=CZ |title=Celkov\u00e9 v\u00fdsledky hlasov\u00e1n\u00ed - volby.cz |website=www.volby.cz}}</ref>\n\nOn 6 April 2014, in the wake of the [[Annexation of Crimea by the Russian Federation|annexation of Crimea]], Zeman called for strong action to be taken, possibly including sending [[NATO]] forces into Ukraine, if Russia tried to annex the eastern part of the country. Speaking on a radio show he said that, \"The moment Russia decides to widen its territorial expansion to the eastern part of Ukraine, that is where the fun ends. There I would plead not only for the strictest EU [[Economic sanctions|sanctions]], but even for military readiness of the [[North Atlantic Alliance]], like for example NATO forces entering Ukrainian territory.\" The Czech Republic has been a NATO member since 1999, when Zeman was prime minister. In the Czech constitutional system it is the government that has the main responsibility for foreign policy, although the President is commander-in-chief of the armed forces. The [[Czech Social Democratic Party|\u010cSSD]] government of [[Bohuslav Sobotka]] resisted strong EU sanctions against Russia after the annexation, because of the negative economic impact such sanctions would have had on the country.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.reuters.com/article/2014/04/06/us-ukraine-crisis-nato-czech-idUSBREA350LY20140406 |title=Czech leader says NATO could offer troops to Ukraine if Russia goes beyond Crimea |date=6 April 2014 |agency=Reuters}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Demonstrace za slu\u0161n\u00e9 \u010cesko \u2013 demise Andreje Babi\u0161e 2.jpg|thumb|Protest against Zeman in [[Prague]], 17 November 2018]] \nIn November 2014, while Czechs celebrated the 25th anniversary of the 1989 [[Velvet Revolution]] against the Soviet-style communist regime, the festivities turned into an appeal for Zeman to resign. Many Czechs believe that Milo\u0161 Zeman has betrayed the legacy of [[V\u00e1clav Havel]] who helped Czechoslovakia and then Czech Republic become a champion of [[human rights]]. Protesters see Zeman as too sympathetic to [[Democracy Index#Democracy Index by country|authoritarian regimes]] and too close to [[Human rights in Russia|Russia]] and [[Human rights in China|China]]. They carried football-style [[Penalty card#Red card|red penalty cards]] as a warning of [[Ejection (sports)|ejection]] to Zeman and pelted eggs at him.<ref name=\"BBC20141117\">{{cite news |url= https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-30086495 |title=Czech president pelted with eggs on revolution anniversary |work=BBC News |date=17 November 2014 |accessdate=}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.dw.com/en/czechs-honor-velvet-revolution-tell-president-zeman-to-resign/a-18069749 |title=Czechs honor Velvet Revolution, tell President Zeman to resign |publisher=[[Deutsche Welle]] |date=17 November 2014 |accessdate=}}</ref>\n\nAn opinion poll conducted by the CVVM agency in March 2016 reported that 62% of Czechs trusted President Milo\u0161 Zeman,<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.praguemonitor.com/2016/03/30/poll-zeman-trusted-record-62-czechs |title=Poll: Zeman trusted by record 62% of Czechs |work=Prague Daily Monitor |date=30 March 2016 |accessdate=}}</ref> up from 55% in September 2015.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.radio.cz/en/section/news/poll-55-percent-express-trust-in-president |title=Poll: 55 percent express trust in president |publisher=[[Radio Prague]] |date=25 September 2015 |accessdate=}}</ref> By December 2016, his approval rating had fallen to 48% following a series of scandals, with around 49% of those surveyed stating that they didn't trust him.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.radio.cz/en/section/curraffrs/trust-in-president-falls-amid-series-of-scandals |title=Trust in president falls amid series of scandals |first=Jan |last=Velinger |publisher=Radio Prague |date=6 December 2016 |accessdate=1 January 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn 9 March 2017, during a meeting with his supporters, Zeman announced his intention to run again for the presidency,<ref>{{cite web |title=Budu znovu kandidovat, ozn\u00e1mil Zeman sv\u00fdm v\u011brn\u00fdm na Hrad\u011b |url= https://www.novinky.cz/domaci/431678-budu-znovu-kandidovat-oznamil-zeman-svym-vernym-na-hrade.html |website=Novinky.cz |accessdate=9 March 2017 |language=cs}}</ref> confirming his decision the next day in a press conference. He said that he had been persuaded by the support of the people. He stated that he does not think he is the favourite in the election, and that he won't run a political campaign, attack his rivals, or participate in debates.<ref>{{cite web |title=Nec\u00edt\u00edm se jako favorit, \u0159ekl Zeman p\u0159i ozn\u00e1men\u00ed kandidatury |url= https://www.novinky.cz/domaci/431710-necitim-se-jako-favorit-rekl-zeman-pri-oznameni-kandidatury.html |website=Novinky.cz |accessdate=10 March 2017 |language=cs}}</ref> He also announced that he would participate in a television programme called ''A week with the President''.<ref>{{cite web |title=P\u0159esv\u011bd\u010dila m\u011b podpora lid\u00ed, \u0159ekl Zeman. Debat\u00e1m s protivn\u00edky se vyhne |url= http://zpravy.idnes.cz/zeman-kandidatura-prima-volba-prezidenta-2018-fe9-/domaci.aspx?c=A170310_095350_domaci_hro |website=iDNES.cz |accessdate=10 March 2017 |date=10 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn 26 March 2017, during a radio interview, Zeman stated that someone had placed [[child pornography]] onto a computer in the official residence. Zeman claimed that he had called \"IT guys\", who had found out that the hackers were from [[Alabama]] in the [[United States]].<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.seznam.cz/zpravy/clanek/prezident-zeman-nasel-detske-porno-ve-svem-pocitaci-jak-se-to-mohlo-stat-29418 |title=Prezident Zeman na\u0161el d\u011btsk\u00e9 porno ve sv\u00e9m po\u010d\u00edta\u010di. Jak se to mohlo st\u00e1t? |language=cs}}</ref> Later, Zeman's spokesman added that \"the President, like every night, googled his own name on the internet and one of the pages contained child pornography\".<ref>{{cite web |url= https://zpravy.aktualne.cz/domaci/zahada-porna-v-prezidentove-pocitaci-milos-zeman-si-googlova/r~989c992e187511e7a4bd0025900fea04/ |title=Zeman si jako ka\u017ed\u00fd ve\u010der hledal \"Milo\u0161 Zeman\", vysv\u011btluje Hrad pornografii v prezidentov\u011b po\u010d\u00edta\u010di |language=cs}}</ref> According to police, there was no evidence of a hacking attack on Zeman's computer.<ref name=\"pdm050417\">{{cite news |title=No unlawful conduct in attack on Zeman's computer, police say |url= http://praguemonitor.com/2017/04/04/no-unlawful-conduct-attack-zemans-computer-police-say |accessdate=5 April 2017 |work=Prague Daily Monitor |date=3 April 2017}}</ref>\n\nZeman decided to run for a second term and stood in the [[2018 Czech presidential election|presidential elections in 2018]]. Observers compared the election to other elections such as the [[2016 United States presidential election|2016 United States]] and [[2017 French presidential election|2017 French]] presidential elections, which saw a [[Liberal internationalism|liberal internationalist]] and a [[right-wing populist]] running against each other.<ref name=\"Prague'sTurn\"/><ref>{{cite web |last=McKenzie |first=Sheena |title=Why the Czech Presidential Election is One to Watch |url= https://www.cnn.com/2018/01/26/europe/why-czech-presidential-election-matters-intl/index.html |date=26 January 2018 |publisher=[[CNN]] |accessdate=27 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Czech Presidential Election Headed for Tight Run-Off Vote -Poll |url= https://www.reuters.com/article/us-czech-election-president-poll/czech-presidential-election-headed-for-tight-run-off-vote-poll-idUSKBN1FA0P2 |date=21 January 2018 |publisher=[[Reuters]] |accessdate=27 January 2018 |quote=The Jan. 26-27 second round echoes other elections in the past two years across the European Union as well as U.S. President Donald Trump\u2019s battle with former Secretary of State Hillary Clinton for the White House in 2016.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Cameron |first=Rob |title=Czech Election: Milos Zeman Wins the Battle of Ideas |url= https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-42848835 |date=27 January 2018 |publisher=BBC News |accessdate=27 January 2018}}</ref> Zeman won the election with 51.37% in the second round.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://zpravy.aktualne.cz/domaci/zeman-posbiral-pro-opetovnou-kandidaturu-na-prezidenta-uz-59/r~936aa014827d11e7b1a4002590604f2e/ |title=Zeman m\u016f\u017ee znovu kandidovat. Jeho t\u00fdm posb\u00edral u\u017e p\u0159es 59 tis\u00edc podpis\u016f |work=Aktu\u00e1ln\u011b.cz |language=cs |date=16 August 2017 |accessdate=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= https://volby.idnes.cz/prezidentske-volby-2018.aspx?k=vysledky-druhe-kolo&t=8&o=7&kandidat=milos-zeman |title=V\u00fdsledky Milo\u0161e Zemana |publisher=Idnes.cz |date=27 January 2018 |accessdate=27 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url= https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/jan/27/czech-president-milos-zeman-wins-second-term |title=Czech president Milo\u0161 Zeman wins second five-year term |last=Prague |first=Associated Press in |date=27 January 2018 |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |publisher=Guardian Media Group |accessdate=31 January 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Political views==\nDuring his premiership and term as leader of the Social Democrats, Zeman was considered a center-left politician, but during his time as president he began to be associated with [[far-right]] [[anti-immigration]] policies in response to the [[European migrant crisis]].<ref name=\"MullerHovet2018\">{{cite web |last1=Muller |first1=Robert |last2=Hovet |first2=Jason |title=Czech President Zeman Re-Elected With Anti-Immigration Message |url= https://www.reuters.com/article/us-czech-election-president/czech-president-zeman-re-elected-with-anti-immigration-message-idUSKBN1FG00C |date=26 January 2018 |publisher=[[Reuters]] |accessdate=27 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Czech Presidential Election Headed for Tight Run-Off Vote -Poll |url= https://www.reuters.com/article/us-czech-election-president-poll/czech-presidential-election-headed-for-tight-run-off-vote-poll-idUSKBN1FA0P2 |date=21 January 2018 |publisher=[[Reuters]] |accessdate=27 January 2018}}</ref> ''[[The Guardian]]'' described Zeman as \"left-of-centre\" in the run-up to the 2013 presidential election,<ref>{{cite news |title=Vladimir Franz: tattooed composer polling strongly in the Czech elections |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2013/jan/09/vladimir-franz-tattooed-czech-elections |accessdate=16 November 2019 |work=The Guardian |date=9 Jan 2013}}</ref> but as \"far-right\" and a [[populism|populist]] in 2018.<ref>{{cite news |last=Tait |first=Robert |title=Czech Republic Re-Elects Far-Right President Milo\u0161 Zeman |url= https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/jan/27/czech-republic-far-right-president-reelected |date=27 January 2018 |newspaper=The Guardian |publisher=Guardian Media Group |accessdate=27 January 2018}}</ref> ''[[The New York Times]]'' described Zeman as a \"populist leftist\".<ref name=BilefskyInfluential>{{cite news |last=Bilefsky |first=Dan |title=Czech Man Is Charged With Attempted Terrorism |url= https://www.nytimes.com/2016/08/03/world/europe/czech-man-attempted-terrorism.html?ref=world |accessdate=3 August 2016 |newspaper=The New York Times |date=2 August 2016}}</ref> Other outlets have simply labeled Zeman a populist.<ref name=\"Prague'sTurn\">{{cite web |last=Mortkowitz |first=Siegfried |title=Prague\u2019s Turn for Populist Vs. Liberal Showdown |url= https://www.politico.eu/article/milos-zeman-jiri-drahos-czech-election-prague-turn-for-populist-vs-liberal-showdown/ |date=26 January 2018 |publisher=[[Politico]] |accessdate=27 January 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"IrishTimes2018\">{{cite newspaper |title=Populist Milo\u0161 Zeman Wins Czech Presidential Election |url= https://www.irishtimes.com/news/world/europe/populist-milo%C5%A1-zeman-wins-czech-presidential-election-1.3371064 |date=27 January 2018 |publisher=[[The Irish Times]] |accessdate=27 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite newspaper |last=Santora |first=Marc |title=Czech Republic Re-elects Milos Zeman, Populist Leader and Foe of Migrants |url= https://www.nytimes.com/2018/01/27/world/europe/czech-election-milos-zeman.html |date=27 January 2018 |newspaper=The New York Times |accessdate=27 January 2018}}</ref> He has been compared to [[United States]] President [[Donald Trump]] and [[List of Donald Trump presidential campaign endorsements, 2016#International political figures|endorsed]] Trump's [[Donald Trump presidential campaign, 2016|2016 presidential campaign]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Janda |first=Jakob |title=Are Czechs about to reelect the Trumpiest president in Europe? |url= https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/democracy-post/wp/2018/01/23/are-czechs-about-to-reelect-the-trumpiest-president-in-europe/ |date=23 January 2018 |newspaper=The Washington Post |accessdate=27 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Muller |first=Robert |title=Trump's Czech Admirer Zeman Weighs Presidential Re-Election Bid |url= https://www.reuters.com/article/us-czech-zeman/trumps-czech-admirer-zeman-weighs-presidential-re-election-bid-idUSKBN16E1VO |date=7 March 2017 |publisher=[[Reuters]] |accessdate=27 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Shaw |first=Adam |title=Pro-Trump Czech President Who Warned of 'Organized Invasion' of Migrants Wins Re-Election |url= http://www.foxnews.com/world/2018/01/27/pro-trump-czech-president-who-warned-organized-invasion-migrants-wins-re-election.html |date=27 January 2018 |publisher=[[Fox News]] |accessdate=27 January 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"HowEuroTrump\">{{cite web |last=Mortkowitz |first=Siegfried |title=How (the European) Trump Won a Second Term |url= https://www.politico.eu/article/milos-zeman-czech-republic-how-the-european-donald-trump-won-a-second-term/ |date=28 January 2018 |publisher=[[Politico]] |accessdate=28 January 2018}}</ref>\n\n===China===\n[[File:2016 Czech Demonstration Against Communist party China & its dictator in Prague with National Flags of TAIWAN & Tibet \u53cd\u4e2d\u793a\u5a01\u8207\u81fa\u7063&\u5716\u535a\u570b\u65d7\u5728\u6377\u514b.jpg|thumb|2016 demonstration against Zeman and China in Prague with picture of late President [[V\u00e1clav Havel]] and Tibetan leader [[14th Dalai Lama]] with flags of [[Tibet]] and [[Taiwan]]]]\nZeman has drawn criticism over his closeness to [[China]]. In 2014, he attracted criticism when he said he wished to learn how China had \"stabilized\" its society.<ref name=\"BBC20141117\"/> In 2016 he invited Chinese president [[Xi Jinping]] on a state visit, which sparked a wave of protest.<ref>[http://www.tibetanreview.net/with-tibetan-flags-opposition-leaders-lead-czech-protest-against-visiting-chinese-president-xi/ With Tibetan flags, opposition leaders lead Czech protest against visiting Chinese President Xi], Tibetan Review, 2016-3-31</ref> He labeled [[Tibetan independence movement|pro-Tibet]] protestors \"mentally impaired individuals\" and used police to prevent protesters from reaching Prague Castle. Police also entered a building of the [[Film and TV School of the Academy of Performing Arts in Prague|Film and TV School of the Academy of Performing Arts]] (FAMU) to remove a Tibetan flag which had been hung out of a window.<ref>[http://lhasadaily.com/opinion/25-views-analysis/886-tibet-symbolism-and-the-czech-republic Tibet, symbolism and the Czech Republic], Tibet Digital Times, 2016-4-28</ref> Deputy [[Finance Minister of the Czech Republic|Finance Minister]] [[Miroslav Kalousek]] accused Zeman of \"bootlicking authoritarian and unfree regimes\".<ref>[http://www.digitaljournal.com/news/world/protests-as-china-s-xi-arrives-in-prague/article/461339 Protests as China's Xi arrives in Prague], Digital Journal, 2016-3-28</ref> Those actions were seen as a contravention of Czech society's [[freedom of expression]], and protests were held by at least 50 members of the two chambers of the [[Parliament of the Czech Republic|Parliament]], opposition leaders and [[civil society]] groups as well as hundreds of supporters of [[Taiwan]], [[Tibet]], and Turkic [[Uyghurs|Uyghur]] separatists in [[Xinjiang]].<ref>[http://www.romea.cz/en/news/world/fifty-legislators-meet-with-the-dalai-lama-in-the-czech-senate-criticize-statement-by-high-officials Fifty legislators meet with the Dalai Lama in the Czech Senate, criticize statement by high officials], [[:cs:ROMEA|ROMEA]], 2016-10-20</ref><ref>[https://www.hongkongfp.com/2016/04/01/czech-opposition-party-leader-flags-up-tibet-during-chinese-leaders-visit/ Czech opposition party leader flags up Tibet during Chinese leader\u2019s visit], [[Hong Kong Free Press]], 2016-4-1</ref><ref>[http://www.thetibetpost.com/en/news/international/4945-hundreds-of-supporters-protest-xis-czech-visit-call-for-free-tibet Hundreds of supporters protest Xi's Czech visit, call for free Tibet], [[Tibet Post International]], 2016-3-30</ref>\n\nZeman has appointed [[Ye Jianming]], the founder and chairman of [[CEFC China Energy]], as his economic adviser.<ref>\"[https://www.reuters.com/article/us-cefc-china/chinas-cefc-has-big-ambitions-but-little-known-about-ownership-funding-idUSKBN14X0B5 China\u2019s CEFC has big ambitions, but little known about ownership, funding]\". Reuters. 13 January 2017.</ref> The company is linked to the [[People's Liberation Army]].<ref>\"[https://www.ft.com/content/e3f8cbd2-983f-11e7-a652-cde3f882dd7b Opaque Chinese oil group makes clear gains in former Soviet bloc]\". ''Financial Times''. 13 September 2017.</ref><ref>\"[http://www.scmp.com/business/companies/article/2072726/whos-39-year-old-paying-hk14-billion-three-office-floors Who\u2019s that 39-year-old paying HK$1.4 billion for three office floors?]\". ''South China Morning Post''. 21 February 2017.</ref> CEFC China Energy has acquired multiple assets in the Czech Republic, including travel agencies and media companies.<ref>\"[https://www.reuters.com/article/czech-china-cefc/update-1-chinas-cefc-adds-to-czech-buying-spree-with-airline-brewery-deals-idUSL5N11B05120150905 China's CEFC adds to Czech buying spree with airline, brewery deals]\". Reuters. 5 September 2015.</ref><ref>\"[https://www.reuters.com/article/us-jtfg-cefc/chinas-cefc-hits-regulatory-hurdle-in-pursuit-of-czech-jtfg-stake-source-idUSKBN1ES1S5 China's CEFC hits regulatory hurdle in pursuit of Czech JTFG stake: source]\". Reuters. 3 January 2018.</ref> Ye was placed under investigation for economic crimes in 2018.<ref>{{cite news|date=1 March 2018|title=China's CEFC chairman investigated for suspected economic crimes: source|first=Benjamin|last=Kang Lim|accessdate=15 August 2018|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-cefc-probe/chinas-cefc-chairman-investigated-for-suspected-economic-crimes-source-idUSKCN1GD3O9|work=Reuters}}</ref><ref>[https://euobserver.com/opinion/141251 The curious case of the Czech president's missing advisor]</ref>\n\n===Gun control===\n{{see also|Gun laws in the Czech Republic}}\n\nIn 2016, following a number of terror attacks around Europe, Zeman joined a number of other Czech politicians and security professionals in urging the 240,000 gun owners in the country with concealed carry licences to carry their firearms, in order to be able to contribute to the protection of [[soft target]]s. Zeman's wife also obtained a concealed carry license and a revolver.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.blesk.cz/clanek/zpravy-politika/410026/ivana-zemanova-uz-ma-revolver-prezident-vyzval-cechy-ke-zbrojeni-proti-teroru.html |title=Ivana Zemanov\u00e1 u\u017e m\u00e1 revolver. Prezident vyzval \u010cechy ke zbrojen\u00ed proti teroru [Ivana Zeman obtained a revolver. President calls Czechs to arm themselves against terrorism] |publisher=Blesk.cz |language=cs |date=31 July 2016 |accessdate=5 March 2017}}</ref>\n\n===European Union===\n{{See also|Euroscepticism in the Czech Republic}}\nZeman has a mixed record on his positions regarding the [[European Union]]. As prime minister, he helped bring the Czech Republic into the EU,<ref name=\"RFERL\">{{cite web |title=Czechs Reelect Populist, Russia-Friendly President In Tight Race |url= https://www.rferl.org/a/czech-zeman-wins-reelection-drahos/29001912.html |date=28 January 2018 |publisher=[[Radio Free Europe/Radio Liberty]] |accessdate=28 January 2018}}</ref> and he has described himself as a \"federalist\" who supports EU membership.<ref name=\"MullerHovet2018\"/><ref name=\"3April2013Reuters\">{{cite web |title=Czech President Raises EU Flag to Signal Change from Klaus Era |url= https://www.reuters.com/article/us-eu-czech/czech-president-raises-eu-flag-to-signal-change-from-klaus-era-idUSBRE9320DK20130403 |date=3 April 2013 |publisher=[[Reuters]] |accessdate=29 January 2018}}</ref> Before becoming president, he promised to fly the [[flag of Europe]] at [[Prague Castle]],<ref>{{cite news |author=B.C. |title=What Kind of President will Milo\u0161 Zeman Be? |url= https://www.economist.com/blogs/easternapproaches/2013/02/czech-politics |date=13 February 2013 |newspaper=[[The Economist]] |accessdate=28 January 2018}}</ref> something that Zeman's predecessor, [[V\u00e1clav Klaus]], refused to do; he did so shortly after taking office.<ref name=\"3April2013Reuters\"/><ref name=\"Richter2013\">{{cite web |last=Richter |first=Jan |title=President Zeman Hoists EU Flag at Prague Castle |url= http://www.radio.cz/en/section/curraffrs/president-zeman-hoists-eu-flag-at-prague-castle |date=3 April 2013 |publisher=[[Czech Radio]] |accessdate=28 January 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Janicek2013\">{{cite news |last=Janicek |first=Karel |title=EU Flag Flies Over Prague Castle, Not All Happy |url= https://www.timesofisrael.com/eu-flag-flies-over-prague-castle-not-all-happy/ |date=4 April 2013 |newspaper=[[The Times of Israel]] |accessdate=28 January 2018}}</ref> On the same day, Zeman ratified the [[Treaty Establishing the European Stability Mechanism]], which Klaus had also refused to do, making the Czech Republic the last country to do so.<ref name=\"Richter2013\"/><ref name=\"Janicek2013\"/> In June 2017, Zeman stated that Czech people are \"irrationally afraid\" of adopting the Euro as the Czech Republic's currency.<ref>{{cite web |title=Zeman Says Czechs are Irrationally Afraid of Euro Adoption |url= http://praguemonitor.com/2017/06/23/zeman-says-czechs-are-irrationally-afraid-euro-adoption |date=23 June 2017 |work=[[Prague Daily Monitor]] |accessdate=29 January 2018}}</ref>\n\nDespite his pro-EU statements and actions, Zeman supports holding a referendum on Czech EU membership similar to the [[2016 United Kingdom European Union membership referendum|Brexit referendum]] held in the [[United Kingdom]] in 2016.<ref name=\"MullerHovet2018\"/><ref name=\"Czexit\">{{cite news |last=John |first=Tara |title=Is 'Czexit' Next? President of Czech Republic Calls for EU Referendum |url= http://time.com/4391005/czexit-milos-zeman-referendum-nato-eu-czech/ |date=1 July 2016 |newspaper=[[Time (magazine)|Time]] |accessdate=27 January 2018}}</ref> He also has been labelled a [[Euroscepticism|Eurosceptic]] and opposes the EU's migrant quotas.<ref name=\"Prague'sTurn\"/><ref name=\"IrishTimes2018\"/><ref>{{cite news |last=Day |first=Matthew |title=Pro-Russia Czech President Milos Zeman Wins Second Term |url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2018/01/27/pro-russia-czech-president-milos-zemen-wins-second-term/ |date=27 January 2018 |newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |accessdate=27 January 2018}}</ref> He is seen by some critics as having pro-Russia leanings, favouring it over the EU.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Santora |first1=Marc |last2=de Goeij |first2=Hana |title=In Czech Election, a Choice Between Leaning East or West |url= https://www.nytimes.com/2018/01/14/world/europe/czech-election-populism-milos-zeman.html |date=14 January 2018 |newspaper=The New York Times |accessdate=27 January 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Environment and climate change===\nLike his predecessor and former opponent [[V\u00e1clav Klaus]], Zeman is a [[climate change skeptic]]. He has said that in his opinion, human activity probably cannot influence global warming.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://zpravy.idnes.cz/klaus-o-globalnim-oteplovani-dis-/domaci.aspx?c=A120821_151609_zahranicni_jw |title=Fanatici, sepsul Klaus \"oteplova\u010de\". A do\u010dkal se uzn\u00e1n\u00ed od klimatologa |last=Wirnitzer |first=Jan |date=22 August 2012 |work=[[Mlad\u00e1 fronta DNES]] |language=cs |accessdate=22 January 2013}}</ref>\n\nWhen the environmental movement [[Hnut\u00ed DUHA]] tried to protect a national park from illegal logging, Zeman said he would treat them in a \"good old medieval way: burn them, piss on them and salt them\".<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2016/sep/15/milos-zeman-czech-republic-president-populists-post-communist |last=Pato\u010dka |first=Jakub |title=Milo\u0161 Zeman makes Nigel Farage look like a nice guy. It's even worse than that |newspaper=The Guardian |publisher=Guardian Media Group |date=15 September 2016 |accessdate=1 February 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Israel===\n[[File:Reuven Rivlin's visit to Czech Republic (3).jpg|thumb|Zeman meets with Israeli President [[Reuven Rivlin]] in [[Prague]], 21 October 2015]]\nZeman is a long-standing supporter of the State of [[Israel]].<ref>{{Cite news |url= http://zpravy.e15.cz/milos-zeman-volby-2018 |title=Volby 2018: Milo\u0161 Zeman, kandid\u00e1t na prezidenta - E15.cz |work=Zpr\u00e1vy E15.cz |accessdate=19 December 2017}}</ref> Zeman was one of the most prominent international leaders to support the [[United States recognition of Jerusalem as Israeli capital|U.S. recognition of Jerusalem as Israel's capital]] under President [[Donald Trump]],<ref>{{cite web |last=Taylor |first=Adam |title=Who supports Trump on Jerusalem? Europe\u2019s anti-Islam politicians. |url= https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/worldviews/wp/2017/12/11/who-supports-trump-on-jerusalem-europes-anti-islam-politicians/ |date=11 December 2017 |newspaper=The Washington Post |accessdate=27 January 2018}}</ref> and he voiced support for following the US in moving its Israeli embassy to [[Jerusalem]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Landau |first=Noa |title=Czech Republic Wants to Move Embassy to Jerusalem, 'Truly Happy' With Trump's Declaration |url= https://www.haaretz.com/world-news/europe/czech-republic-wants-to-move-embassy-to-jerusalem-truly-happy-with-trump-s-declaration-1.5628122 |date=8 December 2017 |newspaper=[[Haaretz]] |accessdate=27 January 2018}}</ref> He criticized the EU's position on Jerusalem, calling its member states \"cowards\" and stating that they \"are doing all they can so a pro-Palestinian terrorist movement can have supremacy over a pro-Israeli movement.\"<ref>{{cite news |last=Lazaroff |first=Tovah |title=EU\u2019s Anti-Israel Stance on Jerusalem is \u2018Cowardice,\u2019 Czech President Says |url= http://www.jpost.com/Israel-News/EUs-anti-Israel-stance-on-Jerusalem-is-cowardice-Czech-president-says-517577 |date=10 December 2017 |newspaper=[[The Jerusalem Post]] |accessdate=27 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Czech Leader Slams EU \u2018Cowards\u2019 on Jerusalem Stance |url= https://www.timesofisrael.com/czech-leader-slams-eu-cowards-on-jerusalem-stance/ |date=10 December 2017 |newspaper=[[The Times of Israel]] |accessdate=27 January 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Kosovo===\nZeman is opposed to having a Czech embassy in [[Republic of Kosovo|Kosovo]]. He said that he is against the [[recognition of Kosovo]], and has described it as a \"[[terror regime]] financed by the illegal drug trade\".<ref>{{cite web |url= http://zpravy.idnes.cz/zeman-by-jmenoval-vladu-oprenou-o-kscm-dhk-/domaci.aspx?c=A121104_133347_domaci_zt |title=Zeman: Vl\u00e1du s pod\u00edlem KS\u010cM jmenuji, p\u0159ej\u00ed-li si to voli\u010di |language=cs |date=4 November 2012 |work=Mlad\u00e1 fronta DNES}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.blic.rs/Vesti/Politika/364191/Zeman-Kosovo-teroristicki-rezim |title=Zeman: Kosovo teroristi\u010dki re\u017eim |language=sr |date=23 January 2013 |publisher=Blic}}</ref> Whilst visiting [[Belgrade]] in 2014, he stated his opposition to the formation of an independent Kosovan army, equating it to the [[Kosovo Liberation Army]] (KLA). He commented on the history of terrorist acts committed by the KLA, and noted that its disbanding was a component of the peace agreements.<ref>{{cite news |title=Kosovo army would be rearmed KLA \u2013 Czech president |url= http://www.b92.net/eng/news/politics.php?yyyy=2014&mm=04&dd=03&nav_id=89869 |accessdate=21 March 2015 |agency=Beta |publisher=B92 |date=3 April 2014}}</ref> During the same visit, he said he hoped [[Serbia]] would join the [[European Union]] soon.<ref name=Belehrad2014>{{cite news |title=Zeman: Douf\u00e1m, \u017ee se vstupu Srbska do EU do\u017eiju |url= http://www.ceskatelevize.cz/ct24/svet/268165-zeman-doufam-ze-se-vstupu-srbska-do-eu-doziju/ |accessdate=21 March 2015 |publisher=\u010cesk\u00e1 Televize |date=1 April 2014 |language=cs}}</ref>\n\n===Middle East and views on Islam===\nZeman has expressed concern about the growth of [[Islamic terrorism]] and of [[ISIL]].<ref name=BilefskyInfluential/> In June 2011, Zeman said, referring to Islam, \"The enemy is the anti-civilisation spreading from North Africa to Indonesia. Two billion people live in it and it is financed partly from oil sales and partly from drug sales.\" He likened Muslims who believe in the [[Qur'an]] to followers of [[Nazism]].<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.israelnationalnews.com/News/News.aspx/145596 |title=Former Czech Leader Charged for Calling Islam an Enemy |first=Tzvi |last=Ben Gedalyahu |publisher=Arutz Sheva |date=11 July 2011 |accessdate=11 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nZeman called for unified armed operation against [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant|Islamic State]] (ISIL) led by the [[United Nations Security Council|U.N. Security Council]]. In June 2015, Zeman commented that: \"If European countries accept a wave of migrants, there will be terrorist groups among them, of which also a Libyan minister has warned. By accepting the migrants, we strongly facilitate Islamic State\u2019s expansion to Europe.\"<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.praguepost.com/czech-news/48577-zeman-accepting-refugees-plays-into-is-hands |title=Zeman: Accepting refugees plays into Islamic State's hands |work=The Prague Post |date=28 June 2015 |accessdate=}}</ref> Zeman described the [[European migrant crisis|Middle Eastern refugees arriving in Europe]] as an \"organized invasion\".<ref>{{cite web |url= https://news.yahoo.com/czech-leader-calls-migrant-wave-europe-organised-invasion-193015933.html |title=Czech leader calls migrant wave in Europe an 'organised invasion' |publisher=}}</ref> In September 2015, Zeman rejected the [[European Union]]'s proposal of [[European migrant crisis#Relocation and resettlement of asylum seekers|compulsory migrant quotas]], saying, \"Only the future will show that this was a big mistake\".<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.praguepost.com/eu-news/49894-president-pm-opposition-reject-latest-eu-refugee-quotas |title=President, PM, opposition reject latest EU refugee quotas |work=The Prague Post |date=22 September 2015 |accessdate=}}</ref>\n\nZeman said that [[Turkey]] should not be in the European Union and criticised Turkish President [[Recep Tayyip Erdo\u011fan|Erdo\u011fan]]'s anti-European rhetoric.<ref>{{cite news |title=Zeman says Erdogan's words show Turkey has no place in EU |url=http://praguemonitor.com/2017/03/23/zeman-says-erdogans-words-show-turkey-has-no-place-eu |work=Prague Daily Monitor |date=23 March 2017}}</ref> He also accused Turkey of allying with [[ISIL]] in its fight against Syrian Kurds.<ref>{{cite news |title=Turkey condemns Czech president accusation it is ally of IS |url=https://www.apnews.com/446c5495ec8341c2bba2c0705829d5f7 |work=Associated Press |date=20 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Turkey foreign ministry denounces claims of President Milo\u0161 Zeman |url=https://www.radio.cz/en/section/news/turkey-foreign-ministry-denounces-claims-of-president-milos-zeman |work=Radio Prague |date=21 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n===United States and NATO===\n[[File:Barack Obama and Milo\u0161 Zeman.jpg|thumb|Zeman with U.S. President [[Barack Obama]] in [[New York City]]]]\nZeman, who played a role in achieving NATO membership for the Czech Republic,<ref name=\"RFERL\"/> has called for a referendum on NATO membership, though he supports remaining in the organization.<ref name=\"Czexit\"/> In November 2012, during a speech at the [[University of Economics, Prague]], Zeman explained his dislike for [[Madeleine Albright]], former [[United States Secretary of State|US Secretary of State]]. Zeman stated that Albright had promised that there would be no bombardment of civilians during the 1999 [[NATO bombing of Serbia]]. \"And Madeleine Albright made a promise, and Madeleine Albright didn't keep the promise. Since then, I don't like her.\"<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.parlamentnilisty.cz/arena/monitor/Zeman-Madlenka-Albrightova-to-slibila-a-nedodrzela-Nemam-ji-rad-252009 |title=Zeman: Madlenka Albrightov\u00e1 to sl\u00edbila a nedodr\u017eela. Nem\u00e1m ji r\u00e1d |language=cs |date=1 November 2012 |publisher= Parlamentn\u00ed Listy}}</ref>{{unreliable source?|date=February 2016}}\n\nIn March 2015, Zeman criticised protests against the US Army's military convoy (called the \"[[Operation Dragoon Ride|Dragoon Ride]]\") crossing the Czech Republic following NATO exercises in Poland and the Baltic states:<ref>{{cite news |title=Zeman: US convoy troops are no occupation army |url= http://www.praguemonitor.com/2015/03/25/zeman-us-convoy-troops-are-no-occupation-army |accessdate=5 April 2015 |newspaper=Prague Daily Monitor |date=25 March 2015}}</ref>\n{{quote|\"In the past months I have been fighting anti-Russian fools, but most recently I have had to fight anti-American fools as well, since fools are evenly spread on both sides. ... I disagree with the U.S. troops being labelled an occupation army for one simple reason. We experienced occupation twice last century [1939 and 1968] and we know what it looks like.\"|Milo\u0161 Zeman}}\n\n===Poland===\nIn March 2016, Zeman defended [[Poland]]'s newly elected [[Law and Justice]] government, saying: \u201cI expressed the view that the Polish government, which was created as a result of free elections, has every right to carry out activities for which it received a mandate in these elections. It should not be subject to moralising or criticism from the European Union, which should finally focus on its primary task \u2013 to protect the external borders of the Union.\u201d<ref>\"[http://www.thenews.pl/1/10/Artykul/244795,Other-countries-should-not-interfere-with-our-internal-issues-Polish-president Other countries should not interfere with our internal issues: Polish president]\". Radio Poland. 15 March 2016.</ref><ref>\"[http://lodzpost.com/polishnews/president-duda-other-countries-should-not-interfere-with-our-internal-affairs/ President Duda: Other countries should not interfere with our internal affairs]\". \u0141\u00f3d\u017a Post.</ref>\n\n===Russia===\n[[File:\u0412\u0441\u0442\u0440\u0435\u0447\u0430 \u0412\u043b\u0430\u0434\u0438\u043c\u0438\u0440\u0430 \u041f\u0443\u0442\u0438\u043d\u0430 \u0441 \u041f\u0440\u0435\u0437\u0438\u0434\u0435\u043d\u0442\u043e\u043c \u0427\u0435\u0445\u0438\u0438 \u041c\u0438\u043b\u043e\u0448\u0435\u043c \u0417\u0435\u043c\u0430\u043d\u043e\u043c 3.jpg|thumb|Zeman meets with Russian President [[Vladimir Putin]] in Moscow]]\nZeman has described the [[war in Donbass]] as \"a civil war between two groups of Ukrainian citizens\" that have foreign support,<ref name=AFP141117/> and compared it to the [[Spanish Civil War]].<ref>\"[http://zpravy.idnes.cz/zeman-prirovnal-ukrajinskou-krizi-k-obcanske-valce-ve-spanelsku-px6-/zahranicni.aspx?c=A141009_165206_zahranicni_mlb Na Ukrajin\u011b je ob\u010dansk\u00e1 v\u00e1lka jako v 30. letech ve \u0160pan\u011blsku, \u0159ekl Zeman]\" (in Czech). ''iDNES.cz.'' 9 October 2014.</ref> As for the [[annexation of Crimea by the Russian Federation]], he has noted that the [[Kosovo precedent]] has been used as an argument for the separation of Crimea from Ukraine.<ref name=Belehrad2014/>\n\nZeman announced that he intended to visit Moscow for the 2015 [[Victory Day (9 May)|Victory Day]] celebrations and the 70th anniversary of the liberation from [[Nazi Germany]]. He said that he was not going to look at military equipment, but rather to honour the soldiers who had sacrificed their lives. He described his visit to Moscow as an \"expression of thankfulness that we in this country don't have to speak German, if we would have become submissive collaborators of Aryan origin\", and that \"we don't have to say ''Heil [[Adolf Hitler|Hitler]]'', ''Heil [[Heinrich Himmler|Himmler]]'', ''Heil [[Hermann G\u00f6ring|G\u00f6ring]]'', and eventually ''Heil [[Reinhard Heydrich|Heydrich]]'', that would have been particularly interesting\".<ref>{{cite news |title=D\u00edky Moskv\u011b nemus\u00edme \u0159\u00edkat Heil Hitler, h\u00e1j\u00ed \u00fa\u010dast na p\u0159ehl\u00eddce Zeman |url= http://zpravy.idnes.cz/diky-moskve-tu-nemusime-mluvit-nemecky-haji-ucast-na-prehlidce-zeman-1iu-/domaci.aspx?c=A150329_192238_domaci_kha |accessdate=31 March 2015 |agency=\u010cTK |work=Mlad\u00e1 fronta DNES |date=29 March 2015 |language=cs}}</ref> Most other EU leaders declared that they would not attend the events due to the conflict in eastern Ukraine.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-32668511 |title=Russia stages massive WW2 parade despite Western boycott |date=9 May 2015 |accessdate=4 May 2017 |website=BBC News}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Zeman jede na Putinovu vojenskou p\u0159ehl\u00eddku. Je jedin\u00fd z Evropsk\u00e9 unie |url= http://zpravy.idnes.cz/zeman-je-jediny-kdo-navstivi-vojenskou-prehlidku-v-moskve-pnn-/zahranicni.aspx?c=A150312_200803_zahranicni_kha |accessdate=31 March 2015 |agency=\u010cTK |work=Mlad\u00e1 fronta DNES |date=31 March 2015|language=cs}}</ref> [[United States Ambassador to the Czech Republic|U.S. ambassador]] [[Andrew H. Schapiro]] criticized the decision, saying that it would \"be awkward\" if Zeman was the only politician from the EU at the ceremony. Zeman responded by banning him from the [[Prague Castle]].<ref name=BBC_Schapiro>{{cite news |title=US ambassador barred from Prague Castle by Czech president |url= https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-32189757 |accessdate=5 April 2015 |publisher=BBC |date=5 April 2015}}</ref>{{quote|\"I cannot imagine that the Czech ambassador in Washington would advise the US president where he should travel. And I will not allow any ambassador to have a say in my foreign travel plans.\"|Milo\u0161 Zeman}}\n\nThe ban was later lifted by Zeman's office.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://m.rozhlas.cz/zpravy/politika/_zprava/1475427|title=Zav\u0159en\u00e9 dve\u0159e pro velvyslance USA platily pro konkr\u00e9tn\u00ed sch\u016fzku, \u0159\u00edk\u00e1 Kmon\u00ed\u010dek |date=7 April 2015 |publisher=[[Czech Radio]] |language=cs |accessdate=17 April 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2019, at odds with his generally pro-Russian stance, Zeman criticised Russian protests against the Czech decision to recognise the anniversary of the [[Warsaw Pact invasion of Czechoslovakia|Soviet invasion of Czechoslovakia]] as a day commemorating the victims, describing it as \"absolute insolence\".<ref>https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/world/czech-leader-slams-russia-s-insolence-over-1968-12216422</ref><ref>https://www.radio.cz/en/section/news/president-zeman-considering-cancelling-visit-to-russia-over-insolent-statement-from-moscow</ref>\n\n===Ukraine===\nIn 2015, Zeman, in response to a letter from a group of Czech and Ukrainian historians defending [[Stepan Bandera]], leader of the [[Organization of Ukrainian Nationalists]] (OUN), wrote: \"I would like to point out that President Yushchenko declared Bandera a national hero, and a similar declaration in the case of [[Roman Shukhevych]], who became known to have shot thousands of Jews in Lvov in 1941, is now being prepared. I can not congratulate Ukraine on such national heroes.\"<ref>\"[http://www.tyden.cz/rubriky/domaci/zeman-ukrajine-k-hrdinum-jako-je-bandera-blahoprat-nemohu_329493.html Zeman: Ukrajin\u011b k hrdin\u016fm, jako je Bandera, blahop\u0159\u00e1t nemohu]\" (in Czech). T\u00fdden. 8 January 2015.</ref>\n\n==Criticism and controversies==\n[[File:N\u011bmcov\u00e1 Zeman.JPG|thumb|right|250px|Zeman (right) and [[Miroslava N\u011bmcov\u00e1]], former [[Speaker of the Chamber of Deputies of the Parliament of the Czech Republic|Speaker]] of the [[Chamber of Deputies of the Parliament of the Czech Republic]] (May 2013). In June 2013, the [[Civic Democratic Party (Czech Republic)|Civic Democratic Party]] (the leading party of the parliamentary coalition government) nominated her for the post of the [[Prime Minister of the Czech Republic|Prime Minister]]; however, Zeman refused to appoint her and instead chose his long-time ally and friend [[Ji\u0159\u00ed Rusnok]]]]\n[[File:Demonstrace Chci si s vami promluvit, pane prezidente na N\u00e1rodn\u00ed t\u0159\u00edd\u011b, 2014 (21).JPG|thumb|250px|right|Czechs showing [[Penalty card#Red card|red cards]] to the President during the protest named \"I Want to Talk to You, Mr. President\", on 17 November 2014, the 25th anniversary of the [[Velvet Revolution]].]]\n\nIn 1996, before the [[1996 Czech legislative election|legislative election]], Zeman met with Czech-Swiss entrepreneur Jan V\u00edzek in the German city of [[Bamberg]]. In the so-called \"Bamberg Memorandum\", a group of Swiss entrepreneurs allegedly agreed to fund the \u010cSSD pre-election campaign in exchange for economic influence in the Czech Republic after the election. The investigation ended in 2000, with V\u00edzek convicted of falsification of the memorandum by copying signatures from earlier documents. He later admitted that he had intentionally publicised the case in order to compromise Zeman before the [[1998 Czech legislative election|next elections in 1998]]. Zeman was never charged with any wrongdoing, but the reason for the meetings between Zeman and V\u00edzek in 1996 was never revealed.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://zpravy.idnes.cz/vysetrovatele-v-kauze-bamberg-potvrdili-dva-roky-jasnou-vec-prn-/domaci.aspx?c=A000120152336domaci_jkl |title=Vy\u0161et\u0159ovatel\u00e9 v kauze Bamberg potvrdili dva roky jasnou v\u011bc |date=20 January 2000 |work=Mlad\u00e1 fronta DNES |language=cs |accessdate=31 January 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn 1999, one of Zeman's advisers, Jaroslav Novotn\u00fd, allegedly blackmailed the director of the state-owned \u0160ti\u0159\u00edn Castle, V\u00e1clav Hrub\u00fd. Novotn\u00fd allegedly pressured him to falsify evidence in order to prove that former Foreign Minister [[Josef Zieleniec]] corrupted journalists.{{clarify|date=February 2017}} The police confirmed the blackmail, but no charges were ever brought.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://aktualne.centrum.cz/domaci/spolecnost/clanek.phtml?id=628813|title=St\u00e1t chce prodat z\u00e1mek \u0160ti\u0159\u00edn. Cena 100 milion\u016f |last=Slonkov\u00e1 |first=Sabina |date=5 February 2009 |publisher=aktu\u00e1ln\u011b.cz |language=cs |accessdate=31 January 2013}}</ref>\n\nZeman has been criticized for his contacts with the powerful Czech lobbyist [[Miroslav \u0160louf]], formerly his chief adviser. While Zeman was prime minister, \u0160louf maintained contact with the controversial entrepreneur [[Franti\u0161ek Mr\u00e1zek]], nicknamed the \"Godfather of Czech Organized Crime\". \u0160louf and Mr\u00e1zek met and exchanged information at the Office of the Czech Government.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://zpravy.idnes.cz/slouf-financuje-navrat-zemana-do-politiky-odkud-bere-penize-pqr-/domaci.aspx?c=A081007_222844_domaci_abr |title=\u0160louf financuje n\u00e1vrat Zemana do politiky. Odkud bere pen\u00edze? |last1=\u0160\u0165astn\u00fd |first1=Ond\u0159ej |last2=Syrov\u00e1tka |first2=Tom\u00e1\u0161 |date=8 October 2008 |work=Mlad\u00e1 fronta DNES |language=cs |accessdate=31 January 2013}}</ref> Mr\u00e1zek was assassinated in 2006. In leaked wiretapping records, he nicknames Zeman ''mlha'' (\"[[fog]]\") and claims that Zeman \"could not be bribed, and wanted only a sandwich, three pickles and for people to like him.\"<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.nytimes.com/2013/01/27/world/europe/former-prime-minister-is-elected-president-of-czech-republic.html |title=Former Prime Minister Is Elected President of Czech Republic |last=Bilefsky |first=Dan |date=26 January 2013 |newspaper=The New York Times |accessdate=31 January 2013}}</ref> In 2010, \u0160louf and Martin Nejedl\u00fd, a representative of the Russian oil company [[LUKoil]] in the Czech Republic, were the main donors to his [[Party of Civic Rights \u2013 Zemanovci]],<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.ceskatelevize.cz/ct24/domaci/78210-zemanovu-stranu-sponzoruje-jednatel-z-ruskeho-lukoilu/ |title=Zemanovu stranu sponzoruje jednatel z rusk\u00e9ho Lukoilu |date=18 January 2010 |publisher=\u010cesk\u00e1 televize |language=cs |accessdate=31 January 2013}}</ref> but Zeman denied that he had any connection with Lukoil.<ref name = \"MF\" />\n\nIn 2002, German chancellor [[Gerhard Schr\u00f6der]] cancelled an official visit to Prague after Zeman called the ethnic Germans in pre-war Czechoslovakia \"Hitler's [[Fifth column]]\".<ref>{{cite news |url= https://articles.washingtonpost.com/2013-01-26/world/36557829_1_milos-zeman-czech-nuclear-plant-vaclav-klaus |title=Former premier elected Czech Republic's new president, replaces Euro-skeptic Vaclav Klaus |date=31 January 2013 |newspaper=The Washington Post |accessdate=10 September 2016}}{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes}}</ref> Zeman stated that \"the Czechs and Slovaks were doing the [[Sudeten Germans]] a favor by [[Expulsion of Germans from Czechoslovakia|expelling them]], because they granted them their wish to go [[Heim ins Reich]]\".<ref>{{cite book |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=pqy-yA8Wr-gC&pg=PA121&lpg=PA121&dq=zeman+Heim+ins+reich&source=bl&ots=cG6qP-1iC0&sig=vNntSDWacX29vx-zmMx72UhCnns&hl=de&sa=X&ei=dEEKUZmnEIjMswbynIDwAQ&ved=0CDMQ6AEwATgK#v=onepage&q=zeman%20Heim%20ins%20reich&f=false |title=The Myriad Chronicles |date=31 January 2013}}</ref> Later, Zeman called [[Karel Schwarzenberg]], his rival in the presidential campaign of 2013, a \"[[Sudeten Germans|sude\u0165\u00e1k]]\" (Sudeten German),<ref>{{cite web |url= http://zpravy.ihned.cz/politika/c1-59149540-zeman-a-schwarzenberg-se-stretli-v-druhe-televizni-debate-lehci-ton-stridaly-tvrde-utoky |title=Zeman a Schwarzenberg se st\u0159etli v druh\u00e9 televizn\u00ed debat\u011b. Leh\u010d\u00ed t\u00f3n st\u0159\u00eddaly tvrd\u00e9 \u00fatoky |date=18 January 2013 |work=[[Hospod\u00e1\u0159sk\u00e9 noviny]] |language=cs |accessdate=22 January 2013}}</ref> leading the Austrian ''[[Die Presse]]'' to ascribe Zeman's victory to an \"unprecedented [[Anti-German sentiment|anti-German]] dirty campaign.\"<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.ceskenoviny.cz/news/zpravy/czechs-wasting-chance-to-change-policy-german-handelsblatt/894237 |title=Czechs wasting chance to change policy \u2013 German Handelsblatt |date=27 January 2013 |publisher=\u010cesk\u00e9 noviny |accessdate=30 January 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn 26 May 2014, during [[Yom Ha'atzmaut|festivities celebrating the independence of Israel]], Zeman said \"So let me quote one of their [Islamic] sacred texts to support this statement: \"A tree says, there is a Jew behind me, come and kill him. A stone says, there is a Jew behind me, come and kill him.\"<ref>{{cite web |url= http://zpravy.idnes.cz/zeman-nestastne-citoval-z-muslimske-apokalypsy-fu0-/domaci.aspx?c=A140527_172823_domaci_jp|title=Zeman citoval isl\u00e1msk\u00e9 proroctv\u00ed. Ne\u0161\u0165astn\u00e9, soud\u00ed orientalista |last=Pokorn\u00fd |first=Jakub |date=27 May 2014 |work=Mlad\u00e1 fronta DNES |language=cs |accessdate=13 June 2014}}</ref> I would criticize those calling for the killing of Arabs, but I do not know of any movement calling for mass murdering of Arabs. However, I know of one anti-civilisation movement calling for the mass murder of Jews.\"<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.reflex.cz/clanek/zpravy/56765/zeman-o-bruselskych-vrazdach-muze-za-to-islam.html |title= Zeman o bruselsk\u00fdch vra\u017ed\u00e1ch: M\u016f\u017ee za to isl\u00e1m |last=Stoni\u0161ov\u00e1 |first=Tereza |date=28 May 2014 |work=[[Reflex (magazine)|Reflex]] |language=cs |accessdate=13 June 2014}}</ref> When criticized and urged to apologise by the [[Organisation of Islamic Cooperation]], his office replied \"President Zeman definitely does not intend to apologise. For the president would consider it [[blasphemy]] to apologise for the quotation of a sacred Islamic text.\"<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.praguepost.com/czech-news/39532-zeman-will-not-apologize-for-statements-on-islam |title=Zeman will not apologize for statements on Islam |date=10 June 2014 |publisher=Prague Post (originally [[Czech News Agency]]) |accessdate=13 June 2014 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20160325072824/http://www.praguepost.com/czech-news/39532-zeman-will-not-apologize-for-statements-on-islam |archivedate=25 March 2016 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nZeman's comments on the [[Jewish Museum of Belgium shooting]] and \"Islamic ideology\" in June 2014 caused a diplomatic dispute with [[Saudi Arabia]]. The diplomatic source said: \"The Saudis had an exact list of what Zeman said on the issue in the past. The list had several pages. The [Czech] ambassador was in a very unpleasant situation as the protest had never gone so far before.\"<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.praguepost.com/czech-news/39575-czech-envoy-called-on-carpet-over-zeman-s-anti-muslim-words |title=Czech envoy called on carpet over Zeman's anti-Muslim words |work=The Prague Post |date=13 June 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 17 November 2014, the 25th anniversary of the [[Velvet Revolution]], thousands of Czechs took part in a demonstration against Zeman, protesting his pro-Russian stance and vulgar language.<ref name=AFP141117>{{cite news |url= http://www.afp.com/en/news/protesters-give-czech-president-red-card-mark-velvet-revolution |title=Protesters give Czech president red card to mark Velvet Revolution |agency=[[Agence France-Presse]] |date=17 November 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20141118124759/http://www.afp.com/en/news/protesters-give-czech-president-red-card-mark-velvet-revolution |archivedate=18 November 2014 |df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=BBC141117/> Eggs were also thrown, with one accidentally hitting the German president, [[Joachim Gauck]]; German officials said it was just a piece of eggshell.<ref name=BBC141117>{{cite news |url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-30086495 |title=Czech president pelted with eggs on revolution anniversary |publisher=BBC News |date=17 November 2014 |accessdate=18 November 2014}}</ref> On the same day, a group of about 60 people held a counter-demonstration in support of president Zeman.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.tyden.cz/rubriky/domaci/akce-na-podporu-zemana-prilakala-desitky-lidi_324504.html |title=Akce na podporu Zemana p\u0159il\u00e1kala des\u00edtky lid\u00ed |publisher=T\u00ddDEN.cz |language=cs}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2017 Zeman suggested that [[Bosnia and Herzegovina]] could become a base for [[Islamic State of Iraq and Syria|Islamic State]], causing a diplomatic row and provoking criticism from [[Bakir Izetbegovi\u0107]] and the [[Bosniak]] public.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.radio.cz/en/section/news/bosnian-leader-accuses-zeman-of-islamophobia-over-is-claim |title=Bosnian leader accuses Zeman of islamophobia over IS claim |publisher=.radio.cz}}</ref>\n\n===Lawsuits===\nZeman has a long history of losing lawsuits regarding his public comments. In 1993 Zeman lost his lawsuit over his defamatory statement towards former police officer Milan Hru\u0161ka. He falsely accused him of lack of intelligence and inadequate education. Zeman was fined, but ignored the court ruling and never apologised.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://zpravy.idnes.cz/milos-zeman-stale-ignoruje-narizeni-soudu-fj2-/domaci.aspx?c=A000909194530domaci_has |title=Milo\u0161 Zeman st\u00e1le ignoruje na\u0159\u00edzen\u00ed soud\u016f |language=cs |date=9 September 2000 |accessdate=20 March 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 1997 Zeman accused his party colleague [[Jozef Wagner]] of wanting to join the [[Communist Party of Bohemia and Moravia|Communist Party]] after leaving his faction in the Chamber of Deputies. Zeman lost the lawsuit and was ordered to apologise and pay compensation. Zeman initially ignored the ruling, before apologising in 2001.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.tyden.cz/rubriky/domaci/skolstvi/at-zeman-dokaze-ze-je-chlap-politici-o-soudem-narizene-omluve_374507.html |title=A\u0165 Zeman dok\u00e1\u017ee, \u017ee je chlap, \u017e\u00e1d\u00e1 ministr po verdiktu soudu |language=cs |date=2 March 2016 |accessdate=20 March 2016}}</ref> In 2000, Prague City court ordered Zeman to apologise to politician [[Miroslav Macek]] after he described him as a \"thief\".<ref>{{cite news |url= http://zpravy.idnes.cz/zeman-se-musi-mackovi-omluvit-dkp-/domaci.aspx?c=A000504113057domaci_jkl|title=Zeman se mus\u00ed Mackovi omluvit |language=cs |date=4 May 2000 |accessdate=20 March 2016}}</ref> In 2007, Prague City court ruled that Zeman had unlawfully accused journalist Ivan Brezina of corruption. Zeman was ordered to publicly apologise by means of a newspaper article and pay 50,000 CZK in damages.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.respekt.cz/last-week/last-week-16-2007 |title=LAST WEEK 16/2007 |date=16 March 2007 |work=[[Respekt]] |accessdate=31 January 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 February 2012, the [[Supreme Administrative Court of the Czech Republic|Supreme Administrative Court]] ruled that Zeman's campaign team had lied during the presidential campaign. According to the court ruling, this did not affect the outcome of the elections.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://zpravy.aktualne.cz/court-zeman-campaign-lied-but-vote-outcome-unaffected/r~i:article:771831/|title=Court: Zeman campaign lied, but vote outcome unaffected |date=19 February 2013 |accessdate=20 March 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn 2 March 2016, The Prague 1 District Court ruled that Zeman had falsely accused well-known journalist [[Ferdinand Peroutka]] of comments that appeared to be positive about [[Adolf Hitler]]. According to the preliminary judgement the Office of the President had to publicly apologise to Terezie Kaslov\u00e1, Peroutka's descendant.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.rozhlas.cz/zpravy/politika/_zprava/hrad-se-musi-omluvit-za-vyroky-prezidenta-na-adresu-ferdinanda-peroutky--1589505 |title=Hrad se mus\u00ed omluvit za v\u00fdroky Zemana o Peroutkovi, chyst\u00e1 odvol\u00e1n\u00ed |language=cs |date=2 March 2016 |accessdate=20 March 2016}}</ref> After the final appeal failed, the president's office announced on 23 September that it would appeal in the [[Supreme Court of the Czech Republic|Supreme Court]].<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.radio.cz/en/section/curraffrs/castle-refuses-apology-in-peroutka-case-citing-fear-of-flood-of-lawsuits |title=Castle refuses apology in Peroutka case citing fear of flood of lawsuits |date=23 September 2016 |accessdate=11 November 2016}}</ref> Zeman said that he was not suffering from [[senile dementia]] and insisted that the article existed.<ref>{{cite web |title=\"Nejsem seniln\u00ed.\" Peroutka \u010dl\u00e1nek o Hitlerovi napsal, trv\u00e1 na sv\u00e9m Zeman |url= https://zpravy.aktualne.cz/domaci/peroutka-clanek-o-hitlerovi-napsal-trva-na-svem-zeman-nejsem/r~3dc7ff82e39411e5ae64002590604f2e/ |publisher=Aktu\u00e1ln\u011b.cz |accessdate=15 November 2017 |language=cs |date=6 March 2016}}</ref> His spokesperson Ji\u0159\u00ed Ov\u010d\u00e1\u010dek has been looking for it since February 2015.<ref>{{cite web |last=Kottov\u00e1 |first=Anna |title=Dva roky kauzy Peroutka. \u010cl\u00e1nek Hitler je gentleman jsem \u010detl, trv\u00e1 na sv\u00e9m Zeman |url= https://www.irozhlas.cz/zpravy-domov/dva-roky-kauzy-peroutka-clanek-hitler-je-gentleman-jsem-cetl-trva-na-svem-zeman_201701271506_akottova2 |publisher=Czech Radio |accessdate=15 November 2017 |language=cs |date=27 January 2017}}</ref> The office was fined 100,000 K\u010d in October 2016 for failing to apologise. However, the Supreme Court stated on 28 October 2016 that the apology would not be necessary until the court had ruled on the Office's appeal.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.radio.cz/en/section/bulletin/daily-news-summary-2016-10-28 |title=Daily News Summary - Office of the President need not apologize for Peroutka comments for the time being |date=28 October 2016 |accessdate=1 January 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n[[File:Katerina zemanova.jpg|thumb|upright|Kate\u0159ina Zemanov\u00e1, Milo\u0161 Zeman's daughter]]\nIn the 1970s, Zeman was married to Blanka Zemanov\u00e1; the couple divorced in 1978.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.blesk.cz/clanek/zpravy-politika/182021/nasli-jsme-utajovanou-prvni-manzelku-milose-zemana.html |title=Na\u0161li jsme utajovanou prvn\u00ed man\u017eelku Milo\u0161e Zemana! |last=Posp\u00ed\u0161ilov\u00e1 |first=Eva |date=25 September 2012 |work=[[Blesk]] |language=cs |accessdate=27 January 2013}}</ref> In 1993, he married his assistant Ivana Bednar\u010d\u00edkov\u00e1<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.lidovky.cz/ivana-zemanova-zena-ve-stinu-sveho-muze-fcs-/lide.asp?c=A120126_184856_lide_rka |title=Ivana Zemanov\u00e1: Hospodyn\u011b ve st\u00ednu premi\u00e9ra |last=Z\u00eddek |first=Petr |date=26 January 2012 |work=[[Lidov\u00e9 noviny]] |language=cs |accessdate=27 January 2013}}</ref> (born 29 April 1965).\n\nHe has an adult son named David from his first marriage. His daughter from the second, Kate\u0159ina Zemanov\u00e1 (born 1 January 1994), was one of the most visible faces in Zeman's presidential election team. In a post-election speech, Zeman asked her to be his \"informal [[First Lady]]\", as his wife is reportedly shy and does not like media attention.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://doma.nova.cz/clanek/krasaamoda/katerina-zemanova-nejvetsi-prezidentova-chlouba.html |title=Kate\u0159ina Zemanov\u00e1: Nejv\u011bt\u0161\u00ed prezidentova chlouba |date=26 January 2013 |publisher=[[TV Nova (Czech Republic)|doma.nova.cz]] |language=cs |accessdate=27 January 2013}}</ref> When asked about his religious beliefs, he describes himself as a \"tolerant [[atheist]]\".<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.krestandnes.cz/article/milos-zeman-jsem-tolerantni-ateista/21707.htm|title=Milo\u0161 Zeman: Jsem tolerantn\u00ed ateista |last=\u010ci\u017em\u00e1r |first=Rastislav Tercius |date=13 December 2012 |publisher=K\u0159es\u0165an Dnes |language=cs |accessdate=31 January 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20130309041451/http://www.krestandnes.cz/article/milos-zeman-jsem-tolerantni-ateista/21707.htm |archivedate=9 March 2013 |df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url= https://blogs.wsj.com/emergingeurope/2013/03/08/czech-president-milos-zeman-casts-himself-as-unifier |title=Czech President Milos Zeman Casts Himself as Unifier |year=2013 |newspaper=[[Wall Street Journal]] |first=Sean |last=Carney |quote=At the close of the speech, which focused entirely on domestic issues with no reference to the European Union or foreign affairs, the new Czech leader described himself as a tolerant atheist.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.krestandnes.cz/article/milos-zeman-jsem-tolerantni-ateista/21707.htm |title=Milo\u0161 Zeman: I am a tolerant atheist |publisher=K\u0159es\u0165an Dnes |language=cs |url-status=dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20130309041451/http://www.krestandnes.cz/article/milos-zeman-jsem-tolerantni-ateista/21707.htm |archivedate=9 March 2013 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nZeman is a heavy drinker and long-term chain smoker. He only slightly curbed his consumption of alcohol and cigarettes after being diagnosed with diabetes in 2015.<ref>{{cite news |title=Czech president makes unlikely recommendation: smoking safe if you start late |url= http://www.radio.cz/en/section/curraffrs/czech-president-makes-unlikely-recommendation-smoking-safe-if-you-start-late |work=Radio Prague |date=21 March 2015}}</ref> He is also suffering from [[diabetic neuropathy]] in the feet, which causes him difficulties when walking.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.praguemonitor.com/2017/08/18/report-president-zemans-health-condition-very-good |title=Report: President Zeman's health condition very good \u2013 Prague Monitor |website=Prague Monitor}}</ref>\n\n==State awards==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! '''Country'''\n! style=\"text-align:center; background:#f0f0f0;\"|'''Awards'''||'''Date'''\n\n|-\n| {{flagu|Czech Republic}}||Knight Grand Cross of the [[Order of the White Lion]]<ref name=mf>{{cite web |url= http://zpravy.idnes.cz/co-se-take-bude-odehravat-pri-zemanove-inauguraci-fbr-/domaci.aspx?c=A130306_133626_domaci_kop |title=Zeman bude skl\u00e1dat slib a v pr\u016fvodu ponesou \u00fastavu i vyznamen\u00e1n\u00ed |last=Kopeck\u00fd |first=Josef |date=6 March 2013 |work=Mlad\u00e1 fronta DNES |language=cs |accessdate=23 March 2013}}</ref>|| 7 March 2013 ([[ex officio]])\n|-\n| {{flagu|Czech Republic}}||Knight Grand Cross of the [[Order of Tom\u00e1\u0161 Garrigue Masaryk]]<ref name=mf/>|| 7 March 2013 (ex officio)\n|-\n| {{flagu|Germany}}||[[Order of Merit of the Federal Republic of Germany]]|| 5 May 2014\n|-\n| {{flagu|Slovakia}}||[[Order of the White Double Cross]]|| 27 May 2014\n|-\n| {{flagu|Jordan}}||[[Order of Al-Hussein bin Ali]]|| February 2015<ref>{{cite news |title=Jordan, Czech Republic set to boost ties at all levels |url= http://www.jordantimes.com/news/local/jordan-czech-republic-set-boost-ties-all-levels |accessdate=11 September 2016 |newspaper=The Jordan Times |date=11 Feb 2015}}</ref>\n|-\n| {{flagu|Poland}}||[[Order of the White Eagle (Poland)|Order of the White Eagle]]|| 15 March 2016\n|-\n| {{flagu|Slovenia}}|| [[Order for Exceptional Merits (Slovenia)|Order for Exceptional Merits]] || 18 February 2016<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.uradni-list.si/1/content?id=125429#!/Ukaz-o-podelitvi-odlikovanja-Republike-Slovenije |title=Uradni list - Vsebina Uradnega lista |website=www.uradni-list.si}}</ref>\n|-\n| {{flagu|North Macedonia}}|| [[Order 8-September]] || 9 June 2016<ref>http://president.mk/mk/2011-09-03-12-21-37/3835-posetamiloszemannajavno.html{{dead link|date=June 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Milo\u0161 Zeman}}\n*[http://www.hrad.cz/en/president-of-the-cr/current-president-of-the-cr-milos-zeman/curriculum-vitae.shtml Curriculum Vitae] at the website of the [[Prague Castle]]\n*{{C-SPAN|miloszeman}}\n*{{IMDb name|1179461}}\n*{{Worldcat id|lccn-nr93-18575}}\n*{{NYTtopic|people/z/milos_zeman}}\n*[http://www.vlada.cz/cz/clenove-vlady/historie-minulych-vlad/rejstrik-predsedu-vlad/milos-zeman-18021/ Milo\u0161 Zeman] at the website of the [[Government of the Czech Republic]] {{in lang|cs}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Ji\u0159\u00ed Hor\u00e1k]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Leader of the [[Czech Social Democratic Party|Social Democratic Party]]|years=1993\u20132001}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Vladim\u00edr \u0160pidla]]}}\n{{s-new|party}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Leader of the [[Party of Civic Rights]]|years=2010}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Vladim\u00edr H\u00f6nig]]<br />{{small|(Acting)}}}}\n|-\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Milan Uhde]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Speaker of the Chamber of Deputies (Czech Republic)|Speaker of the Chamber of Deputies]]|years=1996\u20131998}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[V\u00e1clav Klaus]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Josef To\u0161ovsk\u00fd]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[List of Prime Ministers of the Czech Republic|Prime Minister of the Czech Republic]]|years=1998\u20132002}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Vladim\u00edr \u0160pidla]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[V\u00e1clav Klaus]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[President of the Czech Republic]]|years=2013\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Milo\u0161 Zeman}}\n{{Czech Social Democratic Party|state=collapsed}}\n{{CzechPMs}}\n{{CZ-Chamber-Speakers}}\n{{CSSD-chairman}}\n{{CzechPresidents}}\n{{Candidates in the Czech presidential election, 2003}}\n{{Candidates in the Czech presidential election, 2013}}\n{{Candidates in the Czech presidential election, 2018}}\n{{Heads of state of the European Union Member states}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Zeman, Milos}}\n[[Category:Milo\u0161 Zeman|*]]\n[[Category:1944 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Kol\u00edn]]\n[[Category:Czech atheists]]\n[[Category:Communist Party of Czechoslovakia members]]\n[[Category:Civic Forum politicians]]\n[[Category:Civic Movement politicians]]\n[[Category:Leaders of the Czech Social Democratic Party]]\n[[Category:Czech Social Democratic Party MPs]]\n[[Category:Party of Civic Rights politicians]]\n[[Category:Presidents of the Czech Republic]]\n[[Category:Prime Ministers of the Czech Republic]]\n[[Category:Members of the Chamber of the Nations of Czechoslovakia (1986\u20131990)]]\n[[Category:Members of the Chamber of the Nations of Czechoslovakia (1990\u20131992)]]\n[[Category:Members of the Chamber of the People of Czechoslovakia (1992)]]\n[[Category:Speakers of the Chamber of Deputies (Czech Republic)]]\n[[Category:Members of the Chamber of Deputies of the Czech Republic (1996\u20131998)]]\n[[Category:Members of the Chamber of Deputies of the Czech Republic (1998\u20132002)]]\n[[Category:Candidates in the 2003 Czech presidential election]]\n[[Category:Candidates in the 2013 Czech presidential election]]\n[[Category:Candidates in the 2018 Czech presidential election]]\n[[Category:Czech Social Democratic Party presidential candidates]]\n[[Category:Czech Social Democratic Party Prime Ministers]]\n[[Category:Left-wing nationalism]]\n[[Category:20th-century atheists]]\n[[Category:21st-century atheists]]\n[[Category:Opposition to Islam in Europe]]\n[[Category:University of Economics, Prague alumni]]\n[[Category:Grand Crosses Special Class of the Order of Merit of the Federal Republic of Germany]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of al-Hussein bin Ali]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2016}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = Milo\u0161 Zeman\n| image = Zeman_M_1.JPG\n| office = [[President of the Czech Republic]]\n| primeminister = [[Petr Ne\u010das]]<br />[[Ji\u0159\u00ed Rusnok]]<br />[[Bohuslav Sobotka]]<br />[[Andrej Babi\u0161]]\n| term_start = 8 March 2013\n| term_end = \n| predecessor = [[V\u00e1clav Klaus]]\n| successor = \n| office1 = 3rd [[Prime Minister of the Czech Republic]]\n| president1 = [[V\u00e1clav Havel]]\n| term_start1 = 22 July 1998\n| term_end1 = 15 July 2002\n| predecessor1 = [[Josef To\u0161ovsk\u00fd]]\n| successor1 = [[Vladim\u00edr \u0160pidla]]\n| office2 = 2nd [[Speaker of the Chamber of Deputies (Czech Republic)|Speaker of the Chamber of Deputies]]\n| president2 = [[V\u00e1clav Havel]]\n| term_start2 = 27 June 1996\n| term_end2 = 17 July 1998\n| predecessor2 = [[Milan Uhde]]\n| successor2 = [[V\u00e1clav Klaus]]\n| office3 = Leader of the [[Czech Social Democratic Party|Social Democratic Party]]\n| term_start3 = 28 February 1993\n| term_end3 = 7 April 2001\n| predecessor3 = [[Ji\u0159\u00ed Hor\u00e1k]]\n| successor3 = [[Vladim\u00edr \u0160pidla]]\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1944|9|28}}\n| birth_place = [[Kol\u00edn]], [[Protectorate of Bohemia and Moravia]]<br />{{small|(now [[Czech Republic]])}}\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| spouse = Blanka Zemanov\u00e1  <br />{{small|(1971\u20131978, divorced)}}<br />[[Ivana Zemanov\u00e1|Ivana Bednar\u010d\u00edkov\u00e1]] <br />{{small|(1993\u2013present)}}\n| children = David<br />Kate\u0159ina\n| party = [[Communist Party of Czechoslovakia|Communist Party]] <br />{{small|(1968\u20131970)}}<br />[[Civic Forum]] <br />{{small|(1990\u20131991)}}<br />[[Civic Movement]] <br />{{small|(1991\u20131992)}}<br />[[Czech Social Democratic Party|Social Democratic Party]] <br />{{small|(1992\u20132007)}}<br />[[Party of Civic Rights]] <br />{{small|(2009\u20132013)}}<br />[[Independent politician|Independent]] <br />{{small|(2013\u2013present)}}\n| alma_mater = [[University of Economics, Prague]]\n| website = {{url|zemanmilos.cz|Official website}}\n| signature = Milo\u0161 Zeman Signature black.png\n}}\n'''Milo\u0161 Zeman''' ({{IPA-cs|\u02c8m\u026alo\u0283 \u02c8z\u025bman|-|Cs-Milos Zeman.ogg}}; born 28 September 1944) is a Czech politician serving as the [[List of Presidents of the Czech Republic|third]] and current [[President of the Czech Republic]] since 8 March 2013. He previously served as [[Prime Minister of the Czech Republic]] from 1998 to 2002. As Leader of the [[Czech Social Democratic Party]] during the 1990s, he transformed his party into one of the country's major political forces. Zeman was [[Speaker of the Chamber of Deputies (Czech Republic)|Speaker of the Chamber of Deputies]], the lower house of the [[Parliament of the Czech Republic|Czech parliament]], from 1996 until he became Prime Minister two years later in 1998.\n\nIn January 2013, Zeman was [[2013 Czech presidential election|elected]] President of the Czech Republic. He is the first directly elected President in Czech history; both of his predecessors, [[V\u00e1clav Havel]] and [[V\u00e1clav Klaus]], were elected by the [[Parliament of the Czech Republic|Czech Parliament]]. In 2018, he was [[2018 Czech presidential election|re-elected]] for a second term.\n\n==Early years==\nZeman was born in [[Kol\u00edn]].<ref name=\"novinky\"/> His parents divorced when he was two years old and he was raised by his mother, who was a teacher.<ref name=\"novinky\"/><ref name=\"horakova\">{{cite news |last1=Hor\u00e1kov\u00e1 |first1=Pavla |title=Milos Zeman - Outgoing Prime Minister |url=https://www.radio.cz/en/section/czechstoday/milos-zeman-outgoing-prime-minister |accessdate=30 August 2018 |work=Radio Prague |date=19 June 2002}}</ref> He studied at a high school in Kol\u00edn, then from 1965 he studied at the [[University of Economics, Prague|University of Economics in Prague]], graduating in 1969.<ref name=\"novinky\">{{cite web |url= http://tema.novinky.cz/milos-zeman |title=Milo\u0161 Zeman |publisher=novinky.cz |language=cs |accessdate=27 January 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn 1968, during the [[Prague Spring]],<ref name=\"horakova\"/> he became a member of the [[Communist Party of Czechoslovakia]], but was expelled in 1970 due to his opposition to the [[Warsaw Pact invasion of Czechoslovakia]].<ref name=\"horakova\"/><ref name = MF >{{cite web |url= http://zpravy.idnes.cz/on-line-chat-milos-zeman-0sh-/domaci.aspx?c=A130102_150857_domaci_jw|title=Neud\u011bloval bych ani milosti, ani amnestie, napsal \u010dten\u00e1\u0159\u016fm Zeman |last=Wirnitzer |first=Jan |date=3 January 2013 |work=[[Mlad\u00e1 fronta DNES]] |language=cs |accessdate=27 January 2013 |quotation=Milo\u0161 Zeman byl \u010dlenem KS\u010c v letech 1968-1970. \"Je\u0161t\u011b kr\u00e1tce po okupaci byla nad\u011bje, \u017ee demokratiza\u010dn\u00ed proces v tehdej\u0161\u00edm \u010ceskoslovensku bude pokra\u010dovat. Tato nad\u011bje vyhasla a\u017e pr\u00e1v\u011b v roce 1970,\" vysv\u011btlil to politik, '''kter\u00e9ho vylou\u010dili pr\u00e1v\u011b pro nesouhlas s okupac\u00ed'''.}}</ref> He was dismissed from his job and spent more than ten years working for the sports organisation Sportpropag (1971\u201384).<ref name=\"mladiMZ\">{{cite web |first=Marcela |last=Jurkov\u00e1 |url= http://zpravy.ihned.cz/politika/c1-59177640-zeman-kandidat-prezident |title=Profil mlad\u00e9ho Zemana: Inteligentn\u00ed samot\u00e1\u0159, kter\u00fd se v\u017edy r\u00e1d poslouchal |trans-title=Profile of the young Zeman: an intelligent loner, who always liked to listen |work=Hospod\u00e1\u0159sk\u00e9 noviny |accessdate=4 May 2017 |date=24 January 2013}}</ref> From 1984, he worked at the company Agrodat, but he lost his job again in 1989, as a result of a critical article he had written in ''Technick\u00fd'' magazine in August 1989, entitled \"Prognostika a p\u0159estavba\" (Forecasting and Perestroika).<ref name=\"novinky\"/><ref>{{cite web |url= http://aktualne.centrum.cz/domaci/clanek.phtml?id=653326 |title=Byl mu\u017eem revoluce. 20 let pot\u00e9 Zemana nikam nepozvali |publisher=Aktu\u00e1ln\u011b.cz |language=cs}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://milos.chytrak.cz/1989/zeman-tm.php |first=Milo\u0161 |last=Zeman |title=Prognostika a p\u0159estavba |work=Technick\u00fd magaz\u00edn |date=August 1989 |access-date=24 April 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070206065008/http://milos.chytrak.cz/1989/zeman-tm.php |archive-date=6 February 2007 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Political activities before presidency==\nIn summer 1989, he appeared on [[Czechoslovak Television]] criticising the poor state of the Czechoslovak economy. His speech caused a scandal, but his views helped him join the leaders of the [[Civic Forum]] a few months later, during the [[Velvet Revolution]].<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.ceskatelevize.cz/ct24/exkluzivne-na-ct24/62717-jisty-prognostik-si-dovolil-kritizovat-komunisticke-hospodarstvi/ |title=\"Jist\u00fd prognostik\" si dovolil kritizovat komunistick\u00e9 hospod\u00e1\u0159stv\u00ed |date=3 August 2010 |publisher=[[\u010cesk\u00e1 televize]] |language=cs |accessdate=27 January 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn 1990 Zeman became a member of the House of the Nations of the Czechoslovak [[Federal Assembly (Czechoslovakia)|Federal Assembly]]. In 1992, he ran successfully for the House of the People of the Federal Assembly, already as a member of the [[Czech Social Democratic Party|Czechoslovak Social Democracy]] (\u010cSSD), which he joined the same year. In 1993, he was elected chairman of the party,<ref name=\"novinky\"/> and in the following years he transformed it into one of the country's major parties.\n\nThe success of \u010cSSD in the [[1996 Czech legislative election|1996 legislative election]] allowed him to prevent his rival [[V\u00e1clav Klaus]] and his [[Civic Democratic Party (Czech Republic)|Civic Democratic Party]] (ODS) from forming a [[majority government]]. Zeman became the [[Speaker of the Chamber of Deputies (Czech Republic)|Speaker of the Chamber of Deputies]] and held this post until the [[1998 Czech legislative election|early election in 1998]].\n\nIn 1998, \u010cSSD won the election and Zeman became [[Prime Minister of the Czech Republic|Prime Minister]] of a [[minority government]], which he led for the next four years. In April 2001, he was replaced as leader by [[Vladim\u00edr \u0160pidla]].<ref>{{cite web |url= http://tema.novinky.cz/milos-zeman |title=Milo\u0161 Zeman |publisher=[[novinky.cz]] |accessdate=22 January 2013 |language=cs}}</ref> Zeman then retired and moved to live in the countryside in the [[Vyso\u010dina Region]]. He won [[Czech Social Democratic Party presidential primaries, 2002|a presidential primary in 2002]] to become the \u010cSSD nominee for president, but lost the [[2003 Czech presidential election|2003 presidential election]] to [[V\u00e1clav Klaus]], due to party disunity. Zeman became an outspoken critic of his former party's leaders. He left \u010cSSD on 21 March 2007, due to conflicts with the party leader and chairman, [[Ji\u0159\u00ed Paroubek]].<ref>{{cite web |url= http://zpravy.ihned.cz/cesko/c1-20717420-zeman-ukoncil-clenstvi-v-cssd-kvuli-kauze-altner |title=Zeman ukon\u010dil \u010dlenstv\u00ed v \u010cSSD kv\u016fli kauze Altner |date=21 March 2007 |work=[[Hospod\u00e1\u0159sk\u00e9 noviny]] |language=cs |accessdate=31 January 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2009, he founded a new party, [[Party of Civic Rights \u2013 Zemanovci]].<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.lidovky.cz/zeman-miri-zpatky-do-politiky-ve-volbach-nastoupi-proti-paroubkovi-114-/zpravy-domov.aspx?c=A091231_105142_ln_domov_tai |title=Zeman m\u00ed\u0159\u00ed zp\u00e1tky do politiky. Ve volb\u00e1ch nastoup\u00ed proti Paroubkovi |date=31 December 2009 |work=[[Lidov\u00e9 noviny]] |language=cs |accessdate=31 January 2013}}</ref> The party did not win any seats in the [[2010 Czech legislative election|2010]], [[2013 Czech legislative election|2013]] or [[2017 Czech legislative election|2017]] legislative elections.\n\n==Presidency==\n{{See also|2013 Czech presidential election||2018 Czech presidential election}}\n[[File:Milo\u0161 Zeman Senate of Poland.JPG|thumb|Zeman in the [[Senate of Poland]], 24 May 2013]]\nIn February 2012 Milo\u0161 Zeman announced his return to politics and intention to run in the [[2013 Czech presidential election|first direct presidential election in the Czech Republic]].<ref>{{cite web |url= http://aktualne.centrum.cz/domaci/politika/clanek.phtml?id=733055 |title=Milo\u0161 Zeman: Se\u017ee\u0148te podpisy a pokus\u00edm se znovu o Hrad |date=14 February 2012 |publisher=aktu\u00e1ln\u011b.cz |language=cs |accessdate=22 January 2013}}</ref> Polls indicated that he was one of the two strongest candidates in the election, alongside [[Jan Fischer (politician)|Jan Fischer]].<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.ceskenoviny.cz/news/zpravy/fischer-zeman-favourites-of-czech-presidential-election-poll/833014 |title=Fischer, Zeman favourites of Czech presidential election \u2013 poll |date=27 August 2012 |publisher=[[\u010cTK]] |accessdate=30 December 2012}}</ref> Zeman narrowly won the first round of the elections and progressed to the second round to face [[Karel Schwarzenberg]], winning by a clearer margin.<ref>{{cite web |last=Wirnitzer |first=Jan |title=Rozhodnuto. Zeman vyhr\u00e1l, nezm\u011bn\u00ed to u\u017e ani velk\u00e1 m\u011bsta |url= http://zpravy.idnes.cz/volba-prezidenta-0ej-/domaci.aspx?c=A130126_130102_domaci_jw |work=Mlad\u00e1 fronta DNES |accessdate=26 January 2013}}</ref> His term began in March 2013.\n\nZeman's alleged excessive alcohol consumption became a subject of public discussion and media attention on several occasions. Many Czechs believed he was drunk during his appearances at [[Czech TV]] headquarters, shortly after his victory in the 2013 presidential election, and during the exhibition of the [[Bohemian Crown Jewels]].<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/worldviews/wp/2013/05/13/video-of-czech-president-staggering-through-ceremony-has-many-wondering-if-he-was-drunk/ |title=Video of Czech president staggering through ceremony has many wondering if he was drunk |last=Fisher |first=Max |date=13 May 2013 |work=[[The Washington Post]] |accessdate=28 May 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2013, Zeman refused to grant a tenured professorship to [[literary historian]] [[Martin C. Putna]], due to Putna's appearance at 2011 Prague [[Pride parade|Gay Pride]].<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.ibtimes.co.uk/articles/469206/20130520/zeman-putna-czech-gay-university.htm |title=Czech Gay Pride Row Flares over President Milos Zeman's Snub of University Appointment |last=Bacchi |first=Umberto |date=20 May 2013 |work=[[International Business Times]] |accessdate=31 May 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2013, the [[Petr Ne\u010das' Cabinet|coalition government]] led by [[Petr Ne\u010das]] collapsed due to a [[2013 Czech political corruption scandal|corruption and spying scandal]]. Zeman, ignoring the political balance of power in the [[Czech Parliament]], appointed his friend and long-term ally [[Ji\u0159\u00ed Rusnok]] as [[Prime Minister of the Czech Republic|Prime Minister]], and tasked him with forming a [[Ji\u0159\u00ed Rusnok's Cabinet|new government]]. This was described in parts of the Czech and foreign media as a political power grab, undermining [[parliamentary democracy]] and expanding his powers.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.reuters.com/article/2013/07/08/us-czech-zeman-idUSBRE9670NT20130708 |title=Czech president angers parties with power grab |last=Lopatka |first=Jan |date=8 July 2013 |agency=[[Reuters]] |accessdate=22 July 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-23258228|title=Jiri Rusnok, new Czech PM, faces instant opposition |last=Cameron |first=Rob |date=10 July 2013 |publisher=[[BBC News]] |accessdate=22 July 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.nytimes.com/2013/07/11/world/europe/czech-president-swears-in-government-led-by-ally.html?ref=miloszeman&_r=0 |title=Czech Leader Swears in Interim Government |last=Bilefsky |first=Dan |date=10 July 2013 |work=[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=23 July 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.economist.com/blogs/easternapproaches/2013/06/czech-politics-2 |title=Zeman's coup |date=26 June 2013 |publisher=[[The Economist]] |accessdate=21 November 2013}}</ref> On 10 July, during the appointment of Rusnok's cabinet, Zeman advised the new cabinet members not to \"let yourself get annoyed by media criticism from jealous fools who have never in their lives done anything useful\".<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.lidovky.cz/nenechte-se-otravit-zavistivymi-hlupaky-popral-zeman-nove-vlade-ph5-/zpravy-domov.aspx?c=A130710_114000_ln_domov_khu |title=Nenechte se otr\u00e1vit z\u00e1vistiv\u00fdmi hlup\u00e1ky, pop\u0159\u00e1l Zeman nov\u00e9 vl\u00e1d\u011b |date=10 July 2013 |work=Lidov\u00e9 noviny |language=cs |accessdate=22 July 2013}} (''\"Nenechte se otr\u00e1vit medi\u00e1ln\u00ed kritikou z\u00e1vistiv\u00fdch hlup\u00e1k\u016f, kte\u0159\u00ed nikdy nic sami nedok\u00e1zali\"'')</ref> Rusnok's government was short-lived, and resigned after losing a vote of confidence.\n\nZeman played an important role in a scandal that occurred in October 2013, shortly after the [[2013 Czech legislative election|Czech legislative election]]. \u010cSSD First Deputy Chairman [[Michal Ha\u0161ek]] and his allies in the party called for chairman [[Bohuslav Sobotka]] to resign following the party's poor election result, and excluded him from the team negotiating the next government. However, it subsequently emerged that Ha\u0161ek and his allies had attended a secret post-election meeting with Zeman, where they were rumoured to have negotiated a 'coup' in \u010cSSD. Ha\u0161ek initially denied the accusations, stating on [[\u010cesk\u00e1 televize|Czech Television]] that \"there was no meeting\". However, his allies (deputies [[Milan Chovanec]], [[Zden\u011bk \u0160kromach]], Jeron\u00fdm Tejc and Ji\u0159\u00ed Zimola) later admitted that the meeting took place. The event sparked public protests in the country and eventually led to Ha\u0161ek apologising and resigning his position in the party.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.ceskenoviny.cz/zpravy/sobotka-s-rival-hasek-leaves-czech-social-democrat-leadership/1005734 |title=Sobotka's rival Hasek leaves Czech Social Democrat leadership |date=8 November 2013 |work=[[\u010cTK]] |publisher=\u010cesk\u00e9 noviny |accessdate=21 November 2013}}</ref> Zeman denied having initiated the meeting. His [[Party of Civic Rights \u2013 Zemanovci]] (SPOZ) received 1.5% of the vote in the election, winning no seats.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.volby.cz/pls/ps2013/ps2?xjazyk=CZ |title=Celkov\u00e9 v\u00fdsledky hlasov\u00e1n\u00ed - volby.cz |website=www.volby.cz}}</ref>\n\nOn 6 April 2014, in the wake of the [[Annexation of Crimea by the Russian Federation|annexation of Crimea]], Zeman called for strong action to be taken, possibly including sending [[NATO]] forces into Ukraine, if Russia tried to annex the eastern part of the country. Speaking on a radio show he said that, \"The moment Russia decides to widen its territorial expansion to the eastern part of Ukraine, that is where the fun ends. There I would plead not only for the strictest EU [[Economic sanctions|sanctions]], but even for military readiness of the [[North Atlantic Alliance]], like for example NATO forces entering Ukrainian territory.\" The Czech Republic has been a NATO member since 1999, when Zeman was prime minister. In the Czech constitutional system it is the government that has the main responsibility for foreign policy, although the President is commander-in-chief of the armed forces. The [[Czech Social Democratic Party|\u010cSSD]] government of [[Bohuslav Sobotka]] resisted strong EU sanctions against Russia after the annexation, because of the negative economic impact such sanctions would have had on the country.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.reuters.com/article/2014/04/06/us-ukraine-crisis-nato-czech-idUSBREA350LY20140406 |title=Czech leader says NATO could offer troops to Ukraine if Russia goes beyond Crimea |date=6 April 2014 |agency=Reuters}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Demonstrace za slu\u0161n\u00e9 \u010cesko \u2013 demise Andreje Babi\u0161e 2.jpg|thumb|Protest against Zeman in [[Prague]], 17 November 2018]] \nIn November 2014, while Czechs celebrated the 25th anniversary of the 1989 [[Velvet Revolution]] against the Soviet-style communist regime, the festivities turned into an appeal for Zeman to resign. Many Czechs believe that Milo\u0161 Zeman has betrayed the legacy of [[V\u00e1clav Havel]] who helped Czechoslovakia and then Czech Republic become a champion of [[human rights]]. Protesters see Zeman as too sympathetic to [[Democracy Index#Democracy Index by country|authoritarian regimes]] and too close to [[Human rights in Russia|Russia]] and [[Human rights in China|China]]. They carried football-style [[Penalty card#Red card|red penalty cards]] as a warning of [[Ejection (sports)|ejection]] to Zeman and pelted eggs at him.<ref name=\"BBC20141117\">{{cite news |url= https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-30086495 |title=Czech president pelted with eggs on revolution anniversary |work=BBC News |date=17 November 2014 |accessdate=}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.dw.com/en/czechs-honor-velvet-revolution-tell-president-zeman-to-resign/a-18069749 |title=Czechs honor Velvet Revolution, tell President Zeman to resign |publisher=[[Deutsche Welle]] |date=17 November 2014 |accessdate=}}</ref>\n\nAn opinion poll conducted by the CVVM agency in March 2016 reported that 62% of Czechs trusted President Milo\u0161 Zeman,<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.praguemonitor.com/2016/03/30/poll-zeman-trusted-record-62-czechs |title=Poll: Zeman trusted by record 62% of Czechs |work=Prague Daily Monitor |date=30 March 2016 |accessdate=}}</ref> up from 55% in September 2015.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.radio.cz/en/section/news/poll-55-percent-express-trust-in-president |title=Poll: 55 percent express trust in president |publisher=[[Radio Prague]] |date=25 September 2015 |accessdate=}}</ref> By December 2016, his approval rating had fallen to 48% following a series of scandals, with around 49% of those surveyed stating that they didn't trust him.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.radio.cz/en/section/curraffrs/trust-in-president-falls-amid-series-of-scandals |title=Trust in president falls amid series of scandals |first=Jan |last=Velinger |publisher=Radio Prague |date=6 December 2016 |accessdate=1 January 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn 9 March 2017, during a meeting with his supporters, Zeman announced his intention to run again for the presidency,<ref>{{cite web |title=Budu znovu kandidovat, ozn\u00e1mil Zeman sv\u00fdm v\u011brn\u00fdm na Hrad\u011b |url= https://www.novinky.cz/domaci/431678-budu-znovu-kandidovat-oznamil-zeman-svym-vernym-na-hrade.html |website=Novinky.cz |accessdate=9 March 2017 |language=cs}}</ref> confirming his decision the next day in a press conference. He said that he had been persuaded by the support of the people. He stated that he does not think he is the favourite in the election, and that he won't run a political campaign, attack his rivals, or participate in debates.<ref>{{cite web |title=Nec\u00edt\u00edm se jako favorit, \u0159ekl Zeman p\u0159i ozn\u00e1men\u00ed kandidatury |url= https://www.novinky.cz/domaci/431710-necitim-se-jako-favorit-rekl-zeman-pri-oznameni-kandidatury.html |website=Novinky.cz |accessdate=10 March 2017 |language=cs}}</ref> He also announced that he would participate in a television programme called ''A week with the President''.<ref>{{cite web |title=P\u0159esv\u011bd\u010dila m\u011b podpora lid\u00ed, \u0159ekl Zeman. Debat\u00e1m s protivn\u00edky se vyhne |url= http://zpravy.idnes.cz/zeman-kandidatura-prima-volba-prezidenta-2018-fe9-/domaci.aspx?c=A170310_095350_domaci_hro |website=iDNES.cz |accessdate=10 March 2017 |date=10 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn 26 March 2017, during a radio interview, Zeman stated that someone had placed [[child pornography]] onto a computer in the official residence. Zeman claimed that he had called \"IT guys\", who had found out that the hackers were from [[Alabama]] in the [[United States]].<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.seznam.cz/zpravy/clanek/prezident-zeman-nasel-detske-porno-ve-svem-pocitaci-jak-se-to-mohlo-stat-29418 |title=Prezident Zeman na\u0161el d\u011btsk\u00e9 porno ve sv\u00e9m po\u010d\u00edta\u010di. Jak se to mohlo st\u00e1t? |language=cs}}</ref> Later, Zeman's spokesman added that \"the President, like every night, googled his own name on the internet and one of the pages contained child pornography\".<ref>{{cite web |url= https://zpravy.aktualne.cz/domaci/zahada-porna-v-prezidentove-pocitaci-milos-zeman-si-googlova/r~989c992e187511e7a4bd0025900fea04/ |title=Zeman si jako ka\u017ed\u00fd ve\u010der hledal \"Milo\u0161 Zeman\", vysv\u011btluje Hrad pornografii v prezidentov\u011b po\u010d\u00edta\u010di |language=cs}}</ref> According to police, there was no evidence of a hacking attack on Zeman's computer.<ref name=\"pdm050417\">{{cite news |title=No unlawful conduct in attack on Zeman's computer, police say |url= http://praguemonitor.com/2017/04/04/no-unlawful-conduct-attack-zemans-computer-police-say |accessdate=5 April 2017 |work=Prague Daily Monitor |date=3 April 2017}}</ref>\n\nZeman decided to run for a second term and stood in the [[2018 Czech presidential election|presidential elections in 2018]]. Observers compared the election to other elections such as the [[2016 United States presidential election|2016 United States]] and [[2017 French presidential election|2017 French]] presidential elections, which saw a [[Liberal internationalism|liberal internationalist]] and a [[right-wing populist]] running against each other.<ref name=\"Prague'sTurn\"/><ref>{{cite web |last=McKenzie |first=Sheena |title=Why the Czech Presidential Election is One to Watch |url= https://www.cnn.com/2018/01/26/europe/why-czech-presidential-election-matters-intl/index.html |date=26 January 2018 |publisher=[[CNN]] |accessdate=27 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Czech Presidential Election Headed for Tight Run-Off Vote -Poll |url= https://www.reuters.com/article/us-czech-election-president-poll/czech-presidential-election-headed-for-tight-run-off-vote-poll-idUSKBN1FA0P2 |date=21 January 2018 |publisher=[[Reuters]] |accessdate=27 January 2018 |quote=The Jan. 26-27 second round echoes other elections in the past two years across the European Union as well as U.S. President Donald Trump\u2019s battle with former Secretary of State Hillary Clinton for the White House in 2016.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Cameron |first=Rob |title=Czech Election: Milos Zeman Wins the Battle of Ideas |url= https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-42848835 |date=27 January 2018 |publisher=BBC News |accessdate=27 January 2018}}</ref> Zeman won the election with 51.37% in the second round.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://zpravy.aktualne.cz/domaci/zeman-posbiral-pro-opetovnou-kandidaturu-na-prezidenta-uz-59/r~936aa014827d11e7b1a4002590604f2e/ |title=Zeman m\u016f\u017ee znovu kandidovat. Jeho t\u00fdm posb\u00edral u\u017e p\u0159es 59 tis\u00edc podpis\u016f |work=Aktu\u00e1ln\u011b.cz |language=cs |date=16 August 2017 |accessdate=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= https://volby.idnes.cz/prezidentske-volby-2018.aspx?k=vysledky-druhe-kolo&t=8&o=7&kandidat=milos-zeman |title=V\u00fdsledky Milo\u0161e Zemana |publisher=Idnes.cz |date=27 January 2018 |accessdate=27 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url= https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/jan/27/czech-president-milos-zeman-wins-second-term |title=Czech president Milo\u0161 Zeman wins second five-year term |last=Prague |first=Associated Press in |date=27 January 2018 |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |publisher=Guardian Media Group |accessdate=31 January 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Political views==\nDuring his premiership and term as leader of the Social Democrats, Zeman was considered a center-left politician, but during his time as president he began to be associated with [[far-right]] [[anti-immigration]] policies in response to the [[European migrant crisis]].<ref name=\"MullerHovet2018\">{{cite web |last1=Muller |first1=Robert |last2=Hovet |first2=Jason |title=Czech President Zeman Re-Elected With Anti-Immigration Message |url= https://www.reuters.com/article/us-czech-election-president/czech-president-zeman-re-elected-with-anti-immigration-message-idUSKBN1FG00C |date=26 January 2018 |publisher=[[Reuters]] |accessdate=27 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Czech Presidential Election Headed for Tight Run-Off Vote -Poll |url= https://www.reuters.com/article/us-czech-election-president-poll/czech-presidential-election-headed-for-tight-run-off-vote-poll-idUSKBN1FA0P2 |date=21 January 2018 |publisher=[[Reuters]] |accessdate=27 January 2018}}</ref> ''[[The Guardian]]'' described Zeman as \"left-of-centre\" in the run-up to the 2013 presidential election,<ref>{{cite news |title=Vladimir Franz: tattooed composer polling strongly in the Czech elections |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2013/jan/09/vladimir-franz-tattooed-czech-elections |accessdate=16 November 2019 |work=The Guardian |date=9 Jan 2013}}</ref> but as \"far-right\" and a [[populism|populist]] in 2018.<ref>{{cite news |last=Tait |first=Robert |title=Czech Republic Re-Elects Far-Right President Milo\u0161 Zeman |url= https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/jan/27/czech-republic-far-right-president-reelected |date=27 January 2018 |newspaper=The Guardian |publisher=Guardian Media Group |accessdate=27 January 2018}}</ref> ''[[The New York Times]]'' described Zeman as a \"populist leftist\".<ref name=BilefskyInfluential>{{cite news |last=Bilefsky |first=Dan |title=Czech Man Is Charged With Attempted Terrorism |url= https://www.nytimes.com/2016/08/03/world/europe/czech-man-attempted-terrorism.html?ref=world |accessdate=3 August 2016 |newspaper=The New York Times |date=2 August 2016}}</ref> Other outlets have simply labeled Zeman a populist.<ref name=\"Prague'sTurn\">{{cite web |last=Mortkowitz |first=Siegfried |title=Prague\u2019s Turn for Populist Vs. Liberal Showdown |url= https://www.politico.eu/article/milos-zeman-jiri-drahos-czech-election-prague-turn-for-populist-vs-liberal-showdown/ |date=26 January 2018 |publisher=[[Politico]] |accessdate=27 January 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"IrishTimes2018\">{{cite newspaper |title=Populist Milo\u0161 Zeman Wins Czech Presidential Election |url= https://www.irishtimes.com/news/world/europe/populist-milo%C5%A1-zeman-wins-czech-presidential-election-1.3371064 |date=27 January 2018 |publisher=[[The Irish Times]] |accessdate=27 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite newspaper |last=Santora |first=Marc |title=Czech Republic Re-elects Milos Zeman, Populist Leader and Foe of Migrants |url= https://www.nytimes.com/2018/01/27/world/europe/czech-election-milos-zeman.html |date=27 January 2018 |newspaper=The New York Times |accessdate=27 January 2018}}</ref> He has been compared to [[United States]] President [[Donald Trump]] and [[List of Donald Trump presidential campaign endorsements, 2016#International political figures|endorsed]] Trump's [[Donald Trump presidential campaign, 2016|2016 presidential campaign]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Janda |first=Jakob |title=Are Czechs about to reelect the Trumpiest president in Europe? |url= https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/democracy-post/wp/2018/01/23/are-czechs-about-to-reelect-the-trumpiest-president-in-europe/ |date=23 January 2018 |newspaper=The Washington Post |accessdate=27 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Muller |first=Robert |title=Trump's Czech Admirer Zeman Weighs Presidential Re-Election Bid |url= https://www.reuters.com/article/us-czech-zeman/trumps-czech-admirer-zeman-weighs-presidential-re-election-bid-idUSKBN16E1VO |date=7 March 2017 |publisher=[[Reuters]] |accessdate=27 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Shaw |first=Adam |title=Pro-Trump Czech President Who Warned of 'Organized Invasion' of Migrants Wins Re-Election |url= http://www.foxnews.com/world/2018/01/27/pro-trump-czech-president-who-warned-organized-invasion-migrants-wins-re-election.html |date=27 January 2018 |publisher=[[Fox News]] |accessdate=27 January 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"HowEuroTrump\">{{cite web |last=Mortkowitz |first=Siegfried |title=How (the European) Trump Won a Second Term |url= https://www.politico.eu/article/milos-zeman-czech-republic-how-the-european-donald-trump-won-a-second-term/ |date=28 January 2018 |publisher=[[Politico]] |accessdate=28 January 2018}}</ref>\n\n===China===\n[[File:2016 Czech Demonstration Against Communist party China & its dictator in Prague with National Flags of TAIWAN & Tibet \u53cd\u4e2d\u793a\u5a01\u8207\u81fa\u7063&\u5716\u535a\u570b\u65d7\u5728\u6377\u514b.jpg|thumb|2016 demonstration against Zeman and China in Prague with picture of late President [[V\u00e1clav Havel]] and Tibetan leader [[14th Dalai Lama]] with flags of [[Tibet]] and [[Taiwan]]]]\nZeman has drawn criticism over his closeness to [[China]]. In 2014, he attracted criticism when he said he wished to learn how China had \"stabilized\" its society.<ref name=\"BBC20141117\"/> In 2016 he invited Chinese president [[Xi Jinping]] on a state visit, which sparked a wave of protest.<ref>[http://www.tibetanreview.net/with-tibetan-flags-opposition-leaders-lead-czech-protest-against-visiting-chinese-president-xi/ With Tibetan flags, opposition leaders lead Czech protest against visiting Chinese President Xi], Tibetan Review, 2016-3-31</ref> He labeled [[Tibetan independence movement|pro-Tibet]] protestors \"mentally impaired individuals\" and used police to prevent protesters from reaching Prague Castle. Police also entered a building of the [[Film and TV School of the Academy of Performing Arts in Prague|Film and TV School of the Academy of Performing Arts]] (FAMU) to remove a Tibetan flag which had been hung out of a window.<ref>[http://lhasadaily.com/opinion/25-views-analysis/886-tibet-symbolism-and-the-czech-republic Tibet, symbolism and the Czech Republic], Tibet Digital Times, 2016-4-28</ref> Deputy [[Finance Minister of the Czech Republic|Finance Minister]] [[Miroslav Kalousek]] accused Zeman of \"bootlicking authoritarian and unfree regimes\".<ref>[http://www.digitaljournal.com/news/world/protests-as-china-s-xi-arrives-in-prague/article/461339 Protests as China's Xi arrives in Prague], Digital Journal, 2016-3-28</ref> Those actions were seen as a contravention of Czech society's [[freedom of expression]], and protests were held by at least 50 members of the two chambers of the [[Parliament of the Czech Republic|Parliament]], opposition leaders and [[civil society]] groups as well as hundreds of supporters of [[Taiwan]], [[Tibet]], and Turkic [[Uyghurs|Uyghur]] separatists in [[Xinjiang]].<ref>[http://www.romea.cz/en/news/world/fifty-legislators-meet-with-the-dalai-lama-in-the-czech-senate-criticize-statement-by-high-officials Fifty legislators meet with the Dalai Lama in the Czech Senate, criticize statement by high officials], [[:cs:ROMEA|ROMEA]], 2016-10-20</ref><ref>[https://www.hongkongfp.com/2016/04/01/czech-opposition-party-leader-flags-up-tibet-during-chinese-leaders-visit/ Czech opposition party leader flags up Tibet during Chinese leader\u2019s visit], [[Hong Kong Free Press]], 2016-4-1</ref><ref>[http://www.thetibetpost.com/en/news/international/4945-hundreds-of-supporters-protest-xis-czech-visit-call-for-free-tibet Hundreds of supporters protest Xi's Czech visit, call for free Tibet], [[Tibet Post International]], 2016-3-30</ref>\n\nZeman has appointed [[Ye Jianming]], the founder and chairman of [[CEFC China Energy]], as his economic adviser.<ref>\"[https://www.reuters.com/article/us-cefc-china/chinas-cefc-has-big-ambitions-but-little-known-about-ownership-funding-idUSKBN14X0B5 China\u2019s CEFC has big ambitions, but little known about ownership, funding]\". Reuters. 13 January 2017.</ref> The company is linked to the [[People's Liberation Army]].<ref>\"[https://www.ft.com/content/e3f8cbd2-983f-11e7-a652-cde3f882dd7b Opaque Chinese oil group makes clear gains in former Soviet bloc]\". ''Financial Times''. 13 September 2017.</ref><ref>\"[http://www.scmp.com/business/companies/article/2072726/whos-39-year-old-paying-hk14-billion-three-office-floors Who\u2019s that 39-year-old paying HK$1.4 billion for three office floors?]\". ''South China Morning Post''. 21 February 2017.</ref> CEFC China Energy has acquired multiple assets in the Czech Republic, including travel agencies and media companies.<ref>\"[https://www.reuters.com/article/czech-china-cefc/update-1-chinas-cefc-adds-to-czech-buying-spree-with-airline-brewery-deals-idUSL5N11B05120150905 China's CEFC adds to Czech buying spree with airline, brewery deals]\". Reuters. 5 September 2015.</ref><ref>\"[https://www.reuters.com/article/us-jtfg-cefc/chinas-cefc-hits-regulatory-hurdle-in-pursuit-of-czech-jtfg-stake-source-idUSKBN1ES1S5 China's CEFC hits regulatory hurdle in pursuit of Czech JTFG stake: source]\". Reuters. 3 January 2018.</ref> Ye was placed under investigation for economic crimes in 2018.<ref>{{cite news|date=1 March 2018|title=China's CEFC chairman investigated for suspected economic crimes: source|first=Benjamin|last=Kang Lim|accessdate=15 August 2018|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-cefc-probe/chinas-cefc-chairman-investigated-for-suspected-economic-crimes-source-idUSKCN1GD3O9|work=Reuters}}</ref><ref>[https://euobserver.com/opinion/141251 The curious case of the Czech president's missing advisor]</ref>\n\n===Gun control===\n{{see also|Gun laws in the Czech Republic}}\n\nIn 2016, following a number of terror attacks around Europe, Zeman joined a number of other Czech politicians and security professionals in urging the 240,000 gun owners in the country with concealed carry licences to carry their firearms, in order to be able to contribute to the protection of [[soft target]]s. Zeman's wife also obtained a concealed carry license and a revolver.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.blesk.cz/clanek/zpravy-politika/410026/ivana-zemanova-uz-ma-revolver-prezident-vyzval-cechy-ke-zbrojeni-proti-teroru.html |title=Ivana Zemanov\u00e1 u\u017e m\u00e1 revolver. Prezident vyzval \u010cechy ke zbrojen\u00ed proti teroru [Ivana Zeman obtained a revolver. President calls Czechs to arm themselves against terrorism] |publisher=Blesk.cz |language=cs |date=31 July 2016 |accessdate=5 March 2017}}</ref>\n\n===European Union===\n{{See also|Euroscepticism in the Czech Republic}}\nZeman has a mixed record on his positions regarding the [[European Union]]. As prime minister, he helped bring the Czech Republic into the EU,<ref name=\"RFERL\">{{cite web |title=Czechs Reelect Populist, Russia-Friendly President In Tight Race |url= https://www.rferl.org/a/czech-zeman-wins-reelection-drahos/29001912.html |date=28 January 2018 |publisher=[[Radio Free Europe/Radio Liberty]] |accessdate=28 January 2018}}</ref> and he has described himself as a \"federalist\" who supports EU membership.<ref name=\"MullerHovet2018\"/><ref name=\"3April2013Reuters\">{{cite web |title=Czech President Raises EU Flag to Signal Change from Klaus Era |url= https://www.reuters.com/article/us-eu-czech/czech-president-raises-eu-flag-to-signal-change-from-klaus-era-idUSBRE9320DK20130403 |date=3 April 2013 |publisher=[[Reuters]] |accessdate=29 January 2018}}</ref> Before becoming president, he promised to fly the [[flag of Europe]] at [[Prague Castle]],<ref>{{cite news |author=B.C. |title=What Kind of President will Milo\u0161 Zeman Be? |url= https://www.economist.com/blogs/easternapproaches/2013/02/czech-politics |date=13 February 2013 |newspaper=[[The Economist]] |accessdate=28 January 2018}}</ref> something that Zeman's predecessor, [[V\u00e1clav Klaus]], refused to do; he did so shortly after taking office.<ref name=\"3April2013Reuters\"/><ref name=\"Richter2013\">{{cite web |last=Richter |first=Jan |title=President Zeman Hoists EU Flag at Prague Castle |url= http://www.radio.cz/en/section/curraffrs/president-zeman-hoists-eu-flag-at-prague-castle |date=3 April 2013 |publisher=[[Czech Radio]] |accessdate=28 January 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Janicek2013\">{{cite news |last=Janicek |first=Karel |title=EU Flag Flies Over Prague Castle, Not All Happy |url= https://www.timesofisrael.com/eu-flag-flies-over-prague-castle-not-all-happy/ |date=4 April 2013 |newspaper=[[The Times of Israel]] |accessdate=28 January 2018}}</ref> On the same day, Zeman ratified the [[Treaty Establishing the European Stability Mechanism]], which Klaus had also refused to do, making the Czech Republic the last country to do so.<ref name=\"Richter2013\"/><ref name=\"Janicek2013\"/> In June 2017, Zeman stated that Czech people are \"irrationally afraid\" of adopting the Euro as the Czech Republic's currency.<ref>{{cite web |title=Zeman Says Czechs are Irrationally Afraid of Euro Adoption |url= http://praguemonitor.com/2017/06/23/zeman-says-czechs-are-irrationally-afraid-euro-adoption |date=23 June 2017 |work=[[Prague Daily Monitor]] |accessdate=29 January 2018}}</ref>\n\nDespite his pro-EU statements and actions, Zeman supports holding a referendum on Czech EU membership similar to the [[2016 United Kingdom European Union membership referendum|Brexit referendum]] held in the [[United Kingdom]] in 2016.<ref name=\"MullerHovet2018\"/><ref name=\"Czexit\">{{cite news |last=John |first=Tara |title=Is 'Czexit' Next? President of Czech Republic Calls for EU Referendum |url= http://time.com/4391005/czexit-milos-zeman-referendum-nato-eu-czech/ |date=1 July 2016 |newspaper=[[Time (magazine)|Time]] |accessdate=27 January 2018}}</ref> He also has been labelled a [[Euroscepticism|Eurosceptic]] and opposes the EU's migrant quotas.<ref name=\"Prague'sTurn\"/><ref name=\"IrishTimes2018\"/><ref>{{cite news |last=Day |first=Matthew |title=Pro-Russia Czech President Milos Zeman Wins Second Term |url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2018/01/27/pro-russia-czech-president-milos-zemen-wins-second-term/ |date=27 January 2018 |newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |accessdate=27 January 2018}}</ref> He is seen by some critics as having pro-Russia leanings, favouring it over the EU.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Santora |first1=Marc |last2=de Goeij |first2=Hana |title=In Czech Election, a Choice Between Leaning East or West |url= https://www.nytimes.com/2018/01/14/world/europe/czech-election-populism-milos-zeman.html |date=14 January 2018 |newspaper=The New York Times |accessdate=27 January 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Environment and climate change===\nLike his predecessor and former opponent [[V\u00e1clav Klaus]], Zeman is a [[climate change skeptic]]. He has said that in his opinion, human activity probably cannot influence global warming.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://zpravy.idnes.cz/klaus-o-globalnim-oteplovani-dis-/domaci.aspx?c=A120821_151609_zahranicni_jw |title=Fanatici, sepsul Klaus \"oteplova\u010de\". A do\u010dkal se uzn\u00e1n\u00ed od klimatologa |last=Wirnitzer |first=Jan |date=22 August 2012 |work=[[Mlad\u00e1 fronta DNES]] |language=cs |accessdate=22 January 2013}}</ref>\n\nWhen the environmental movement [[Hnut\u00ed DUHA]] tried to protect a national park from illegal logging, Zeman said he would treat them in a \"good old medieval way: burn them, piss on them and salt them\".<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2016/sep/15/milos-zeman-czech-republic-president-populists-post-communist |last=Pato\u010dka |first=Jakub |title=Milo\u0161 Zeman makes Nigel Farage look like a nice guy. It's even worse than that |newspaper=The Guardian |publisher=Guardian Media Group |date=15 September 2016 |accessdate=1 February 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Israel===\n[[File:Reuven Rivlin's visit to Czech Republic (3).jpg|thumb|Zeman meets with Israeli President [[Reuven Rivlin]] in [[Prague]], 21 October 2015]]\nZeman is a long-standing supporter of the State of [[Israel]].<ref>{{Cite news |url= http://zpravy.e15.cz/milos-zeman-volby-2018 |title=Volby 2018: Milo\u0161 Zeman, kandid\u00e1t na prezidenta - E15.cz |work=Zpr\u00e1vy E15.cz |accessdate=19 December 2017}}</ref> Zeman was one of the most prominent international leaders to support the [[United States recognition of Jerusalem as Israeli capital|U.S. recognition of Jerusalem as Israel's capital]] under President [[Donald Trump]],<ref>{{cite web |last=Taylor |first=Adam |title=Who supports Trump on Jerusalem? Europe\u2019s anti-Islam politicians. |url= https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/worldviews/wp/2017/12/11/who-supports-trump-on-jerusalem-europes-anti-islam-politicians/ |date=11 December 2017 |newspaper=The Washington Post |accessdate=27 January 2018}}</ref> and he voiced support for following the US in moving its Israeli embassy to [[Jerusalem]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Landau |first=Noa |title=Czech Republic Wants to Move Embassy to Jerusalem, 'Truly Happy' With Trump's Declaration |url= https://www.haaretz.com/world-news/europe/czech-republic-wants-to-move-embassy-to-jerusalem-truly-happy-with-trump-s-declaration-1.5628122 |date=8 December 2017 |newspaper=[[Haaretz]] |accessdate=27 January 2018}}</ref> He criticized the EU's position on Jerusalem, calling its member states \"cowards\" and stating that they \"are doing all they can so a pro-Palestinian terrorist movement can have supremacy over a pro-Israeli movement.\"<ref>{{cite news |last=Lazaroff |first=Tovah |title=EU\u2019s Anti-Israel Stance on Jerusalem is \u2018Cowardice,\u2019 Czech President Says |url= http://www.jpost.com/Israel-News/EUs-anti-Israel-stance-on-Jerusalem-is-cowardice-Czech-president-says-517577 |date=10 December 2017 |newspaper=[[The Jerusalem Post]] |accessdate=27 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Czech Leader Slams EU \u2018Cowards\u2019 on Jerusalem Stance |url= https://www.timesofisrael.com/czech-leader-slams-eu-cowards-on-jerusalem-stance/ |date=10 December 2017 |newspaper=[[The Times of Israel]] |accessdate=27 January 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Kosovo===\nZeman is opposed to having a Czech embassy in [[Republic of Kosovo|Kosovo]]. He said that he is against the [[recognition of Kosovo]], and has described it as a \"[[terror regime]] financed by the illegal drug trade\".<ref>{{cite web |url= http://zpravy.idnes.cz/zeman-by-jmenoval-vladu-oprenou-o-kscm-dhk-/domaci.aspx?c=A121104_133347_domaci_zt |title=Zeman: Vl\u00e1du s pod\u00edlem KS\u010cM jmenuji, p\u0159ej\u00ed-li si to voli\u010di |language=cs |date=4 November 2012 |work=Mlad\u00e1 fronta DNES}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.blic.rs/Vesti/Politika/364191/Zeman-Kosovo-teroristicki-rezim |title=Zeman: Kosovo teroristi\u010dki re\u017eim |language=sr |date=23 January 2013 |publisher=Blic}}</ref> Whilst visiting [[Belgrade]] in 2014, he stated his opposition to the formation of an independent Kosovan army, equating it to the [[Kosovo Liberation Army]] (KLA). He commented on the history of terrorist acts committed by the KLA, and noted that its disbanding was a component of the peace agreements.<ref>{{cite news |title=Kosovo army would be rearmed KLA \u2013 Czech president |url= http://www.b92.net/eng/news/politics.php?yyyy=2014&mm=04&dd=03&nav_id=89869 |accessdate=21 March 2015 |agency=Beta |publisher=B92 |date=3 April 2014}}</ref> During the same visit, he said he hoped [[Serbia]] would join the [[European Union]] soon.<ref name=Belehrad2014>{{cite news |title=Zeman: Douf\u00e1m, \u017ee se vstupu Srbska do EU do\u017eiju |url= http://www.ceskatelevize.cz/ct24/svet/268165-zeman-doufam-ze-se-vstupu-srbska-do-eu-doziju/ |accessdate=21 March 2015 |publisher=\u010cesk\u00e1 Televize |date=1 April 2014 |language=cs}}</ref>\n\n===Middle East and views on Islam===\nZeman has expressed concern about the growth of [[Islamic terrorism]] and of [[ISIL]].<ref name=BilefskyInfluential/> In June 2011, Zeman said, referring to Islam, \"The enemy is the anti-civilisation spreading from North Africa to Indonesia. Two billion people live in it and it is financed partly from oil sales and partly from drug sales.\" He likened Muslims who believe in the [[Qur'an]] to followers of [[Nazism]].<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.israelnationalnews.com/News/News.aspx/145596 |title=Former Czech Leader Charged for Calling Islam an Enemy |first=Tzvi |last=Ben Gedalyahu |publisher=Arutz Sheva |date=11 July 2011 |accessdate=11 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nZeman called for unified armed operation against [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant|Islamic State]] (ISIL) led by the [[United Nations Security Council|U.N. Security Council]]. In June 2015, Zeman commented that: \"If European countries accept a wave of migrants, there will be terrorist groups among them, of which also a Libyan minister has warned. By accepting the migrants, we strongly facilitate Islamic State\u2019s expansion to Europe.\"<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.praguepost.com/czech-news/48577-zeman-accepting-refugees-plays-into-is-hands |title=Zeman: Accepting refugees plays into Islamic State's hands |work=The Prague Post |date=28 June 2015 |accessdate=}}</ref> Zeman described the [[European migrant crisis|Middle Eastern refugees arriving in Europe]] as an \"organized invasion\".<ref>{{cite web |url= https://news.yahoo.com/czech-leader-calls-migrant-wave-europe-organised-invasion-193015933.html |title=Czech leader calls migrant wave in Europe an 'organised invasion' |publisher=}}</ref> In September 2015, Zeman rejected the [[European Union]]'s proposal of [[European migrant crisis#Relocation and resettlement of asylum seekers|compulsory migrant quotas]], saying, \"Only the future will show that this was a big mistake\".<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.praguepost.com/eu-news/49894-president-pm-opposition-reject-latest-eu-refugee-quotas |title=President, PM, opposition reject latest EU refugee quotas |work=The Prague Post |date=22 September 2015 |accessdate=}}</ref>\n\nZeman said that [[Turkey]] should not be in the European Union and criticised Turkish President [[Recep Tayyip Erdo\u011fan|Erdo\u011fan]]'s anti-European rhetoric.<ref>{{cite news |title=Zeman says Erdogan's words show Turkey has no place in EU |url=http://praguemonitor.com/2017/03/23/zeman-says-erdogans-words-show-turkey-has-no-place-eu |work=Prague Daily Monitor |date=23 March 2017}}</ref> He also accused Turkey of allying with [[ISIL]] in its fight against Syrian Kurds.<ref>{{cite news |title=Turkey condemns Czech president accusation it is ally of IS |url=https://www.apnews.com/446c5495ec8341c2bba2c0705829d5f7 |work=Associated Press |date=20 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Turkey foreign ministry denounces claims of President Milo\u0161 Zeman |url=https://www.radio.cz/en/section/news/turkey-foreign-ministry-denounces-claims-of-president-milos-zeman |work=Radio Prague |date=21 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n===United States and NATO===\n[[File:Barack Obama and Milo\u0161 Zeman.jpg|thumb|Zeman with U.S. President [[Barack Obama]] in [[New York City]]]]\nZeman, who played a role in achieving NATO membership for the Czech Republic,<ref name=\"RFERL\"/> has called for a referendum on NATO membership, though he supports remaining in the organization.<ref name=\"Czexit\"/> In November 2012, during a speech at the [[University of Economics, Prague]], Zeman explained his dislike for [[Madeleine Albright]], former [[United States Secretary of State|US Secretary of State]]. Zeman stated that Albright had promised that there would be no bombardment of civilians during the 1999 [[NATO bombing of Serbia]]. \"And Madeleine Albright made a promise, and Madeleine Albright didn't keep the promise. Since then, I don't like her.\"<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.parlamentnilisty.cz/arena/monitor/Zeman-Madlenka-Albrightova-to-slibila-a-nedodrzela-Nemam-ji-rad-252009 |title=Zeman: Madlenka Albrightov\u00e1 to sl\u00edbila a nedodr\u017eela. Nem\u00e1m ji r\u00e1d |language=cs |date=1 November 2012 |publisher= Parlamentn\u00ed Listy}}</ref>{{unreliable source?|date=February 2016}}\n\nIn March 2015, Zeman criticised protests against the US Army's military convoy (called the \"[[Operation Dragoon Ride|Dragoon Ride]]\") crossing the Czech Republic following NATO exercises in Poland and the Baltic states:<ref>{{cite news |title=Zeman: US convoy troops are no occupation army |url= http://www.praguemonitor.com/2015/03/25/zeman-us-convoy-troops-are-no-occupation-army |accessdate=5 April 2015 |newspaper=Prague Daily Monitor |date=25 March 2015}}</ref>\n{{quote|\"In the past months I have been fighting anti-Russian fools, but most recently I have had to fight anti-American fools as well, since fools are evenly spread on both sides. ... I disagree with the U.S. troops being labelled an occupation army for one simple reason. We experienced occupation twice last century [1939 and 1968] and we know what it looks like.\"|Milo\u0161 Zeman}}\n\n===Poland===\nIn March 2016, Zeman defended [[Poland]]'s newly elected [[Law and Justice]] government, saying: \u201cI expressed the view that the Polish government, which was created as a result of free elections, has every right to carry out activities for which it received a mandate in these elections. It should not be subject to moralising or criticism from the European Union, which should finally focus on its primary task \u2013 to protect the external borders of the Union.\u201d<ref>\"[http://www.thenews.pl/1/10/Artykul/244795,Other-countries-should-not-interfere-with-our-internal-issues-Polish-president Other countries should not interfere with our internal issues: Polish president]\". Radio Poland. 15 March 2016.</ref><ref>\"[http://lodzpost.com/polishnews/president-duda-other-countries-should-not-interfere-with-our-internal-affairs/ President Duda: Other countries should not interfere with our internal affairs]\". \u0141\u00f3d\u017a Post.</ref>\n\n===Russia===\n[[File:\u0412\u0441\u0442\u0440\u0435\u0447\u0430 \u0412\u043b\u0430\u0434\u0438\u043c\u0438\u0440\u0430 \u041f\u0443\u0442\u0438\u043d\u0430 \u0441 \u041f\u0440\u0435\u0437\u0438\u0434\u0435\u043d\u0442\u043e\u043c \u0427\u0435\u0445\u0438\u0438 \u041c\u0438\u043b\u043e\u0448\u0435\u043c \u0417\u0435\u043c\u0430\u043d\u043e\u043c 3.jpg|thumb|Zeman meets with Russian President [[Vladimir Putin]] in Moscow]]\nZeman has described the [[war in Donbass]] as \"a civil war between two groups of Ukrainian citizens\" that have foreign support,<ref name=AFP141117/> and compared it to the [[Spanish Civil War]].<ref>\"[http://zpravy.idnes.cz/zeman-prirovnal-ukrajinskou-krizi-k-obcanske-valce-ve-spanelsku-px6-/zahranicni.aspx?c=A141009_165206_zahranicni_mlb Na Ukrajin\u011b je ob\u010dansk\u00e1 v\u00e1lka jako v 30. letech ve \u0160pan\u011blsku, \u0159ekl Zeman]\" (in Czech). ''iDNES.cz.'' 9 October 2014.</ref> As for the [[annexation of Crimea by the Russian Federation]], he has noted that the [[Kosovo precedent]] has been used as an argument for the separation of Crimea from Ukraine.<ref name=Belehrad2014/>\n\nZeman announced that he intended to visit Moscow for the 2015 [[Victory Day (9 May)|Victory Day]] celebrations and the 70th anniversary of the liberation from [[Nazi Germany]]. He said that he was not going to look at military equipment, but rather to honour the soldiers who had sacrificed their lives. He described his visit to Moscow as an \"expression of thankfulness that we in this country don't have to speak German, if we would have become submissive collaborators of Aryan origin\", and that \"we don't have to say ''Heil [[Adolf Hitler|Hitler]]'', ''Heil [[Heinrich Himmler|Himmler]]'', ''Heil [[Hermann G\u00f6ring|G\u00f6ring]]'', and eventually ''Heil [[Reinhard Heydrich|Heydrich]]'', that would have been particularly interesting\".<ref>{{cite news |title=D\u00edky Moskv\u011b nemus\u00edme \u0159\u00edkat Heil Hitler, h\u00e1j\u00ed \u00fa\u010dast na p\u0159ehl\u00eddce Zeman |url= http://zpravy.idnes.cz/diky-moskve-tu-nemusime-mluvit-nemecky-haji-ucast-na-prehlidce-zeman-1iu-/domaci.aspx?c=A150329_192238_domaci_kha |accessdate=31 March 2015 |agency=\u010cTK |work=Mlad\u00e1 fronta DNES |date=29 March 2015 |language=cs}}</ref> Most other EU leaders declared that they would not attend the events due to the conflict in eastern Ukraine.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-32668511 |title=Russia stages massive WW2 parade despite Western boycott |date=9 May 2015 |accessdate=4 May 2017 |website=BBC News}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Zeman jede na Putinovu vojenskou p\u0159ehl\u00eddku. Je jedin\u00fd z Evropsk\u00e9 unie |url= http://zpravy.idnes.cz/zeman-je-jediny-kdo-navstivi-vojenskou-prehlidku-v-moskve-pnn-/zahranicni.aspx?c=A150312_200803_zahranicni_kha |accessdate=31 March 2015 |agency=\u010cTK |work=Mlad\u00e1 fronta DNES |date=31 March 2015|language=cs}}</ref> [[United States Ambassador to the Czech Republic|U.S. ambassador]] [[Andrew H. Schapiro]] criticized the decision, saying that it would \"be awkward\" if Zeman was the only politician from the EU at the ceremony. Zeman responded by banning him from the [[Prague Castle]].<ref name=BBC_Schapiro>{{cite news |title=US ambassador barred from Prague Castle by Czech president |url= https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-32189757 |accessdate=5 April 2015 |publisher=BBC |date=5 April 2015}}</ref>{{quote|\"I cannot imagine that the Czech ambassador in Washington would advise the US president where he should travel. And I will not allow any ambassador to have a say in my foreign travel plans.\"|Milo\u0161 Zeman}}\n\nThe ban was later lifted by Zeman's office.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://m.rozhlas.cz/zpravy/politika/_zprava/1475427|title=Zav\u0159en\u00e9 dve\u0159e pro velvyslance USA platily pro konkr\u00e9tn\u00ed sch\u016fzku, \u0159\u00edk\u00e1 Kmon\u00ed\u010dek |date=7 April 2015 |publisher=[[Czech Radio]] |language=cs |accessdate=17 April 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2019, at odds with his generally pro-Russian stance, Zeman criticised Russian protests against the Czech decision to recognise the anniversary of the [[Warsaw Pact invasion of Czechoslovakia|Soviet invasion of Czechoslovakia]] as a day commemorating the victims, describing it as \"absolute insolence\".<ref>https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/world/czech-leader-slams-russia-s-insolence-over-1968-12216422</ref><ref>https://www.radio.cz/en/section/news/president-zeman-considering-cancelling-visit-to-russia-over-insolent-statement-from-moscow</ref>\n\n===Ukraine===\nIn 2015, Zeman, in response to a letter from a group of Czech and Ukrainian historians defending [[Stepan Bandera]], leader of the [[Organization of Ukrainian Nationalists]] (OUN), wrote: \"I would like to point out that President Yushchenko declared Bandera a national hero, and a similar declaration in the case of [[Roman Shukhevych]], who became known to have shot thousands of Jews in Lvov in 1941, is now being prepared. I can not congratulate Ukraine on such national heroes.\"<ref>\"[http://www.tyden.cz/rubriky/domaci/zeman-ukrajine-k-hrdinum-jako-je-bandera-blahoprat-nemohu_329493.html Zeman: Ukrajin\u011b k hrdin\u016fm, jako je Bandera, blahop\u0159\u00e1t nemohu]\" (in Czech). T\u00fdden. 8 January 2015.</ref>\n\n==Criticism and controversies==\n[[File:N\u011bmcov\u00e1 Zeman.JPG|thumb|right|250px|Zeman (right) and [[Miroslava N\u011bmcov\u00e1]], former [[Speaker of the Chamber of Deputies of the Parliament of the Czech Republic|Speaker]] of the [[Chamber of Deputies of the Parliament of the Czech Republic]] (May 2013). In June 2013, the [[Civic Democratic Party (Czech Republic)|Civic Democratic Party]] (the leading party of the parliamentary coalition government) nominated her for the post of the [[Prime Minister of the Czech Republic|Prime Minister]]; however, Zeman refused to appoint her and instead chose his long-time ally and friend [[Ji\u0159\u00ed Rusnok]]]]\n[[File:Demonstrace Chci si s vami promluvit, pane prezidente na N\u00e1rodn\u00ed t\u0159\u00edd\u011b, 2014 (21).JPG|thumb|250px|right|Czechs showing [[Penalty card#Red card|red cards]] to the President during the protest named \"I Want to Talk to You, Mr. President\", on 17 November 2014, the 25th anniversary of the [[Velvet Revolution]].]]\n\nIn 1996, before the [[1996 Czech legislative election|legislative election]], Zeman met with Czech-Swiss entrepreneur Jan V\u00edzek in the German city of [[Bamberg]]. In the so-called \"Bamberg Memorandum\", a group of Swiss entrepreneurs allegedly agreed to fund the \u010cSSD pre-election campaign in exchange for economic influence in the Czech Republic after the election. The investigation ended in 2000, with V\u00edzek convicted of falsification of the memorandum by copying signatures from earlier documents. He later admitted that he had intentionally publicised the case in order to compromise Zeman before the [[1998 Czech legislative election|next elections in 1998]]. Zeman was never charged with any wrongdoing, but the reason for the meetings between Zeman and V\u00edzek in 1996 was never revealed.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://zpravy.idnes.cz/vysetrovatele-v-kauze-bamberg-potvrdili-dva-roky-jasnou-vec-prn-/domaci.aspx?c=A000120152336domaci_jkl |title=Vy\u0161et\u0159ovatel\u00e9 v kauze Bamberg potvrdili dva roky jasnou v\u011bc |date=20 January 2000 |work=Mlad\u00e1 fronta DNES |language=cs |accessdate=31 January 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn 1999, one of Zeman's advisers, Jaroslav Novotn\u00fd, allegedly blackmailed the director of the state-owned \u0160ti\u0159\u00edn Castle, V\u00e1clav Hrub\u00fd. Novotn\u00fd allegedly pressured him to falsify evidence in order to prove that former Foreign Minister [[Josef Zieleniec]] corrupted journalists.{{clarify|date=February 2017}} The police confirmed the blackmail, but no charges were ever brought.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://aktualne.centrum.cz/domaci/spolecnost/clanek.phtml?id=628813|title=St\u00e1t chce prodat z\u00e1mek \u0160ti\u0159\u00edn. Cena 100 milion\u016f |last=Slonkov\u00e1 |first=Sabina |date=5 February 2009 |publisher=aktu\u00e1ln\u011b.cz |language=cs |accessdate=31 January 2013}}</ref>\n\nZeman has been criticized for his contacts with the powerful Czech lobbyist [[Miroslav \u0160louf]], formerly his chief adviser. While Zeman was prime minister, \u0160louf maintained contact with the controversial entrepreneur [[Franti\u0161ek Mr\u00e1zek]], nicknamed the \"Godfather of Czech Organized Crime\". \u0160louf and Mr\u00e1zek met and exchanged information at the Office of the Czech Government.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://zpravy.idnes.cz/slouf-financuje-navrat-zemana-do-politiky-odkud-bere-penize-pqr-/domaci.aspx?c=A081007_222844_domaci_abr |title=\u0160louf financuje n\u00e1vrat Zemana do politiky. Odkud bere pen\u00edze? |last1=\u0160\u0165astn\u00fd |first1=Ond\u0159ej |last2=Syrov\u00e1tka |first2=Tom\u00e1\u0161 |date=8 October 2008 |work=Mlad\u00e1 fronta DNES |language=cs |accessdate=31 January 2013}}</ref> Mr\u00e1zek was assassinated in 2006. In leaked wiretapping records, he nicknames Zeman ''mlha'' (\"[[fog]]\") and claims that Zeman \"could not be bribed, and wanted only a sandwich, three pickles and for people to like him.\"<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.nytimes.com/2013/01/27/world/europe/former-prime-minister-is-elected-president-of-czech-republic.html |title=Former Prime Minister Is Elected President of Czech Republic |last=Bilefsky |first=Dan |date=26 January 2013 |newspaper=The New York Times |accessdate=31 January 2013}}</ref> In 2010, \u0160louf and Martin Nejedl\u00fd, a representative of the Russian oil company [[LUKoil]] in the Czech Republic, were the main donors to his [[Party of Civic Rights \u2013 Zemanovci]],<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.ceskatelevize.cz/ct24/domaci/78210-zemanovu-stranu-sponzoruje-jednatel-z-ruskeho-lukoilu/ |title=Zemanovu stranu sponzoruje jednatel z rusk\u00e9ho Lukoilu |date=18 January 2010 |publisher=\u010cesk\u00e1 televize |language=cs |accessdate=31 January 2013}}</ref> but Zeman denied that he had any connection with Lukoil.<ref name = \"MF\" />\n\nIn 2002, German chancellor [[Gerhard Schr\u00f6der]] cancelled an official visit to Prague after Zeman called the ethnic Germans in pre-war Czechoslovakia \"Hitler's [[Fifth column]]\".<ref>{{cite news |url= https://articles.washingtonpost.com/2013-01-26/world/36557829_1_milos-zeman-czech-nuclear-plant-vaclav-klaus |title=Former premier elected Czech Republic's new president, replaces Euro-skeptic Vaclav Klaus |date=31 January 2013 |newspaper=The Washington Post |accessdate=10 September 2016}}{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes}}</ref> Zeman stated that \"the Czechs and Slovaks were doing the [[Sudeten Germans]] a favor by [[Expulsion of Germans from Czechoslovakia|expelling them]], because they granted them their wish to go [[Heim ins Reich]]\".<ref>{{cite book |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=pqy-yA8Wr-gC&pg=PA121&lpg=PA121&dq=zeman+Heim+ins+reich&source=bl&ots=cG6qP-1iC0&sig=vNntSDWacX29vx-zmMx72UhCnns&hl=de&sa=X&ei=dEEKUZmnEIjMswbynIDwAQ&ved=0CDMQ6AEwATgK#v=onepage&q=zeman%20Heim%20ins%20reich&f=false |title=The Myriad Chronicles |date=31 January 2013}}</ref> Later, Zeman called [[Karel Schwarzenberg]], his rival in the presidential campaign of 2013, a \"[[Sudeten Germans|sude\u0165\u00e1k]]\" (Sudeten German),<ref>{{cite web |url= http://zpravy.ihned.cz/politika/c1-59149540-zeman-a-schwarzenberg-se-stretli-v-druhe-televizni-debate-lehci-ton-stridaly-tvrde-utoky |title=Zeman a Schwarzenberg se st\u0159etli v druh\u00e9 televizn\u00ed debat\u011b. Leh\u010d\u00ed t\u00f3n st\u0159\u00eddaly tvrd\u00e9 \u00fatoky |date=18 January 2013 |work=[[Hospod\u00e1\u0159sk\u00e9 noviny]] |language=cs |accessdate=22 January 2013}}</ref> leading the Austrian ''[[Die Presse]]'' to ascribe Zeman's victory to an \"unprecedented [[Anti-German sentiment|anti-German]] dirty campaign.\"<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.ceskenoviny.cz/news/zpravy/czechs-wasting-chance-to-change-policy-german-handelsblatt/894237 |title=Czechs wasting chance to change policy \u2013 German Handelsblatt |date=27 January 2013 |publisher=\u010cesk\u00e9 noviny |accessdate=30 January 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn 26 May 2014, during [[Yom Ha'atzmaut|festivities celebrating the independence of Israel]], Zeman said \"So let me quote one of their [Islamic] sacred texts to support this statement: \"A tree says, there is a Jew behind me, come and kill him. A stone says, there is a Jew behind me, come and kill him.\"<ref>{{cite web |url= http://zpravy.idnes.cz/zeman-nestastne-citoval-z-muslimske-apokalypsy-fu0-/domaci.aspx?c=A140527_172823_domaci_jp|title=Zeman citoval isl\u00e1msk\u00e9 proroctv\u00ed. Ne\u0161\u0165astn\u00e9, soud\u00ed orientalista |last=Pokorn\u00fd |first=Jakub |date=27 May 2014 |work=Mlad\u00e1 fronta DNES |language=cs |accessdate=13 June 2014}}</ref> I would criticize those calling for the killing of Arabs, but I do not know of any movement calling for mass murdering of Arabs. However, I know of one anti-civilisation movement calling for the mass murder of Jews.\"<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.reflex.cz/clanek/zpravy/56765/zeman-o-bruselskych-vrazdach-muze-za-to-islam.html |title= Zeman o bruselsk\u00fdch vra\u017ed\u00e1ch: M\u016f\u017ee za to isl\u00e1m |last=Stoni\u0161ov\u00e1 |first=Tereza |date=28 May 2014 |work=[[Reflex (magazine)|Reflex]] |language=cs |accessdate=13 June 2014}}</ref> When criticized and urged to apologise by the [[Organisation of Islamic Cooperation]], his office replied \"President Zeman definitely does not intend to apologise. For the president would consider it [[blasphemy]] to apologise for the quotation of a sacred Islamic text.\"<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.praguepost.com/czech-news/39532-zeman-will-not-apologize-for-statements-on-islam |title=Zeman will not apologize for statements on Islam |date=10 June 2014 |publisher=Prague Post (originally [[Czech News Agency]]) |accessdate=13 June 2014 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20160325072824/http://www.praguepost.com/czech-news/39532-zeman-will-not-apologize-for-statements-on-islam |archivedate=25 March 2016 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nZeman's comments on the [[Jewish Museum of Belgium shooting]] and \"Islamic ideology\" in June 2014 caused a diplomatic dispute with [[Saudi Arabia]]. The diplomatic source said: \"The Saudis had an exact list of what Zeman said on the issue in the past. The list had several pages. The [Czech] ambassador was in a very unpleasant situation as the protest had never gone so far before.\"<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.praguepost.com/czech-news/39575-czech-envoy-called-on-carpet-over-zeman-s-anti-muslim-words |title=Czech envoy called on carpet over Zeman's anti-Muslim words |work=The Prague Post |date=13 June 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 17 November 2014, the 25th anniversary of the [[Velvet Revolution]], thousands of Czechs took part in a demonstration against Zeman, protesting his pro-Russian stance and vulgar language.<ref name=AFP141117>{{cite news |url= http://www.afp.com/en/news/protesters-give-czech-president-red-card-mark-velvet-revolution |title=Protesters give Czech president red card to mark Velvet Revolution |agency=[[Agence France-Presse]] |date=17 November 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20141118124759/http://www.afp.com/en/news/protesters-give-czech-president-red-card-mark-velvet-revolution |archivedate=18 November 2014 |df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=BBC141117/> Eggs were also thrown, with one accidentally hitting the German president, [[Joachim Gauck]]; German officials said it was just a piece of eggshell.<ref name=BBC141117>{{cite news |url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-30086495 |title=Czech president pelted with eggs on revolution anniversary |publisher=BBC News |date=17 November 2014 |accessdate=18 November 2014}}</ref> On the same day, a group of about 60 people held a counter-demonstration in support of president Zeman.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.tyden.cz/rubriky/domaci/akce-na-podporu-zemana-prilakala-desitky-lidi_324504.html |title=Akce na podporu Zemana p\u0159il\u00e1kala des\u00edtky lid\u00ed |publisher=T\u00ddDEN.cz |language=cs}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2017 Zeman suggested that [[Bosnia and Herzegovina]] could become a base for [[Islamic State of Iraq and Syria|Islamic State]], causing a diplomatic row and provoking criticism from [[Bakir Izetbegovi\u0107]] and the [[Bosniak]] public.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.radio.cz/en/section/news/bosnian-leader-accuses-zeman-of-islamophobia-over-is-claim |title=Bosnian leader accuses Zeman of islamophobia over IS claim |publisher=.radio.cz}}</ref>\n\n===Lawsuits===\nZeman has a long history of losing lawsuits regarding his public comments. In 1993 Zeman lost his lawsuit over his defamatory statement towards former police officer Milan Hru\u0161ka. He falsely accused him of lack of intelligence and inadequate education. Zeman was fined, but ignored the court ruling and never apologised.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://zpravy.idnes.cz/milos-zeman-stale-ignoruje-narizeni-soudu-fj2-/domaci.aspx?c=A000909194530domaci_has |title=Milo\u0161 Zeman st\u00e1le ignoruje na\u0159\u00edzen\u00ed soud\u016f |language=cs |date=9 September 2000 |accessdate=20 March 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 1997 Zeman accused his party colleague [[Jozef Wagner]] of wanting to join the [[Communist Party of Bohemia and Moravia|Communist Party]] after leaving his faction in the Chamber of Deputies. Zeman lost the lawsuit and was ordered to apologise and pay compensation. Zeman initially ignored the ruling, before apologising in 2001.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.tyden.cz/rubriky/domaci/skolstvi/at-zeman-dokaze-ze-je-chlap-politici-o-soudem-narizene-omluve_374507.html |title=A\u0165 Zeman dok\u00e1\u017ee, \u017ee je chlap, \u017e\u00e1d\u00e1 ministr po verdiktu soudu |language=cs |date=2 March 2016 |accessdate=20 March 2016}}</ref> In 2000, Prague City court ordered Zeman to apologise to politician [[Miroslav Macek]] after he described him as a \"thief\".<ref>{{cite news |url= http://zpravy.idnes.cz/zeman-se-musi-mackovi-omluvit-dkp-/domaci.aspx?c=A000504113057domaci_jkl|title=Zeman se mus\u00ed Mackovi omluvit |language=cs |date=4 May 2000 |accessdate=20 March 2016}}</ref> In 2007, Prague City court ruled that Zeman had unlawfully accused journalist Ivan Brezina of corruption. Zeman was ordered to publicly apologise by means of a newspaper article and pay 50,000 CZK in damages.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.respekt.cz/last-week/last-week-16-2007 |title=LAST WEEK 16/2007 |date=16 March 2007 |work=[[Respekt]] |accessdate=31 January 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 February 2012, the [[Supreme Administrative Court of the Czech Republic|Supreme Administrative Court]] ruled that Zeman's campaign team had lied during the presidential campaign. According to the court ruling, this did not affect the outcome of the elections.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://zpravy.aktualne.cz/court-zeman-campaign-lied-but-vote-outcome-unaffected/r~i:article:771831/|title=Court: Zeman campaign lied, but vote outcome unaffected |date=19 February 2013 |accessdate=20 March 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn 2 March 2016, The Prague 1 District Court ruled that Zeman had falsely accused well-known journalist [[Ferdinand Peroutka]] of comments that appeared to be positive about [[Adolf Hitler]]. According to the preliminary judgement the Office of the President had to publicly apologise to Terezie Kaslov\u00e1, Peroutka's descendant.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.rozhlas.cz/zpravy/politika/_zprava/hrad-se-musi-omluvit-za-vyroky-prezidenta-na-adresu-ferdinanda-peroutky--1589505 |title=Hrad se mus\u00ed omluvit za v\u00fdroky Zemana o Peroutkovi, chyst\u00e1 odvol\u00e1n\u00ed |language=cs |date=2 March 2016 |accessdate=20 March 2016}}</ref> After the final appeal failed, the president's office announced on 23 September that it would appeal in the [[Supreme Court of the Czech Republic|Supreme Court]].<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.radio.cz/en/section/curraffrs/castle-refuses-apology-in-peroutka-case-citing-fear-of-flood-of-lawsuits |title=Castle refuses apology in Peroutka case citing fear of flood of lawsuits |date=23 September 2016 |accessdate=11 November 2016}}</ref> Zeman said that he was not suffering from [[senile dementia]] and insisted that the article existed.<ref>{{cite web |title=\"Nejsem seniln\u00ed.\" Peroutka \u010dl\u00e1nek o Hitlerovi napsal, trv\u00e1 na sv\u00e9m Zeman |url= https://zpravy.aktualne.cz/domaci/peroutka-clanek-o-hitlerovi-napsal-trva-na-svem-zeman-nejsem/r~3dc7ff82e39411e5ae64002590604f2e/ |publisher=Aktu\u00e1ln\u011b.cz |accessdate=15 November 2017 |language=cs |date=6 March 2016}}</ref> His spokesperson Ji\u0159\u00ed Ov\u010d\u00e1\u010dek has been looking for it since February 2015.<ref>{{cite web |last=Kottov\u00e1 |first=Anna |title=Dva roky kauzy Peroutka. \u010cl\u00e1nek Hitler je gentleman jsem \u010detl, trv\u00e1 na sv\u00e9m Zeman |url= https://www.irozhlas.cz/zpravy-domov/dva-roky-kauzy-peroutka-clanek-hitler-je-gentleman-jsem-cetl-trva-na-svem-zeman_201701271506_akottova2 |publisher=Czech Radio |accessdate=15 November 2017 |language=cs |date=27 January 2017}}</ref> The office was fined 100,000 K\u010d in October 2016 for failing to apologise. However, the Supreme Court stated on 28 October 2016 that the apology would not be necessary until the court had ruled on the Office's appeal.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.radio.cz/en/section/bulletin/daily-news-summary-2016-10-28 |title=Daily News Summary - Office of the President need not apologize for Peroutka comments for the time being |date=28 October 2016 |accessdate=1 January 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n[[File:Katerina zemanova.jpg|thumb|upright|Kate\u0159ina Zemanov\u00e1, Milo\u0161 Zeman's daughter]]\nIn the 1970s, Zeman was married to Blanka Zemanov\u00e1; the couple divorced in 1978.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.blesk.cz/clanek/zpravy-politika/182021/nasli-jsme-utajovanou-prvni-manzelku-milose-zemana.html |title=Na\u0161li jsme utajovanou prvn\u00ed man\u017eelku Milo\u0161e Zemana! |last=Posp\u00ed\u0161ilov\u00e1 |first=Eva |date=25 September 2012 |work=[[Blesk]] |language=cs |accessdate=27 January 2013}}</ref> In 1993, he married his assistant Ivana Bednar\u010d\u00edkov\u00e1<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.lidovky.cz/ivana-zemanova-zena-ve-stinu-sveho-muze-fcs-/lide.asp?c=A120126_184856_lide_rka |title=Ivana Zemanov\u00e1: Hospodyn\u011b ve st\u00ednu premi\u00e9ra |last=Z\u00eddek |first=Petr |date=26 January 2012 |work=[[Lidov\u00e9 noviny]] |language=cs |accessdate=27 January 2013}}</ref> (born 29 April 1965).\n\nHe has an adult son named David from his first marriage. His daughter from the second, Kate\u0159ina Zemanov\u00e1 (born 1 January 1994), was one of the most visible faces in Zeman's presidential election team. In a post-election speech, Zeman asked her to be his \"informal [[First Lady]]\", as his wife is reportedly shy and does not like media attention.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://doma.nova.cz/clanek/krasaamoda/katerina-zemanova-nejvetsi-prezidentova-chlouba.html |title=Kate\u0159ina Zemanov\u00e1: Nejv\u011bt\u0161\u00ed prezidentova chlouba |date=26 January 2013 |publisher=[[TV Nova (Czech Republic)|doma.nova.cz]] |language=cs |accessdate=27 January 2013}}</ref> When asked about his religious beliefs, he describes himself as a \"tolerant [[atheist]]\".<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.krestandnes.cz/article/milos-zeman-jsem-tolerantni-ateista/21707.htm|title=Milo\u0161 Zeman: Jsem tolerantn\u00ed ateista |last=\u010ci\u017em\u00e1r |first=Rastislav Tercius |date=13 December 2012 |publisher=K\u0159es\u0165an Dnes |language=cs |accessdate=31 January 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20130309041451/http://www.krestandnes.cz/article/milos-zeman-jsem-tolerantni-ateista/21707.htm |archivedate=9 March 2013 |df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url= https://blogs.wsj.com/emergingeurope/2013/03/08/czech-president-milos-zeman-casts-himself-as-unifier |title=Czech President Milos Zeman Casts Himself as Unifier |year=2013 |newspaper=[[Wall Street Journal]] |first=Sean |last=Carney |quote=At the close of the speech, which focused entirely on domestic issues with no reference to the European Union or foreign affairs, the new Czech leader described himself as a tolerant atheist.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.krestandnes.cz/article/milos-zeman-jsem-tolerantni-ateista/21707.htm |title=Milo\u0161 Zeman: I am a tolerant atheist |publisher=K\u0159es\u0165an Dnes |language=cs |url-status=dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20130309041451/http://www.krestandnes.cz/article/milos-zeman-jsem-tolerantni-ateista/21707.htm |archivedate=9 March 2013 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nZeman is a heavy drinker and long-term chain smoker. He only slightly curbed his consumption of alcohol and cigarettes after being diagnosed with diabetes in 2015.<ref>{{cite news |title=Czech president makes unlikely recommendation: smoking safe if you start late |url= http://www.radio.cz/en/section/curraffrs/czech-president-makes-unlikely-recommendation-smoking-safe-if-you-start-late |work=Radio Prague |date=21 March 2015}}</ref> He is also suffering from [[diabetic neuropathy]] in the feet, which causes him difficulties when walking.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.praguemonitor.com/2017/08/18/report-president-zemans-health-condition-very-good |title=Report: President Zeman's health condition very good \u2013 Prague Monitor |website=Prague Monitor}}</ref>\n\n==State awards==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! '''Country'''\n! style=\"text-align:center; background:#f0f0f0;\"|'''Awards'''||'''Date'''\n\n|-\n| {{flagu|Czech Republic}}||Knight Grand Cross of the [[Order of the White Lion]]<ref name=mf>{{cite web |url= http://zpravy.idnes.cz/co-se-take-bude-odehravat-pri-zemanove-inauguraci-fbr-/domaci.aspx?c=A130306_133626_domaci_kop |title=Zeman bude skl\u00e1dat slib a v pr\u016fvodu ponesou \u00fastavu i vyznamen\u00e1n\u00ed |last=Kopeck\u00fd |first=Josef |date=6 March 2013 |work=Mlad\u00e1 fronta DNES |language=cs |accessdate=23 March 2013}}</ref>|| 7 March 2013 ([[ex officio]])\n|-\n| {{flagu|Czech Republic}}||Knight Grand Cross of the [[Order of Tom\u00e1\u0161 Garrigue Masaryk]]<ref name=mf/>|| 7 March 2013 (ex officio)\n|-\n| {{flagu|Germany}}||[[Order of Merit of the Federal Republic of Germany]]|| 5 May 2014\n|-\n| {{flagu|Slovakia}}||[[Order of the White Double Cross]]|| 27 May 2014\n|-\n| {{flagu|Jordan}}||[[Order of Al-Hussein bin Ali]]|| February 2015<ref>{{cite news |title=Jordan, Czech Republic set to boost ties at all levels |url= http://www.jordantimes.com/news/local/jordan-czech-republic-set-boost-ties-all-levels |accessdate=11 September 2016 |newspaper=The Jordan Times |date=11 Feb 2015}}</ref>\n|-\n| {{flagu|Poland}}||[[Order of the White Eagle (Poland)|Order of the White Eagle]]|| 15 March 2016\n|-\n| {{flagu|Slovenia}}|| [[Order for Exceptional Merits (Slovenia)|Order for Exceptional Merits]] || 18 February 2016<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.uradni-list.si/1/content?id=125429#!/Ukaz-o-podelitvi-odlikovanja-Republike-Slovenije |title=Uradni list - Vsebina Uradnega lista |website=www.uradni-list.si}}</ref>\n|-\n| {{flagu|North Macedonia}}|| [[Order 8-September]] || 9 June 2016<ref>http://president.mk/mk/2011-09-03-12-21-37/3835-posetamiloszemannajavno.html{{dead link|date=June 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Milo\u0161 Zeman}}\n*[http://www.hrad.cz/en/president-of-the-cr/current-president-of-the-cr-milos-zeman/curriculum-vitae.shtml Curriculum Vitae] at the website of the [[Prague Castle]]\n*{{C-SPAN|miloszeman}}\n*{{IMDb name|1179461}}\n*{{Worldcat id|lccn-nr93-18575}}\n*{{NYTtopic|people/z/milos_zeman}}\n*[http://www.vlada.cz/cz/clenove-vlady/historie-minulych-vlad/rejstrik-predsedu-vlad/milos-zeman-18021/ Milo\u0161 Zeman] at the website of the [[Government of the Czech Republic]] {{in lang|cs}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Ji\u0159\u00ed Hor\u00e1k]]}}\n{{