{"title_page": "Circle MRT line", "text_new": "{{about|the rapid transit system in Singapore|the rapid transit system in Malaysia|MRT Circle Line}}\n{{Infobox rail line\n| name                            =\n| color                           = {{SMRT color|Circle}}\n| native_name                     = {{nobold|{{native name|ms|Laluan MRT Bulatan}}<br />{{native name|zh|\u5730\u94c1\u73af\u7ebf|italics=off}}<br />{{native name|ta|\u0b87\u0ba3\u0bc8\u0baa\u0bcd\u0baa\u0bc1 \u0b8e\u0bae\u0bcd\u0b86\u0bb0\u0bcd\u0b9f\u0bbf \u0bb5\u0bb4\u0bbf|italics=off}}<!--end nobold:-->}}\n| logo                            = [[File:MRT Singapore Destination 8 (1).png|25px]] [[File:MRT Singapore Destination 9.png|25px]] [[File:MRT Singapore Destination 10.png|25px]]\n| logo_width                      = \n| image                           = CC15 Bishan during peak hours.jpg\n| image_width                     = 300px\n| caption                         = C830C trainset at [[Bishan MRT station|Bishan station]] during peak hours\n| type                            = [[Rapid transit]]\n| system                          = [[Mass Rapid Transit (Singapore)]]\n| status                          = Operational<br />Under construction (Stage 6)\n| locale                          = \n| start                           = [[Dhoby Ghaut MRT station|Dhoby Ghaut]]<br />[[Stadium MRT station|Stadium]] (All trains departing from Marina Bay will end here during off-peak hours)\n| end                             = [[HarbourFront MRT station|HarbourFront]]<br />[[Marina Bay MRT station|Marina Bay]]\n| stations                        = 30 (Operational)\n<br />3 (Under construction)\n| routes                          = 3\n| daily_ridership                 = 398,000 (May 2015)\n| open                            = {{start date and age|df=yes|2009|05|28}} (Stage 3)<br />{{start date and age|df=yes|2010|04|17}} (Stages 1 and 2)<br />{{start date and age|df=yes|2011|10|08}} (Stages 4 and 5)<br />{{start date and age|df=yes|2012|01|14}} (Circle Line extension)\n| planopen                        = {{start date and age|df=yes|2025}} (Stage 6)<br />20?? ([[Bukit Brown MRT station]])\n| close                           = \n| owner                           = [[Land Transport Authority]]\n| operator                        = [[SMRT Trains|SMRT Trains Ltd]] ([[SMRT Corporation]])\n| character                       = Fully Underground\n| stock                           = [[Alstom Metropolis C830|C830]] <br /> [[Alstom Metropolis C830C|C830C]] <br /> [[Alstom Metropolis C851E|C851E]] (Future)\n| linelength                      = {{convert|35.5|km|mi|abbr=on}} (Operational) <br /> {{convert|4|km|mi|abbr=on}} (''Under construction'')\n| tracklength                     = \n| tracks                          = \n| gauge                           = {{track gauge|sg|allk=on}}\n| electrification                 = 750 V [[Direct current|DC]] [[third rail]]\n| speed                           = limit of {{convert|78|km/h|mph|abbr=on}}\n| elevation                       = \n| map                             = {{MRT route/Circle|navbar=1|legend=0|collapsed=no}}\n| map_state                       = hide\n| depot                           = [[Kim Chuan Depot|Kim Chuan]]\n}}\n\nThe '''Circle MRT Line''' ('''CCL''') is a medium-capacity [[Mass Rapid Transit (Singapore)|Mass Rapid Transit]] line in [[Singapore]] operated by [[SMRT Corporation]]. It runs a currently incomplete [[Circle route|loop]] from [[Dhoby Ghaut MRT station|Dhoby Ghaut]] station in the [[Central Area, Singapore|city area of Singapore]] to [[HarbourFront MRT station|HarbourFront]] station in the south via [[Bishan MRT station|Bishan station]] in [[Central Area, Singapore|Central Singapore]]. It also has a branch to [[Marina Bay MRT station|Marina Bay]] station from [[Promenade MRT station|Promenade]] station, which will be extended to Harbourfront station in the future, forming a complete loop. Coloured orange on the rail map, the fully-underground line is {{convert|35.5|km|mi}} long with 30 stations. Travelling from one end of the line to the other takes about an hour.\n\nIt is the second in Singapore to be [[automatic train operation|completely automated]] and driverless and is among the [[List of driverless trains|world's longest]] driverless [[rapid transit]] lines.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.railway-technology.com/contractors/suburban/alstom/press5.html | title=ALSTOM chosen for the world's longest fully automated metro line in Singapore | publisher=railway-technology.com | date=2002-02-20 }}</ref> As of May 2015, the daily ridership is 398,000.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/transport/four-more-trains-for-circle-line-as-ridership-rises|title=Four more trains for Circle line as ridership rises|website=The Straits Times|access-date=2016-03-04}}</ref> It is also the first [[Medium-capacity rail transport system|medium capacity line]] in Singapore, with each Circle Line train having a three-car configuration. \n\nThe line is the fourth MRT line to be opened, with the first stage (from [[Bartley MRT station|Bartley]] to [[Marymount MRT station|Marymount]] stations) commencing operations on 28 May 2009. The next stage to Dhoby Ghaut station was completed on 17 April 2010,  with the next stage to Harbourfront opening on 8 October 2011, and the last two-station extension to Marina Bay station opening on 14 February 2012. The last stage of the line from Harbourfront to Marina Bay will be completed in 2026, completing the loop.\n\n==History==\n===Original Plans===\n\nThe Circle Line dates back to 1989, when then Minister for Communications and Information, Dr [[Yeo Ning Hong]] stated that such a system would be \"feasible when the population reaches four million.\"<ref>{{cite web |title=Circle line 'needed with 4 million people' |url=https://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article/straitstimes19891104-1.2.2 |website=The Straits Times (retrieved from NLB) |accessdate=6 October 2019 |date=4 November 1989}}</ref>\n\nFeasibility studies for the proposed line commenced on 11 October 1994. The Circle Line was first named as the Marina Line on 12 June 1998, initially planned as a 12-station underground line (upgraded from LRT to 3-car MRT line), starting from [[Chinatown MRT station|Chinatown]] and [[Dhoby Ghaut MRT station|Dhoby Ghaut]] via the [[Stadium MRT station|National Stadium]] to either [[Kallang MRT station|Kallang]] or [[Paya Lebar MRT station|Paya Lebar]] station.<ref>{{cite web |title=Signing of E&M contracts ceremony |url=http://www.nas.gov.sg/archivesonline/data/pdfdoc/1998061201.htm |website=NAS |accessdate=23 November 2019 |date=12 June 1998}}</ref> However, the Chinatown leg was later truncated and was reduced to 6 stations up to [[Stadium MRT station|Stadium]] station. A part of the truncated leg later became part of the [[Downtown MRT line|Downtown line]]<ref>{{cite book|last1=Colin|first1=Cheong|title=The Circle Line, Linking All Lines|date=2012|isbn=978-981-4342-02-5|page=36}}</ref> On the other hand, a further extension towards Upper Paya Lebar was announced on 28 April 2001.<ref>{{cite web |title=Circle Line and Kallang/Paya Lebar Expressway |url=https://www.nas.gov.sg/archivesonline/data/pdfdoc/2001042808.htm |website=NAS |accessdate=23 November 2019 |date=28 April 2001}}</ref> The Marina Line was also merged with an [[Light Rail Transit (Singapore)|LRT line]] that goes from [[Paya Lebar MRT station|Paya Lebar]] to [[Buona Vista MRT station|Buona Vista]] via [[Serangoon MRT station|Serangoon]] and [[Bishan MRT station|Bishan]] to form Circle Line Stage 3 on 20 January 2003,<ref>{{cite web |title=Circle Line Stage 3 |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20030526200150/http://www.lta.gov.sg/Menu_NewsRelease.htm |website=LTA |accessdate=15 July 2019 |date=20 January 2003}}</ref> and subsequently Circle Line Stage 4 and 5 on 12 December 2003 when Stage 4 was extended from [[Buona Vista MRT station|Buona Vista]] to World Trade Centre to close up the link and to provide connectivity from the west to Sentosa, and it became the full Circle line in the end.<ref>{{cite web |title=Completing the Circle via Holland V |url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article/today20031213-1.2.3 |website=Today (retrieved from NLB) |accessdate=6 September 2019 |date=13 December 2003}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=News 5 Tonight (12 December 2003) |url=http://www.nas.gov.sg/archivesonline/audiovisual_records/record-details/57de1bd1-1164-11e3-83d5-0050568939ad |website=MediaCorp (retrieved from NAS) |accessdate=19 July 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190719031728/http://www.nas.gov.sg/archivesonline/audiovisual_records/record-details/57de1bd1-1164-11e3-83d5-0050568939ad |archive-date=19 July 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Stations in Circle Line that were a part of the original Marina Line plans include [[Dhoby Ghaut MRT station|Dhoby Ghaut]], [[Bras Basah MRT station|Bras Basah]], [[Esplanade MRT station|Esplanade]], [[Promenade MRT station|Promenade]], [[Nicoll Highway MRT station|Nicoll Highway]] and [[Stadium MRT station|Stadium]]. On 8 August 2001, [[SMRT Corporation|SMRT]] won the bid and was appointed the operator of the Circle Line.<ref>{{cite web |title=Appointment Of Operator For The Circle Line |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20021224094604fw_/http://app.internet.gov.sg/scripts/lta/3_press_content.asp?start=315 |website=LTA |accessdate=19 July 2019 |date=8 August 2001}}</ref>\n\n===Construction of the initial stages===\n[[File:Construction of Bishan MRT Circle Line 2005-03-29.JPG|thumb|left|The construction of Bishan station.]]\n[[File:CC18BukitBrown.jpg|thumb|left|Bukit Brown station, the only \"shell station\"]]\n\nConstruction started on 13 March 2002 for Stage 1, 5 September 2002 for Stage 2, May 2003 for Stage 3, and January 2005 for Stages 4 and 5. The Circle Line was supposed to be opened in stages from 2006 to 2010, with an estimated cost of S$6.7 billion, but the [[Nicoll Highway collapse]] caused the opening of the first stage to be delayed to 28 May 2009. When the line fully opened on 8 October 2011, the cost of construction had escalated to nearly S$10 billion.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite book|last1=Colin|first1=Cheong|title=The Circle Line, Linking All Lines|date=2012|isbn=978-981-4342-02-5|page=46}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://motoring.asiaone.com/Motoring/Motorworld/Story/A1Story20090818-161682.html|title=Circle Line could cost taxpayers $10 billion|publisher=AsiaOne Motoring|accessdate=21 August 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111008134221/http://motoring.asiaone.com/Motoring/Motorworld/Story/A1Story20090818-161682.html|archivedate=8 October 2011}}</ref> Due to the re-alignment of the [[Nicoll Highway MRT station|Nicoll Highway station]] to a new location, the station is only two-thirds the size of the original plan before the collapse. It was located {{convert|100|m|ft}} away from the original site.<ref>[http://www.straitstimes.com/Free/Story/STIStory_157967.html \"Circle line will exceed $6.7b budget\"] Christopher Tan, [[The Straits Times]], 15 September 2007</ref> Some stations on the Circle Line were initially designed as 'shell stations', but the decision was made to open Caldecott and Haw Par Villa (previously Thomson and West Coast respectively), which leaves [[Bukit Brown MRT station|Bukit Brown]] as the only unopened station on the line.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\nStage 3, a {{convert|5|km|mi}} five-station segment stretching from [[Bartley MRT station|Bartley]] to [[Marymount MRT station|Marymount]], was the first section of the line opened on 28 May 2009. Initial ridership on this section was lower than estimated, at 32,000 passengers per day (ppd) instead of the estimated 55,000 ppd.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.channelnewsasia.com/stories/singaporelocalnews/view/449350/1/.html|title=LTA completes final tunnelling work on Circle Line|publisher=Channel News Asia|date=17 August 2009|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121019161745/http://www.channelnewsasia.com/stories/singaporelocalnews/view/449350/1/.html|archivedate=19 October 2012}}</ref> Tunneling works for the entire line were completed on 17 August 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.straitstimes.com/Breaking%2BNews/Singapore/Story/STIStory_417858.html?vgnmr=1|title=Circle Line: The longest dig|publisher=The Straits Times|date=17 August 2009|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090821173820/https://www.straitstimes.com/Breaking%2BNews/Singapore/Story/STIStory_417858.html?vgnmr=1|archivedate=21 August 2009}}</ref> Stages 1 and 2 started operations on 17 April 2010,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://app.lta.gov.sg/corp_press_content.asp?start=kpt8zx9w8ik53wi33gr59p754348fsj35b9glldouy8ndlh7kb |title=Circle Line from Bartley to Dhoby Ghaut to Open 17 April |accessdate=2010-01-26 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110621220756/http://app.lta.gov.sg/corp_press_content.asp?start=kpt8zx9w8ik53wi33gr59p754348fsj35b9glldouy8ndlh7kb |archivedate=2011-06-21 }}</ref> Stages 4 and 5 on 8 October 2011,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sg.news.yahoo.com/blogs/singaporescene/final-batch-circle-line-stations-open-004355257.html|title=Train crowding to ease with launch of full Circle line: Minister Lui|publisher=|accessdate=21 August 2016}}</ref> and the final two-station Circle Line Extension on 14 January 2012. The line was also fully completed on 8 October 2011 to commemorate SMRT's 24th anniversary.\n\n===Circle Line Stage 6===\nOn 17 January 2013, the [[Land Transport Authority|Land Transport Authority (LTA)]] announced 'Circle Line Stage 6' which will finally 'close the circle'. To be completed by 2025,<ref>https://www.lta.gov.sg/content/ltagov/en/newsroom/2013/11/2/joint-news-release-by-the-land-transport-authority-sla---construction-of-circle-line-stage-6.html</ref> this 4&nbsp;km extension will run between [[Marina Bay MRT station|Marina Bay]] and [[HarbourFront MRT station|HarbourFront]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.mot.gov.sg/news-centre/news/Detail/Speech%20by%20Mr%20Lui%20Tuck%20Yew%20at%20visit%20to%20DTL1%20Chinatown%20Station%20on%2017%20January%202013/ |title=Speech by Mr Lui Tuck Yew at visit to DTL1 Chinatown Station on 17 January 2013 |website=MOT |accessdate=19 September 2019 |date=17 January 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lta.gov.sg/content/ltaweb/en/public-transport/projects/circle-line-6.html|title=Circle line 6 - Projects - Public Transport - Land Transport Authority|publisher=|accessdate=21 August 2016}}</ref> The extension will connect commuters between [[HarbourFront MRT station|HarbourFront]] to [[Marina Bay MRT station|Marina Bay]] and expand the rail network to the southern edge of the Central Business District. On 29 October 2015, LTA announced the station locations for Stage 6. The working names of the stations are [[Keppel MRT station|Keppel]], [[Cantonment MRT station|Cantonment]] and [[Prince Edward Road MRT station|Prince Edward]]. Tenders were called for construction between 2016 and 2017,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lta.gov.sg/apps/tender/default.aspx?scr=yes&Ref=882&scrdate=&fromdate=&todate=&keyword=keppel|title=Tender information {{!}} Land Transport Authority|website=www.lta.gov.sg|language=en|access-date=2017-04-23}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lta.gov.sg/apps/tender/default.aspx?scr=yes&Ref=&scrdate=&fromdate=&todate=&keyword=cantonment|title=Tender information {{!}} Land Transport Authority|website=www.lta.gov.sg|language=en|access-date=2017-04-23}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lta.gov.sg/apps/tender/default.aspx?scr=yes&Ref=&scrdate=&fromdate=&todate=&keyword=prince|title=Tender information {{!}} Land Transport Authority|website=www.lta.gov.sg|language=en|access-date=2017-04-23}}</ref> and demolition, diversion and utility works commenced in 2017.\n\nOn 15 May 2017, Land Transport Authority (LTA) invited the public to send in suggestions for names of the three new MRT stations. Their current working names are derived from their proximity to names of nearby locations. The public can also propose to keep their current names, which are Keppel, Cantonment and Prince Edward.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lta.gov.sg/apps/news/page.aspx?c=2&id=5cf30fa9-12bd-463d-a481-120c410dcb99|title=LTA Invites Public to Suggest MRT station Names for Circle line 6 stations {{!}} Press Room {{!}} Land Transport Authority|website=www.lta.gov.sg|language=en|access-date=2017-09-18}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/wanted-names-for-3-new-circle-line-stations-8847558| website=Channel NewsAsia| accessdate=15 May 2017| title=Wanted: Names for 3 new Circle line stations| date=15 May 2017}}</ref> On 28 September 2018, the LTA finalised the names for Keppel and Cantonment, while Prince Edward was finalised as Prince Edward Road.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/transport/excavation-for-circle-line-6-to-start-in-middle-of-next-year|title=Excavation for Circle Line 6 to start in middle of next year|date=2018-09-28|work=The Straits Times|access-date=2018-10-13|language=en}}</ref>\n\nConstruction of the Circle Line Stage 6 commenced in late 2017. A [[joint venture]] \u2013 by China State Construction Engineering (The Singapore branch) and Nishimatsu Construction \u2013 won the contract to build the new Keppel MRT station and its associated tunnels.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/first-circle-line-6-contracts-worth-s-1-75b-awarded-by-lta-9198368|title= First CCL6 contracts awarded by LTA|publisher=ChannelNewsAsia|access-date=12 October 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/construction-of-circle-line-6-to-start-by-end-of-2017-first-three-civil-contracts-awarded|title=Construction of Circle line 6 to start by end of 2017, first three civil contracts awarded|publisher=[[The Straits Times]]|access-date=2017-10-12}}</ref>\n\n==Incidents==\n===Nicoll Highway collapse===\n{{Main|Nicoll Highway collapse}}\nOn 20 April 2004, a section of the tunnel being built for the Circle Line collapsed, when a [[retaining wall]] used in the tunnel's construction gave way. This incident occurred near the proposed site of the [[Nicoll Highway MRT station|Nicoll Highway]] station, not far from the [[Merdeka Bridge, Singapore|Merdeka Bridge]]. The accident left a collapse zone that was {{convert|150|m|ft}} wide, {{convert|100|m|ft}} long, and {{convert|30|m|ft}} deep. Four workers were killed, three were injured.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.nas.gov.sg/archivesonline/data/pdfdoc/20050513987.pdf|title=COMMITTEE OF INQUIRY CONCLUDES STRING OF CRITICAL DESIGN ERRORS CAUSED COLLAPSE AT NICOLL HIGHWAY.|last=|first=|date=13 May 2005|website=|access-date=18 September 2017}}</ref>\n\nA criminal inquiry found the main contractor Nishimatsu Construction Company and joint venture partner firm Lum Chang Construction Company and their officers, as well as key [[Land Transport Authority]] officers responsible for the collapse. Several other officers and [[subcontractor]]s were reprimanded and issued warnings in connection with the accident.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nAs a result of this accident, the first phase of the Circle Line, previously scheduled to open in 2008, was completed in 2009 instead. The affected station has been shifted about {{convert|100|m|ft}} away from the accident site and is now located at Republic Avenue.\n\nThis accident had also resulted in stricter safety regulations for the construction of all future MRT lines. The shifting of the Nicoll Highway station also meant it can no longer serve as a terminus for the Bukit Timah Line, partially influencing the creation of the current [[Downtown MRT line|Downtown Line]].{{Citation needed|date=September 2017}}\n\n===Other incidents===\nOn 16 August 2007, the [[Building and Construction Authority]] (BCA) issued a stop-work order and revoked the contractor's tunnelling permit after a {{convert|7|m|ft|adj=on}} stretch of two lanes sank about {{convert|20|cm|in}}, close to the junction of Telok Blangah Road and Alexandra Road in the evening, resulting in a halting of tunnelling works.<ref>[http://www.straitstimes.com/Free/Story/STIStory_150531.html \"Stop-work order at Telok Blangah site is fourth this year on $6.7b MRT project\"] T. Rajan, [[The Straits Times]], 22 August 2007</ref>\n\nA section of the road above a construction site near [[Holland Road, Singapore|Holland Road]] caved in on the morning of 24 May 2008, creating a massive hole. The hole, directly in front of two private houses along Cornwall Gardens, measured 8 by 7 metres and was 3 metres deep. No one was injured, but the road was temporarily closed to traffic.<ref>[http://www.channelnewsasia.com/stories/singaporelocalnews/view/349771/1/.html \"Road above Circle line construction site caves in\"] CNA Live, [[Channel NewsAsia]], 24 May 2008</ref>\n\n===Line disruptions===\nOn 20 September 2011, a power fault disrupted train services on all 16 then-opened stations on the Circle Line. The four hours delay left thousands of commuters stranded during rush-hour. It was reported that [[leaks]] and a damaged [[electrical cable]] along the Circle Line were the cause of the disruption.<ref>{{cite news|title=Leaks, damaged cable cause of 4-hour delay on Circle line|url=http://www.straitstimes.com/BreakingNews/Singapore/Story/STIStory_717665.html|accessdate=19 October 2011|newspaper=The Straits Times|date=29 September 2011}}</ref> The disruption started at about 5.30 am. Train services were gradually restored from 8 am and all services were restored just before 10 am. [[Dakota MRT station|Dakota]] and [[Mountbatten MRT station|Mountbatten]] stations were the last two to resume operations.<ref>{{cite news|title=Thousands affected by Circle line disruption|url=http://www.channelnewsasia.com/stories/singaporelocalnews/view/1154288/1/.html|accessdate=19 October 2011|newspaper=Channel News Asia|date=20 September 2011}}</ref> Investigations were carried out. It was later found that a faulty cable beneath the platform level at Dakota station caused a power fault on Tuesday morning that affected train services at all 16 stations on the Circle Line.<ref>{{cite news|title=Faulty cable led to Circle line disruption|url=http://www.channelnewsasia.com/stories/singaporelocalnews/view/1154317/1/.html|accessdate=19 October 2011|newspaper=Channel News Asia|date=20 September 2011}}</ref> 27,000 passengers were affected by the disruption during the four hours delay, with bus bridging services plying the Circle Line route.<ref>{{cite news|title=Call for thorough probe on Circle line disruption|url=http://www.channelnewsasia.com/stories/singaporelocalnews/view/1154777/1/.html|accessdate=19 October 2011|newspaper=Channel News Asia|date=22 September 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn late August 2016, intermittent signal interference led to a five-day series of train disruptions. The issue reappeared in November.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.todayonline.com/singapore/no-service-6-circle-line-stations-disruption-caused-signal-fault-widens|title=Signal interference issue plagues Circle line again|newspaper=TODAYonline|access-date=2016-12-03}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/transport/circle-line-signal-fault-that-caused-train-disruptions-on-wednesday-morning|title=Circle line signal fault that caused train disruptions on Wednesday similar to problem in September: LTA, SMRT|date=2016-11-02|newspaper=The Straits Times|access-date=2016-12-03}}</ref> A team of [[Data science|data scientists]] explored the data and discovered via a Marey Chart visualization that it was caused by hardware problems, sending errant signals from a \"rogue\" train, PV46.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.techinasia.com/govtech-data-scientists-projects|title=Tech in Asia - Connecting Asia's startup ecosystem|website=www.techinasia.com|language=en-US|access-date=2016-12-03}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blog.data.gov.sg/how-we-caught-the-circle-line-rogue-train-with-data-79405c86ab6a|title=How the Circle line rogue train was caught with data|last=datagovsg|date=2016-12-01|website=Data.gov.sg Blog|access-date=2016-12-03}}</ref>\n\n==Overview==\n===Route===\n[[File:MRT Route Map CC.svg|450px]]\n\nAs the name implies, the Circle Line is an [[orbit]]al [[circle route]] linking all [[radial route]]s leading to the [[Downtown Core (Singapore)|city]]. It also covers many parts of the [[Central Area, Singapore|Central Area]]. From [[Promenade MRT station|Promenade]], the line branches into two, with one branch terminating at [[Dhoby Ghaut MRT station|Dhoby Ghaut]], and the other at [[Marina Bay MRT station|Marina Bay]]. The Circle Line interchanges with all other Mass Rapid Transit lines within Singapore, such as the [[North South MRT line|North South Line]] and [[East West MRT line|East West Line]], which shortens travelling time for commuters by shortening trips between northern, eastern and western Singapore.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lta.gov.sg/content/ltaweb/en/public-transport/projects/circle-line.html|title=Circle line {{!}} Projects {{!}} Public Transport {{!}} Land Transport Authority|website=www.lta.gov.sg|language=en|access-date=2017-09-18}}</ref>\n\n===Stations===\n\n{{main|List of Circle MRT line station names}}\n{|class=\"wikitable\" border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"2\" style=\"margin-left: 1em; margin-bottom: 1em; color: black; border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 95%\"\n|- align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#{{SMRT color|Circle}}\" style=\"color:white\"\n|'''Station Number'''\n|'''Station Name'''\n|'''Images'''\n|'''Interchange/Notes'''\n|-\n|{{SMRT code 3I/C|CC|1|NS|24|NE|6}}||[[Dhoby Ghaut MRT station|Dhoby Ghaut]]||[[File:DhobyGhaut-CCLPlatform.JPG|100px]]||Interchange with the [[North South MRT line|'''{{fontcolor|#dc241f|North South line}}''']] and the [[North East MRT line|'''{{fontcolor|#9016b2|North East line}}''']]\n|-\n|{{SMRT code|CC|2}}||[[Bras Basah MRT station|Bras Basah]]||[[File:Bras Basah MRT Station, 2014 (04).JPG|frameless|100x100px]]||\n|-\n|{{SMRT code|CC|3}}||[[Esplanade MRT station|Esplanade]]||[[File:Esplanade-CCLStation.JPG|100px]]||\n|-\n|{{SMRT code 2I/C|CC|4|DT|15}}||[[Promenade MRT station|Promenade]]||[[File:Promenade-CCLPlatform.JPG|100px]]||Interchange with the [[Downtown MRT line|'''{{fontcolor|#0354A6|Downtown line}}''']]\nChange for train services towards [[Bayfront MRT station|Bayfront]] or [[Marina Bay MRT station|Marina Bay]] stations\n|-\n|{{SMRT code|CC|5}}||[[Nicoll Highway MRT station|Nicoll Highway]]||[[File:NicollHighway-CCLPlatform.JPG|100px]]||&nbsp;\n|-\n|{{SMRT code|CC|6}}||[[Stadium MRT station|Stadium]]||[[File:Stadium MRT Station.jpg|frameless|133x133px]]||Marina Bay shuttle terminus during off-peak hours\n|-\n|{{SMRT code|CC|7}}||[[Mountbatten MRT station|Mountbatten]]||[[File:Mountbatten-CCLPlatform.JPG|100px]]||\n|-\n|{{SMRT code|CC|8}}||[[Dakota MRT station|Dakota]]||[[File:Dakota-CCLPlatform.JPG|100px]]||&nbsp;\n|-\n|{{SMRT code 2I/C|CC|9|EW|8}}||[[Paya Lebar MRT station|Paya Lebar]]||[[File:PayaLebar-CCLPlatform-TopView.JPG|100px]]||Interchange with the [[East West MRT line|'''{{fontcolor|#009530|East West line}}''']]\n|-\n|{{SMRT code 2I/C|CC|10|DT|26}}||[[MacPherson MRT station|MacPherson]]||[[File:MacPherson-CCLPlatform.JPG|100px]]||Interchange with the [[Downtown MRT line|'''{{fontcolor|#0354A6|Downtown line}}''']]\n|-\n|{{SMRT code|CC|11}}||[[Tai Seng MRT station|Tai Seng]]||[[File:CC11 Tai Seng MRT Platform.jpg|100px]]||&nbsp;\n|-\n|{{SMRT code|CC|12}}||[[Bartley MRT station|Bartley]]||[[File:Bartley MRT Station.jpg|frameless|99x99px]]||&nbsp;\n|-\n|{{SMRT code 2I/C|CC|13|NE|12}}||[[Serangoon MRT station|Serangoon]]||[[File:CCL Platform of Serangoon MRT Station.jpg|frameless|99x99px]]||Interchange with the [[North East MRT line|'''{{fontcolor|#9016b2|North East line}}''']]\n|-\n|{{SMRT code|CC|14}}||[[Lorong Chuan MRT station|Lorong Chuan]]||[[File:Lorong Chuan MRT for Wikipedia.jpg|100px]]||&nbsp;\n|-\n|{{SMRT code 2I/C|CC|15|NS|17}}||[[Bishan MRT station|Bishan]]||[[File:CC15 Bishan MRT Station Platform.jpg|100px]]||Interchange with the [[North South MRT line|'''{{fontcolor|#dc241f|North South line}}''']]\n|-\n|{{SMRT code|CC|16}} ||[[Marymount MRT station|Marymount]]||[[File:CC16 Marymount Platform A.jpg|100px]]||&nbsp;\n|-\n|{{SMRT code 2I/C|CC|17|TE|9}}||[[Caldecott MRT station|Caldecott]]||[[File:CC17 Caldecott Platform.jpg|frameless|100x100px]]||Interchange with the [[Thomson-East Coast MRT line|'''{{fontcolor|#734538|Thomson-East Coast line}}''']] <small>''(2020)''</small>\n|-\n|{{SMRT code|CC|18}} ||''[[Bukit Brown MRT station|Bukit Brown]]''||[[File:CC18 Bukit Brown shell station tunnel 2.jpg|frameless|100x100px]]\n|Reserve station to be open at a later date\n|-\n|{{SMRT code 2I/C|CC|19|DT|9}}||[[Botanic Gardens MRT station|Botanic Gardens]]||[[File:CC19 Botanic Gardens MRT Station platform.jpg|100px]]||Interchange with the [[Downtown MRT line|'''{{fontcolor|#0354A6|Downtown line}}''']]  \n|-\n|{{SMRT code|CC|20}}||[[Farrer Road MRT station|Farrer Road]]||[[File:CC20 Farrer Road Platform level.jpg|100px]]||&nbsp;\n|-\n|{{SMRT code|CC|21}}||[[Holland Village MRT station|Holland Village]]||[[File:Interior of Holland Village MRT Station - 20111008.jpg|100px]]||&nbsp;\n|-\n|{{SMRT code 2I/C|CC|22|EW|21}}||[[Buona Vista MRT station|Buona Vista]]||[[File:Interior of the Circle Line section of Buona Vista MRT Station, Singapore - 20110820.jpg|100px]]||Interchange with the [[East West MRT line|'''{{fontcolor|#009530|East West line}}''']]\n|-\n|{{SMRT code|CC|23}}||[[one-north MRT station|one-north]]||[[File:CC23 one-north Platform B.jpg|100px]]||&nbsp;\n|-\n|{{SMRT code|CC|24}}||[[Kent Ridge MRT station|Kent Ridge]]||[[File:CC24 Kent Ridge Platform A.jpg|100px]]||&nbsp;\n|-\n|{{SMRT code|CC|25}}||[[Haw Par Villa MRT station|Haw Par Villa]]||[[File:CC25 Haw Par Villa Exit A.jpg|100px]]||&nbsp;\n|-\n|{{SMRT code|CC|26}}||[[Pasir Panjang MRT station|Pasir Panjang]]||[[File:Platform level of Pasir Panjang MRT Station, Singapore - 20111002.jpg|100px]]||&nbsp;\n|-\n|{{SMRT code|CC|27}}||[[Labrador Park MRT station|Labrador Park]]||[[File:CC27 Labrador Park Platform B.jpg|100px]]||&nbsp;\n|-\n|{{SMRT code|CC|28}}||[[Telok Blangah MRT station|Telok Blangah]]||[[File:CC28 Telok Blangah Platform A.jpg|100px]]||&nbsp;\n|-\n|{{SMRT code 2I/C|CC|29|NE|1}}||[[HarbourFront MRT station|HarbourFront]]||[[File:CC29 Harbourfront Exit A with train.jpg|100px]]||Interchange with the [[North East MRT line|'''{{fontcolor|#9016b2|North East line}}''']]\n|-\n!colspan=4|Stage 6 <small>''(under construction, to be ready by 2025)''</small>\n|-\n|{{SMRT code|CC|30}}||[[Keppel MRT station|Keppel]]||||\n|-\n|{{SMRT code|CC|31}}||[[Cantonment MRT station|Cantonment]]||||\n|-\n|{{SMRT code|CC|32}}||[[Prince Edward Road MRT station|Prince Edward Road]]||||\n|-\n!colspan=4|Circle Line extension\n|-\n|{{SMRT code 2I/C|CE|1|DT|16}}<br>{{SMRT code 2I/C|CC|34|DT|16}} (from 2025)||[[Bayfront MRT station|Bayfront]]||[[File:CE1 Bayfront Platform B.jpg|100px]]||Cross-Platform Interchange with the [[Downtown MRT line|'''{{fontcolor|#0354A6|Downtown line}}''']]\n|-\n|{{SMRT code 3I/C|CE|2|NS|27|TE|20}}<br>{{SMRT code 3I/C|CC|33|NS|27|TE|20}} (from 2025)||[[Marina Bay MRT station|Marina Bay]]||[[File:CE2 Marina Bay Platform A.jpg|100px]]||Interchange with the [[North South MRT line|'''{{fontcolor|#dc241f|North South line}}''']] and the [[Thomson-East Coast MRT line|'''{{fontcolor|#734538|Thomson-East Coast line}}''']] <small>''(2021)''</small>\n|}\nThe Circle Line's numbering scheme reserves station code \"CC18\" for future use.\n\n==Rolling stock==\nThe [[rolling stock]] consists of 40<ref>{{cite speech | url = http://www.news.gov.sg/public/sgpc/en/media_releases/agencies/mot/speech/S-20120504-1/AttachmentPar/0/file/Tuas%20West%20Extension%20Groundbreaking%20Ceremony%20Speech%20on%20040512_media.pdf | title = Tuas West Extension Groundbreaking Ceremony Speech | publisher = Land Transport Authority | date = 4 May 2012 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20130929131926/http://www.news.gov.sg/public/sgpc/en/media_releases/agencies/mot/speech/S-20120504-1/AttachmentPar/0/file/Tuas%20West%20Extension%20Groundbreaking%20Ceremony%20Speech%20on%20040512_media.pdf | archivedate = 29 September 2013 }}</ref> [[Alstom Metropolis C830]] trains<ref>[http://app.lta.gov.sg/corp_press_content.asp?start=785 AWARD OF ELECTRICAL & MECHANICAL SYSTEMS CONTRACT 830 FOR THE MARINA line] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110527043441/http://app.lta.gov.sg/corp_press_content.asp?start=785 |date=2011-05-27 }}</ref> running in three-car formation. They are stabled at [[Kim Chuan Depot]], the world's largest underground depot when it opened in 2009.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/transport/biggest-underground-train-depot-set-to-become-even-bigger|title=Biggest underground train depot set to become even bigger|website=The Straits Times|access-date=2016-03-04}}</ref>  24 new [[Alstom Metropolis & Shanghai Electric C830C]] trains were delivered to SMRT from end July 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://app.lta.gov.sg/apps/news/page.aspx?c=2&id=5qmktlgi52sor9rc5r00c6xm8pg371lwhgx5hvtwu8381p6o95 |title=LTA and SMRT Award Contracts for New Trains and Re-Signalling Project |date=1 February 2012 |accessdate=16 November 2013 |publisher=Land Transport Authority |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130929162504/http://app.lta.gov.sg/apps/news/page.aspx?c=2&id=5qmktlgi52sor9rc5r00c6xm8pg371lwhgx5hvtwu8381p6o95 |archivedate=29 September 2013 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.alstom.com/press-centre/2012/2/80885/ | title=Alstom to supply 34 Metropolis trains and upgrade signaling on the system | date=3 February 2012 | accessdate=16 November 2013 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131231010930/http://www.alstom.com/press-centre/2012/2/80885/ | archivedate=31 December 2013 }}</ref> They began operation on 26 June 2015. Currently, all 24 C830Cs are in revenue service.\n\nThe automated CBTC system on board relies on \"continuous two-way digital communication\" between each controlled train and the control centre.\n\nTo facilitate the extension of the line with the construction of Stage 6, a tender for additional trains for the line was published on 31 March 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lta.gov.sg/apps/tender/default.aspx?scr=yes&Ref=851E&scrdate=&fromdate=&todate=&keyword=|title=Tender information {{!}} Land Transport Authority|website=www.lta.gov.sg|language=en|access-date=2017-04-23}}</ref>\n\n==Train control==\nThe Circle Line is equipped with [[Alstom]] Urbalis 300 [[Communications-based train control]] (CBTC) [[moving block]] signalling system on the MASTRIA system with [[Automatic train control]] (ATC) under [[Automatic train operation]] (ATO) GoA 4 (UTO). The subsystems consist of [[Automatic train protection]] (ATP) to govern train speed, Iconis Automatic Train Supervision (ATS) to track and schedule trains and Smartlock [[Computer-based interlocking]] (CBI) system that prevents incorrect signal and track points to be set.<!--Note:Please do not delete any hidden content in the train control section-->\n\nTrain Data Management System (TDMS) which concentrate and dispatch the rolling stock information with fixed equipment. The IAGO Waveguide communications network has the capability to transmit video and is almost maintenance-free. Base stations are located within the signalling equipment room.\n\nAutomatic [[platform screen doors]] supplied by [[Westinghouse Rail Systems|Westinghouse]] provide safety for commuters, offering protection from arriving and departing trains.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|3}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Commons category-inline|Mass Rapid Transit (Singapore) Circle Line}}\n* [http://www.lta.gov.sg/content/ltaweb/en/public-transport/projects/circle-line.html Circle line]\n* [https://www.lta.gov.sg/content/dam/ltagov/who_we_are/statistics_and_publications/books/pdf/Circle_Line_Book.pdf LTA's commemorative book detailing the construction of the Circle Line]\n\n{{Singapore MRT stations|circle=yes}}\n{{Rail transport in Singapore}}\n{{Urban Rail Transit in ASEAN}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Circle MRT line}}\n[[Category:Mass Rapid Transit (Singapore) lines]]\n[[Category:Railway lines opened in 2009]]\n[[Category:Railway loop lines]]\n[[Category:2009 establishments in Singapore]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|the rapid transit system in Singapore|the rapid transit system in Malaysia|MRT Circle Line}}\n{{Infobox rail line\n| name                            = [[File:MRT Singapore Destination 8 (1).png|25px]] [[File:MRT Singapore Destination 9.png|25px]] [[File:MRT Singapore Destination 10.png|25px]]<br />Circle Line\n| color                           = {{SMRT color|Circle}}\n| native_name                     = {{nobold|{{native name|ms|Laluan MRT Bulatan}}<br />{{native name|zh|\u5730\u94c1\u73af\u7ebf|italics=off}}<br />{{native name|ta|\u0b87\u0ba3\u0bc8\u0baa\u0bcd\u0baa\u0bc1 \u0b8e\u0bae\u0bcd\u0b86\u0bb0\u0bcd\u0b9f\u0bbf \u0bb5\u0bb4\u0bbf|italics=off}}<!--end nobold:-->}}\n| logo                            = Circle Line logo.svg\n| logo_width                      = \n| image                           = CC15 Bishan during peak hours.jpg\n| image_width                     = 300px\n| caption                         = C830C trainset at [[Bishan MRT station|Bishan station]] during peak hours\n| type                            = [[Rapid transit]]\n| system                          = [[Mass Rapid Transit (Singapore)]]\n| status                          = Operational<br />Under construction (Stage 6)\n| locale                          = \n| start                           = [[Dhoby Ghaut MRT station|Dhoby Ghaut]]<br />[[Stadium MRT station|Stadium]] (All trains departing from Marina Bay will end here during off-peak hours)\n| end                             = [[HarbourFront MRT station|HarbourFront]]<br />[[Marina Bay MRT station|Marina Bay]]\n| stations                        = 30 (Operational)\n<br />3 (Under construction)\n| routes                          = 3\n| daily_ridership                 = 398,000 (May 2015)\n| open                            = {{start date and age|df=yes|2009|05|28}} (Stage 3)<br />{{start date and age|df=yes|2010|04|17}} (Stages 1 and 2)<br />{{start date and age|df=yes|2011|10|08}} (Stages 4 and 5)<br />{{start date and age|df=yes|2012|01|14}} (Circle Line extension)\n| planopen                        = {{start date and age|df=yes|2025}} (Stage 6)<br />20?? ([[Bukit Brown MRT station]])\n| close                           = \n| owner                           = [[Land Transport Authority]]\n| operator                        = [[SMRT Trains|SMRT Trains Ltd]] ([[SMRT Corporation]])\n| character                       = Fully Underground\n| stock                           = [[Alstom Metropolis C830|C830]] <br /> [[Alstom Metropolis C830C|C830C]] <br /> [[Alstom Metropolis C851E|C851E]] (Future)\n| linelength                      = {{convert|35.5|km|mi|abbr=on}} (Operational) <br /> {{convert|4|km|mi|abbr=on}} (''Under construction'')\n| tracklength                     = \n| tracks                          = \n| gauge                           = {{track gauge|sg|allk=on}}\n| electrification                 = 750 V [[Direct current|DC]] [[third rail]]\n| speed                           = limit of {{convert|78|km/h|mph|abbr=on}}\n| elevation                       = \n| map                             = {{MRT route/Circle|navbar=1|legend=0|collapsed=no}}\n| map_state                       = hide\n| depot                           = [[Kim Chuan Depot|Kim Chuan]]\n}}\n\nThe '''Circle MRT Line''' ('''CCL''') is a medium-capacity [[Mass Rapid Transit (Singapore)|Mass Rapid Transit]] line in [[Singapore]] operated by [[SMRT Corporation]]. It runs a currently incomplete [[Circle route|loop]] from [[Dhoby Ghaut MRT station|Dhoby Ghaut]] station in the [[Central Area, Singapore|city area of Singapore]] to [[HarbourFront MRT station|HarbourFront]] station in the south via [[Bishan MRT station|Bishan station]] in [[Central Area, Singapore|Central Singapore]]. It also has a branch to [[Marina Bay MRT station|Marina Bay]] station from [[Promenade MRT station|Promenade]] station, which will be extended to Harbourfront station in the future, forming a complete loop. Coloured orange on the rail map, the fully-underground line is {{convert|35.5|km|mi}} long with 30 stations. Travelling from one end of the line to the other takes about an hour.\n\nIt is the second in Singapore to be [[automatic train operation|completely automated]] and driverless and is among the [[List of driverless trains|world's longest]] driverless [[rapid transit]] lines.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.railway-technology.com/contractors/suburban/alstom/press5.html | title=ALSTOM chosen for the world's longest fully automated metro line in Singapore | publisher=railway-technology.com | date=2002-02-20 }}</ref> As of May 2015, the daily ridership is 398,000.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/transport/four-more-trains-for-circle-line-as-ridership-rises|title=Four more trains for Circle line as ridership rises|website=The Straits Times|access-date=2016-03-04}}</ref> It is also the first [[Medium-capacity rail transport system|medium capacity line]] in Singapore, with each Circle Line train having a three-car configuration. \n\nThe line is the fourth MRT line to be opened, with the first stage (from [[Bartley MRT station|Bartley]] to [[Marymount MRT station|Marymount]] stations) commencing operations on 28 May 2009. The next stage to Dhoby Ghaut station was completed on 17 April 2010,  with the next stage to Harbourfront opening on 8 October 2011, and the last two-station extension to Marina Bay station opening on 14 February 2012. The last stage of the line from Harbourfront to Marina Bay will be completed in 2026, completing the loop.\n\n==History==\n===Original Plans===\n\nThe Circle Line dates back to 1989, when then Minister for Communications and Information, Dr [[Yeo Ning Hong]] stated that such a system would be \"feasible when the population reaches four million.\"<ref>{{cite web |title=Circle line 'needed with 4 million people' |url=https://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article/straitstimes19891104-1.2.2 |website=The Straits Times (retrieved from NLB) |accessdate=6 October 2019 |date=4 November 1989}}</ref>\n\nFeasibility studies for the proposed line commenced on 11 October 1994. The Circle Line was first named as the Marina Line on 12 June 1998, initially planned as a 12-station underground line (upgraded from LRT to 3-car MRT line), starting from [[Chinatown MRT station|Chinatown]] and [[Dhoby Ghaut MRT station|Dhoby Ghaut]] via the [[Stadium MRT station|National Stadium]] to either [[Kallang MRT station|Kallang]] or [[Paya Lebar MRT station|Paya Lebar]] station.<ref>{{cite web |title=Signing of E&M contracts ceremony |url=http://www.nas.gov.sg/archivesonline/data/pdfdoc/1998061201.htm |website=NAS |accessdate=23 November 2019 |date=12 June 1998}}</ref> However, the Chinatown leg was later truncated and was reduced to 6 stations up to [[Stadium MRT station|Stadium]] station. A part of the truncated leg later became part of the [[Downtown MRT line|Downtown line]]<ref>{{cite book|last1=Colin|first1=Cheong|title=The Circle Line, Linking All Lines|date=2012|isbn=978-981-4342-02-5|page=36}}</ref> On the other hand, a further extension towards Upper Paya Lebar was announced on 28 April 2001.<ref>{{cite web |title=Circle Line and Kallang/Paya Lebar Expressway |url=https://www.nas.gov.sg/archivesonline/data/pdfdoc/2001042808.htm |website=NAS |accessdate=23 November 2019 |date=28 April 2001}}</ref> The Marina Line was also merged with an [[Light Rail Transit (Singapore)|LRT line]] that goes from [[Paya Lebar MRT station|Paya Lebar]] to [[Buona Vista MRT station|Buona Vista]] via [[Serangoon MRT station|Serangoon]] and [[Bishan MRT station|Bishan]] to form Circle Line Stage 3 on 20 January 2003,<ref>{{cite web |title=Circle Line Stage 3 |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20030526200150/http://www.lta.gov.sg/Menu_NewsRelease.htm |website=LTA |accessdate=15 July 2019 |date=20 January 2003}}</ref> and subsequently Circle Line Stage 4 and 5 on 12 December 2003 when Stage 4 was extended from [[Buona Vista MRT station|Buona Vista]] to World Trade Centre to close up the link and to provide connectivity from the west to Sentosa, and it became the full Circle line in the end.<ref>{{cite web |title=Completing the Circle via Holland V |url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article/today20031213-1.2.3 |website=Today (retrieved from NLB) |accessdate=6 September 2019 |date=13 December 2003}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=News 5 Tonight (12 December 2003) |url=http://www.nas.gov.sg/archivesonline/audiovisual_records/record-details/57de1bd1-1164-11e3-83d5-0050568939ad |website=MediaCorp (retrieved from NAS) |accessdate=19 July 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190719031728/http://www.nas.gov.sg/archivesonline/audiovisual_records/record-details/57de1bd1-1164-11e3-83d5-0050568939ad |archive-date=19 July 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Stations in Circle Line that were a part of the original Marina Line plans include [[Dhoby Ghaut MRT station|Dhoby Ghaut]], [[Bras Basah MRT station|Bras Basah]], [[Esplanade MRT station|Esplanade]], [[Promenade MRT station|Promenade]], [[Nicoll Highway MRT station|Nicoll Highway]] and [[Stadium MRT station|Stadium]]. On 8 August 2001, [[SMRT Corporation|SMRT]] won the bid and was appointed the operator of the Circle Line.<ref>{{cite web |title=Appointment Of Operator For The Circle Line |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20021224094604fw_/http://app.internet.gov.sg/scripts/lta/3_press_content.asp?start=315 |website=LTA |accessdate=19 July 2019 |date=8 August 2001}}</ref>\n\n===Construction of the initial stages===\n[[File:Construction of Bishan MRT Circle Line 2005-03-29.JPG|thumb|left|The construction of Bishan station.]]\n[[File:CC18BukitBrown.jpg|thumb|left|Bukit Brown station, the only \"shell station\"]]\n\nConstruction started on 13 March 2002 for Stage 1, 5 September 2002 for Stage 2, May 2003 for Stage 3, and January 2005 for Stages 4 and 5. The Circle Line was supposed to be opened in stages from 2006 to 2010, with an estimated cost of S$6.7 billion, but the [[Nicoll Highway collapse]] caused the opening of the first stage to be delayed to 28 May 2009. When the line fully opened on 8 October 2011, the cost of construction had escalated to nearly S$10 billion.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite book|last1=Colin|first1=Cheong|title=The Circle Line, Linking All Lines|date=2012|isbn=978-981-4342-02-5|page=46}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://motoring.asiaone.com/Motoring/Motorworld/Story/A1Story20090818-161682.html|title=Circle Line could cost taxpayers $10 billion|publisher=AsiaOne Motoring|accessdate=21 August 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111008134221/http://motoring.asiaone.com/Motoring/Motorworld/Story/A1Story20090818-161682.html|archivedate=8 October 2011}}</ref> Due to the re-alignment of the [[Nicoll Highway MRT station|Nicoll Highway station]] to a new location, the station is only two-thirds the size of the original plan before the collapse. It was located {{convert|100|m|ft}} away from the original site.<ref>[http://www.straitstimes.com/Free/Story/STIStory_157967.html \"Circle line will exceed $6.7b budget\"] Christopher Tan, [[The Straits Times]], 15 September 2007</ref> Some stations on the Circle Line were initially designed as 'shell stations', but the decision was made to open Caldecott and Haw Par Villa (previously Thomson and West Coast respectively), which leaves [[Bukit Brown MRT station|Bukit Brown]] as the only unopened station on the line.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\nStage 3, a {{convert|5|km|mi}} five-station segment stretching from [[Bartley MRT station|Bartley]] to [[Marymount MRT station|Marymount]], was the first section of the line opened on 28 May 2009. Initial ridership on this section was lower than estimated, at 32,000 passengers per day (ppd) instead of the estimated 55,000 ppd.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.channelnewsasia.com/stories/singaporelocalnews/view/449350/1/.html|title=LTA completes final tunnelling work on Circle Line|publisher=Channel News Asia|date=17 August 2009|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121019161745/http://www.channelnewsasia.com/stories/singaporelocalnews/view/449350/1/.html|archivedate=19 October 2012}}</ref> Tunneling works for the entire line were completed on 17 August 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.straitstimes.com/Breaking%2BNews/Singapore/Story/STIStory_417858.html?vgnmr=1|title=Circle Line: The longest dig|publisher=The Straits Times|date=17 August 2009|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090821173820/https://www.straitstimes.com/Breaking%2BNews/Singapore/Story/STIStory_417858.html?vgnmr=1|archivedate=21 August 2009}}</ref> Stages 1 and 2 started operations on 17 April 2010,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://app.lta.gov.sg/corp_press_content.asp?start=kpt8zx9w8ik53wi33gr59p754348fsj35b9glldouy8ndlh7kb |title=Circle Line from Bartley to Dhoby Ghaut to Open 17 April |accessdate=2010-01-26 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110621220756/http://app.lta.gov.sg/corp_press_content.asp?start=kpt8zx9w8ik53wi33gr59p754348fsj35b9glldouy8ndlh7kb |archivedate=2011-06-21 }}</ref> Stages 4 and 5 on 8 October 2011,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sg.news.yahoo.com/blogs/singaporescene/final-batch-circle-line-stations-open-004355257.html|title=Train crowding to ease with launch of full Circle line: Minister Lui|publisher=|accessdate=21 August 2016}}</ref> and the final two-station Circle Line Extension on 14 January 2012. The line was also fully completed on 8 October 2011 to commemorate SMRT's 24th anniversary.\n\n===Circle Line Stage 6===\nOn 17 January 2013, the [[Land Transport Authority|Land Transport Authority (LTA)]] announced 'Circle Line Stage 6' which will finally 'close the circle'. To be completed by 2025,<ref>https://www.lta.gov.sg/content/ltagov/en/newsroom/2013/11/2/joint-news-release-by-the-land-transport-authority-sla---construction-of-circle-line-stage-6.html</ref> this 4&nbsp;km extension will run between [[Marina Bay MRT station|Marina Bay]] and [[HarbourFront MRT station|HarbourFront]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.mot.gov.sg/news-centre/news/Detail/Speech%20by%20Mr%20Lui%20Tuck%20Yew%20at%20visit%20to%20DTL1%20Chinatown%20Station%20on%2017%20January%202013/ |title=Speech by Mr Lui Tuck Yew at visit to DTL1 Chinatown Station on 17 January 2013 |website=MOT |accessdate=19 September 2019 |date=17 January 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lta.gov.sg/content/ltaweb/en/public-transport/projects/circle-line-6.html|title=Circle line 6 - Projects - Public Transport - Land Transport Authority|publisher=|accessdate=21 August 2016}}</ref> The extension will connect commuters between [[HarbourFront MRT station|HarbourFront]] to [[Marina Bay MRT station|Marina Bay]] and expand the rail network to the southern edge of the Central Business District. On 29 October 2015, LTA announced the station locations for Stage 6. The working names of the stations are [[Keppel MRT station|Keppel]], [[Cantonment MRT station|Cantonment]] and [[Prince Edward Road MRT station|Prince Edward]]. Tenders were called for construction between 2016 and 2017,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lta.gov.sg/apps/tender/default.aspx?scr=yes&Ref=882&scrdate=&fromdate=&todate=&keyword=keppel|title=Tender information {{!}} Land Transport Authority|website=www.lta.gov.sg|language=en|access-date=2017-04-23}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lta.gov.sg/apps/tender/default.aspx?scr=yes&Ref=&scrdate=&fromdate=&todate=&keyword=cantonment|title=Tender information {{!}} Land Transport Authority|website=www.lta.gov.sg|language=en|access-date=2017-04-23}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lta.gov.sg/apps/tender/default.aspx?scr=yes&Ref=&scrdate=&fromdate=&todate=&keyword=prince|title=Tender information {{!}} Land Transport Authority|website=www.lta.gov.sg|language=en|access-date=2017-04-23}}</ref> and demolition, diversion and utility works commenced in 2017.\n\nOn 15 May 2017, Land Transport Authority (LTA) invited the public to send in suggestions for names of the three new MRT stations. Their current working names are derived from their proximity to names of nearby locations. The public can also propose to keep their current names, which are Keppel, Cantonment and Prince Edward.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lta.gov.sg/apps/news/page.aspx?c=2&id=5cf30fa9-12bd-463d-a481-120c410dcb99|title=LTA Invites Public to Suggest MRT station Names for Circle line 6 stations {{!}} Press Room {{!}} Land Transport Authority|website=www.lta.gov.sg|language=en|access-date=2017-09-18}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/wanted-names-for-3-new-circle-line-stations-8847558| website=Channel NewsAsia| accessdate=15 May 2017| title=Wanted: Names for 3 new Circle line stations| date=15 May 2017}}</ref> On 28 September 2018, the LTA finalised the names for Keppel and Cantonment, while Prince Edward was finalised as Prince Edward Road.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/transport/excavation-for-circle-line-6-to-start-in-middle-of-next-year|title=Excavation for Circle Line 6 to start in middle of next year|date=2018-09-28|work=The Straits Times|access-date=2018-10-13|language=en}}</ref>\n\nConstruction of the Circle Line Stage 6 commenced in late 2017. A [[joint venture]] \u2013 by China State Construction Engineering (The Singapore branch) and Nishimatsu Construction \u2013 won the contract to build the new Keppel MRT station and its associated tunnels.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/first-circle-line-6-contracts-worth-s-1-75b-awarded-by-lta-9198368|title= First CCL6 contracts awarded by LTA|publisher=ChannelNewsAsia|access-date=12 October 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/construction-of-circle-line-6-to-start-by-end-of-2017-first-three-civil-contracts-awarded|title=Construction of Circle line 6 to start by end of 2017, first three civil contracts awarded|publisher=[[The Straits Times]]|access-date=2017-10-12}}</ref>\n\n==Incidents==\n===Nicoll Highway collapse===\n{{Main|Nicoll Highway collapse}}\nOn 20 April 2004, a section of the tunnel being built for the Circle Line collapsed, when a [[retaining wall]] used in the tunnel's construction gave way. This incident occurred near the proposed site of the [[Nicoll Highway MRT station|Nicoll Highway]] station, not far from the [[Merdeka Bridge, Singapore|Merdeka Bridge]]. The accident left a collapse zone that was {{convert|150|m|ft}} wide, {{convert|100|m|ft}} long, and {{convert|30|m|ft}} deep. Four workers were killed, three were injured.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.nas.gov.sg/archivesonline/data/pdfdoc/20050513987.pdf|title=COMMITTEE OF INQUIRY CONCLUDES STRING OF CRITICAL DESIGN ERRORS CAUSED COLLAPSE AT NICOLL HIGHWAY.|last=|first=|date=13 May 2005|website=|access-date=18 September 2017}}</ref>\n\nA criminal inquiry found the main contractor Nishimatsu Construction Company and joint venture partner firm Lum Chang Construction Company and their officers, as well as key [[Land Transport Authority]] officers responsible for the collapse. Several other officers and [[subcontractor]]s were reprimanded and issued warnings in connection with the accident.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nAs a result of this accident, the first phase of the Circle Line, previously scheduled to open in 2008, was completed in 2009 instead. The affected station has been shifted about {{convert|100|m|ft}} away from the accident site and is now located at Republic Avenue.\n\nThis accident had also resulted in stricter safety regulations for the construction of all future MRT lines. The shifting of the Nicoll Highway station also meant it can no longer serve as a terminus for the Bukit Timah Line, partially influencing the creation of the current [[Downtown MRT line|Downtown Line]].{{Citation needed|date=September 2017}}\n\n===Other incidents===\nOn 16 August 2007, the [[Building and Construction Authority]] (BCA) issued a stop-work order and revoked the contractor's tunnelling permit after a {{convert|7|m|ft|adj=on}} stretch of two lanes sank about {{convert|20|cm|in}}, close to the junction of Telok Blangah Road and Alexandra Road in the evening, resulting in a halting of tunnelling works.<ref>[http://www.straitstimes.com/Free/Story/STIStory_150531.html \"Stop-work order at Telok Blangah site is fourth this year on $6.7b MRT project\"] T. Rajan, [[The Straits Times]], 22 August 2007</ref>\n\nA section of the road above a construction site near [[Holland Road, Singapore|Holland Road]] caved in on the morning of 24 May 2008, creating a massive hole. The hole, directly in front of two private houses along Cornwall Gardens, measured 8 by 7 metres and was 3 metres deep. No one was injured, but the road was temporarily closed to traffic.<ref>[http://www.channelnewsasia.com/stories/singaporelocalnews/view/349771/1/.html \"Road above Circle line construction site caves in\"] CNA Live, [[Channel NewsAsia]], 24 May 2008</ref>\n\n===Line disruptions===\nOn 20 September 2011, a power fault disrupted train services on all 16 then-opened stations on the Circle Line. The four hours delay left thousands of commuters stranded during rush-hour. It was reported that [[leaks]] and a damaged [[electrical cable]] along the Circle Line were the cause of the disruption.<ref>{{cite news|title=Leaks, damaged cable cause of 4-hour delay on Circle line|url=http://www.straitstimes.com/BreakingNews/Singapore/Story/STIStory_717665.html|accessdate=19 October 2011|newspaper=The Straits Times|date=29 September 2011}}</ref> The disruption started at about 5.30 am. Train services were gradually restored from 8 am and all services were restored just before 10 am. [[Dakota MRT station|Dakota]] and [[Mountbatten MRT station|Mountbatten]] stations were the last two to resume operations.<ref>{{cite news|title=Thousands affected by Circle line disruption|url=http://www.channelnewsasia.com/stories/singaporelocalnews/view/1154288/1/.html|accessdate=19 October 2011|newspaper=Channel News Asia|date=20 September 2011}}</ref> Investigations were carried out. It was later found that a faulty cable beneath the platform level at Dakota station caused a power fault on Tuesday morning that affected train services at all 16 stations on the Circle Line.<ref>{{cite news|title=Faulty cable led to Circle line disruption|url=http://www.channelnewsasia.com/stories/singaporelocalnews/view/1154317/1/.html|accessdate=19 October 2011|newspaper=Channel News Asia|date=20 September 2011}}</ref> 27,000 passengers were affected by the disruption during the four hours delay, with bus bridging services plying the Circle Line route.<ref>{{cite news|title=Call for thorough probe on Circle line disruption|url=http://www.channelnewsasia.com/stories/singaporelocalnews/view/1154777/1/.html|accessdate=19 October 2011|newspaper=Channel News Asia|date=22 September 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn late August 2016, intermittent signal interference led to a five-day series of train disruptions. The issue reappeared in November.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.todayonline.com/singapore/no-service-6-circle-line-stations-disruption-caused-signal-fault-widens|title=Signal interference issue plagues Circle line again|newspaper=TODAYonline|access-date=2016-12-03}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/transport/circle-line-signal-fault-that-caused-train-disruptions-on-wednesday-morning|title=Circle line signal fault that caused train disruptions on Wednesday similar to problem in September: LTA, SMRT|date=2016-11-02|newspaper=The Straits Times|access-date=2016-12-03}}</ref> A team of [[Data science|data scientists]] explored the data and discovered via a Marey Chart visualization that it was caused by hardware problems, sending errant signals from a \"rogue\" train, PV46.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.techinasia.com/govtech-data-scientists-projects|title=Tech in Asia - Connecting Asia's startup ecosystem|website=www.techinasia.com|language=en-US|access-date=2016-12-03}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blog.data.gov.sg/how-we-caught-the-circle-line-rogue-train-with-data-79405c86ab6a|title=How the Circle line rogue train was caught with data|last=datagovsg|date=2016-12-01|website=Data.gov.sg Blog|access-date=2016-12-03}}</ref>\n\n==Overview==\n===Route===\n[[File:MRT Route Map CC.svg|450px]]\n\nAs the name implies, the Circle Line is an [[orbit]]al [[circle route]] linking all [[radial route]]s leading to the [[Downtown Core (Singapore)|city]]. It also covers many parts of the [[Central Area, Singapore|Central Area]]. From [[Promenade MRT station|Promenade]], the line branches into two, with one branch terminating at [[Dhoby Ghaut MRT station|Dhoby Ghaut]], and the other at [[Marina Bay MRT station|Marina Bay]]. The Circle Line interchanges with all other Mass Rapid Transit lines within Singapore, such as the [[North South MRT line|North South Line]] and [[East West MRT line|East West Line]], which shortens travelling time for commuters by shortening trips between northern, eastern and western Singapore.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lta.gov.sg/content/ltaweb/en/public-transport/projects/circle-line.html|title=Circle line {{!}} Projects {{!}} Public Transport {{!}} Land Transport Authority|website=www.lta.gov.sg|language=en|access-date=2017-09-18}}</ref>\n\n===Stations===\n\n{{main|List of Circle MRT line station names}}\n{|class=\"wikitable\" border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"2\" style=\"margin-left: 1em; margin-bottom: 1em; color: black; border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 95%\"\n|- align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#{{SMRT color|Circle}}\" style=\"color:white\"\n|'''Station Number'''\n|'''Station Name'''\n|'''Images'''\n|'''Interchange/Notes'''\n|-\n|{{SMRT code 3I/C|CC|1|NS|24|NE|6}}||[[Dhoby Ghaut MRT station|Dhoby Ghaut]]||[[File:DhobyGhaut-CCLPlatform.JPG|100px]]||Interchange with the [[North South MRT line|'''{{fontcolor|#dc241f|North South line}}''']] and the [[North East MRT line|'''{{fontcolor|#9016b2|North East line}}''']]\n|-\n|{{SMRT code|CC|2}}||[[Bras Basah MRT station|Bras Basah]]||[[File:Bras Basah MRT Station, 2014 (04).JPG|frameless|100x100px]]||\n|-\n|{{SMRT code|CC|3}}||[[Esplanade MRT station|Esplanade]]||[[File:Esplanade-CCLStation.JPG|100px]]||\n|-\n|{{SMRT code 2I/C|CC|4|DT|15}}||[[Promenade MRT station|Promenade]]||[[File:Promenade-CCLPlatform.JPG|100px]]||Interchange with the [[Downtown MRT line|'''{{fontcolor|#0354A6|Downtown line}}''']]\nChange for train services towards [[Bayfront MRT station|Bayfront]] or [[Marina Bay MRT station|Marina Bay]] stations\n|-\n|{{SMRT code|CC|5}}||[[Nicoll Highway MRT station|Nicoll Highway]]||[[File:NicollHighway-CCLPlatform.JPG|100px]]||&nbsp;\n|-\n|{{SMRT code|CC|6}}||[[Stadium MRT station|Stadium]]||[[File:Stadium MRT Station.jpg|frameless|133x133px]]||Marina Bay shuttle terminus during off-peak hours\n|-\n|{{SMRT code|CC|7}}||[[Mountbatten MRT station|Mountbatten]]||[[File:Mountbatten-CCLPlatform.JPG|100px]]||\n|-\n|{{SMRT code|CC|8}}||[[Dakota MRT station|Dakota]]||[[File:Dakota-CCLPlatform.JPG|100px]]||&nbsp;\n|-\n|{{SMRT code 2I/C|CC|9|EW|8}}||[[Paya Lebar MRT station|Paya Lebar]]||[[File:PayaLebar-CCLPlatform-TopView.JPG|100px]]||Interchange with the [[East West MRT line|'''{{fontcolor|#009530|East West line}}''']]\n|-\n|{{SMRT code 2I/C|CC|10|DT|26}}||[[MacPherson MRT station|MacPherson]]||[[File:MacPherson-CCLPlat