\n|-\n|{{SMRT code 2I/C|CC|22|EW|21}}||[[Buona Vista MRT station|Buona Vista]]||[[File:Interior of the Circle Line section of Buona Vista MRT Station, Singapore - 20110820.jpg|100px]]||Interchange with the [[East West MRT line|'''{{fontcolor|#009530|East West line}}''']]\n|-\n|{{SMRT code|CC|23}}||[[one-north MRT station|one-north]]||[[File:CC23 one-north Platform B.jpg|100px]]||&nbsp;\n|-\n|{{SMRT code|CC|24}}||[[Kent Ridge MRT station|Kent Ridge]]||[[File:CC24 Kent Ridge Platform A.jpg|100px]]||&nbsp;\n|-\n|{{SMRT code|CC|25}}||[[Haw Par Villa MRT station|Haw Par Villa]]||[[File:CC25 Haw Par Villa Exit A.jpg|100px]]||&nbsp;\n|-\n|{{SMRT code|CC|26}}||[[Pasir Panjang MRT station|Pasir Panjang]]||[[File:Platform level of Pasir Panjang MRT Station, Singapore - 20111002.jpg|100px]]||&nbsp;\n|-\n|{{SMRT code|CC|27}}||[[Labrador Park MRT station|Labrador Park]]||[[File:CC27 Labrador Park Platform B.jpg|100px]]||&nbsp;\n|-\n|{{SMRT code|CC|28}}||[[Telok Blangah MRT station|Telok Blangah]]||[[File:CC28 Telok Blangah Platform A.jpg|100px]]||&nbsp;\n|-\n|{{SMRT code 2I/C|CC|29|NE|1}}||[[HarbourFront MRT station|HarbourFront]]||[[File:CC29 Harbourfront Exit A with train.jpg|100px]]||Interchange with the [[North East MRT line|'''{{fontcolor|#9016b2|North East line}}''']]\n|-\n!colspan=4|Stage 6 <small>''(under construction, to be ready by 2025)''</small>\n|-\n|{{SMRT code|CC|30}}||[[Keppel MRT station|Keppel]]||||\n|-\n|{{SMRT code|CC|31}}||[[Cantonment MRT station|Cantonment]]||||\n|-\n|{{SMRT code|CC|32}}||[[Prince Edward Road MRT station|Prince Edward Road]]||||\n|-\n!colspan=4|Circle Line extension\n|-\n|{{SMRT code 2I/C|CE|1|DT|16}}<br>{{SMRT code 2I/C|CC|34|DT|16}} (from 2025)||[[Bayfront MRT station|Bayfront]]||[[File:CE1 Bayfront Platform B.jpg|100px]]||Cross-Platform Interchange with the [[Downtown MRT line|'''{{fontcolor|#0354A6|Downtown line}}''']]\n|-\n|{{SMRT code 3I/C|CE|2|NS|27|TE|20}}<br>{{SMRT code 3I/C|CC|33|NS|27|TE|20}} (from 2025)||[[Marina Bay MRT station|Marina Bay]]||[[File:CE2 Marina Bay Platform A.jpg|100px]]||Interchange with the [[North South MRT line|'''{{fontcolor|#dc241f|North South line}}''']] and the [[Thomson-East Coast MRT line|'''{{fontcolor|#734538|Thomson-East Coast line}}''']] <small>''(2021)''</small>\n|}\nThe Circle Line's numbering scheme reserves station code \"CC18\" for future use.\n\n==Rolling stock==\nThe [[rolling stock]] consists of 40<ref>{{cite speech | url = http://www.news.gov.sg/public/sgpc/en/media_releases/agencies/mot/speech/S-20120504-1/AttachmentPar/0/file/Tuas%20West%20Extension%20Groundbreaking%20Ceremony%20Speech%20on%20040512_media.pdf | title = Tuas West Extension Groundbreaking Ceremony Speech | publisher = Land Transport Authority | date = 4 May 2012 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20130929131926/http://www.news.gov.sg/public/sgpc/en/media_releases/agencies/mot/speech/S-20120504-1/AttachmentPar/0/file/Tuas%20West%20Extension%20Groundbreaking%20Ceremony%20Speech%20on%20040512_media.pdf | archivedate = 29 September 2013 }}</ref> [[Alstom Metropolis C830]] trains<ref>[http://app.lta.gov.sg/corp_press_content.asp?start=785 AWARD OF ELECTRICAL & MECHANICAL SYSTEMS CONTRACT 830 FOR THE MARINA line] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110527043441/http://app.lta.gov.sg/corp_press_content.asp?start=785 |date=2011-05-27 }}</ref> running in three-car formation. They are stabled at [[Kim Chuan Depot]], the world's largest underground depot when it opened in 2009.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/transport/biggest-underground-train-depot-set-to-become-even-bigger|title=Biggest underground train depot set to become even bigger|website=The Straits Times|access-date=2016-03-04}}</ref>  24 new [[Alstom Metropolis & Shanghai Electric C830C]] trains were delivered to SMRT from end July 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://app.lta.gov.sg/apps/news/page.aspx?c=2&id=5qmktlgi52sor9rc5r00c6xm8pg371lwhgx5hvtwu8381p6o95 |title=LTA and SMRT Award Contracts for New Trains and Re-Signalling Project |date=1 February 2012 |accessdate=16 November 2013 |publisher=Land Transport Authority |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130929162504/http://app.lta.gov.sg/apps/news/page.aspx?c=2&id=5qmktlgi52sor9rc5r00c6xm8pg371lwhgx5hvtwu8381p6o95 |archivedate=29 September 2013 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.alstom.com/press-centre/2012/2/80885/ | title=Alstom to supply 34 Metropolis trains and upgrade signaling on the system | date=3 February 2012 | accessdate=16 November 2013 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131231010930/http://www.alstom.com/press-centre/2012/2/80885/ | archivedate=31 December 2013 }}</ref> They began operation on 26 June 2015. Currently, all 24 C830Cs are in revenue service.\n\nThe automated CBTC system on board relies on \"continuous two-way digital communication\" between each controlled train and the control centre.\n\nTo facilitate the extension of the line with the construction of Stage 6, a tender for additional trains for the line was published on 31 March 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lta.gov.sg/apps/tender/default.aspx?scr=yes&Ref=851E&scrdate=&fromdate=&todate=&keyword=|title=Tender information {{!}} Land Transport Authority|website=www.lta.gov.sg|language=en|access-date=2017-04-23}}</ref>\n\n==Train control==\nThe Circle Line is equipped with [[Alstom]] Urbalis 300 [[Communications-based train control]] (CBTC) [[moving block]] signalling system on the MASTRIA system with [[Automatic train control]] (ATC) under [[Automatic train operation]] (ATO) GoA 4 (UTO). The subsystems consist of [[Automatic train protection]] (ATP) to govern train speed, Iconis Automatic Train Supervision (ATS) to track and schedule trains and Smartlock [[Computer-based interlocking]] (CBI) system that prevents incorrect signal and track points to be set.<!--Note:Please do not delete any hidden content in the train control section-->\n\nTrain Data Management System (TDMS) which concentrate and dispatch the rolling stock information with fixed equipment. The IAGO Waveguide communications network has the capability to transmit video and is almost maintenance-free. Base stations are located within the signalling equipment room.\n\nAutomatic [[platform screen doors]] supplied by [[Westinghouse Rail Systems|Westinghouse]] provide safety for commuters, offering protection from arriving and departing trains.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|3}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Commons category-inline|Mass Rapid Transit (Singapore) Circle Line}}\n* [http://www.lta.gov.sg/content/ltaweb/en/public-transport/projects/circle-line.html Circle line]\n* [https://www.lta.gov.sg/content/dam/ltagov/who_we_are/statistics_and_publications/books/pdf/Circle_Line_Book.pdf LTA's commemorative book detailing the construction of the Circle Line]\n\n{{Singapore MRT stations|circle=yes}}\n{{Rail transport in Singapore}}\n{{Urban Rail Transit in ASEAN}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Circle MRT line}}\n[[Category:Mass Rapid Transit (Singapore) lines]]\n[[Category:Railway lines opened in 2009]]\n[[Category:Railway loop lines]]\n[[Category:2009 establishments in Singapore]]\n", "name_user": "Lise Hereford", "label": "safe", "comment": "rmv unofficial and unused logo", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Circle_MRT_line"}
{"title_page": "Po\u00e1s Volcano", "text_new": "{{Infobox mountain\n| name = Po\u00e1s Volcano\n| photo = Poas crater.jpg\n| photo_caption = Po\u00e1s volcano crater, shown before the 2017 eruptions\n| elevation_m = 2,708\n| elevation_ref =<ref name=SMI>[https://volcano.si.edu/volcano.cfm?vn=345040 GLOBAL VOLCANISM PROGRAM, SMITHSONIAN INSTITUTION]</ref>\n| prominence = \n| location = [[Costa Rica]]\n| range = [[Cordillera Central, Costa Rica|Cordillera Central]]\n| coordinates = {{coord|10.2|N|84.233|W|display=inline,title|type:mountain}}<ref name=SMI/>\n| map = Costa Rica\n| map_caption = Location in Costa Rica\n| topo = \n| type = [[Stratovolcano]]\n| age = \n| last_eruption = February 2019\n| first_ascent = \n| easiest_route = Hike\n}}\n\nThe '''Po\u00e1s Volcano''', ({{lang-es|Volc\u00e1n Po\u00e1s}}), is an active {{Convert|2708|m|adj=on}} [[stratovolcano]] in central [[Costa Rica]] and is located within [[Poas Volcano National Park]]. It has erupted 40 times since 1828, including April 2017 when visitors and residents were evacuated.<ref name=\"news.co.cr\">{{Cite web | url=http://news.co.cr/new-eruption-at-poas-volcano-in-costa-rica-forces-evacuation-of-a-few-neighbors/59243/ |title = New Eruption at Poas Volcano in Costa Rica Forces Evacuation of Residents as Preventive Measure|date = 2017-04-13}}</ref> The volcano and surrounding park were closed for nearly 17 months, with a 2.5 kilometer safety perimeter established around the erupting crater.<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.ticotimes.net/2017/04/17/poas-volcano-turrialba |title = Po\u00e1s Volcano closed indefinitely; Turrialba keeps spewing ash}}</ref> As of September 1, 2018 the park has reopened with limited access only to the crater observation area and requires a reservation to be made on the National Park Website.  Adjacent trails to Lake Botos as well as the museum at the visitor center remained closed. The volcano erupted briefly twice in September 2019.<ref> https://ticotimes.net/2019/09/30/poas-volcano-erupts-again-sends-ash-cloud-2-km-into-atmosphere </ref>\n\n== Crater lakes ==\nThere are two crater lakes near the summit. The northe blabla rn lake is known as the ''Laguna Caliente'' (\"hot lagoon\") and is located at a height of 2,300&nbsp;m in a crater approximately 0.3&nbsp;km wide and 30&nbsp;m deep. It is one of the world's most acidic lakes. The acidity varies after rain and changes in volcanic activity, sometimes reaching a [[pH]] of almost 0; consequently, it supports little or no aquatic life. The bottom of this lake is covered with a layer of liquid sulfur.<ref>{{citation |author= O. Vaselli, F. Tassi, A.Minissale, G. Montegrossi, E. Duarte, E.Fernandez, E. Bergamaschi |title = Fumarole migration and fluid geochemistry at Po\u00e1s Volcano (Costa Rica) |publisher = The Geological Society of London. |year =  2003 |url = https://books.google.com/books?id=zsPoH-aCJqwC&pg=PA256&lpg=PA256&dq=Po%C3%A1s+acid+rain+Laguna+Caliente#v=onepage&q&f=false|isbn = 9781862391369 }}</ref> Acid gases create [[acid rain]] and acid fog, causing damage to surrounding ecosystems and often irritation of eyes and lungs.\n\n[[Lake Botos]], the southern lake, fills an inactive crater, which last erupted in 7500&nbsp;[[Anno Domini|BC]]. It is cold and clear, and is surrounded by a [[cloud forest]] within the National Park boundaries.\n\n== Eruptive history ==\n\n[[File:Volc\u00e1n Po\u00e1s columna de humo.JPG|thumb|Column of smoke rising from the main crater]]\n\nOn May 17, 1953, an eruption occurred that started a cycle that lasted until 1956. At least two people were reported missing.<ref>[https://www.crhoy.com/nacionales/video-asi-asusto-a-los-ticos-el-poas-en-1953/ (Video) As\u00ed asust\u00f3 a los ticos el Po\u00e1s \u00a1en 1953!]</ref>\n\nPo\u00e1s was near the epicenter of a 6.1-magnitude [[2009 Costa Rica earthquake|earthquake in January 2009]] that killed at least forty people and affected [[Fraijanes, Costa Rica|Fraijanes]], [[Vara Blanca]], [[Cinchona, Costa Rica|Cinchona]] (the most affected area), the capital [[San Jos\u00e9, Costa Rica|San Jos\u00e9]], and the Central Valley region of Costa Rica.\n\nThere was also eruptive activity in 2009 involving minor [[phreatic eruption]]s and [[landslide]]s within the northern active crater.  Po\u00e1s eruptions often include [[geyser]]-like ejections of crater-lake water.\n\nOn February 25, 2014, a webcam from the Volcanological and Seismological Observatory of Costa Rica (OVSICORI) captured the moment a dark cloud exploded about 1,000 feet in the air from a massive crater of the Po\u00e1s Volcano.  This volcano remains active today.<ref>[http://www.nydailynews.com/news/world/poas-volcano-erupts-central-costa-rica-article-1.1701326 NY Daily News 2/25/14]</ref><ref>[http://news.co.cr/volcano-tourists-costa-rica-enjoy-phreatic-eruption/35354/ Costa Rica Star News 12/28/16]</ref>\nPo\u00e1s is one of 9 volcanoes currently monitored by the [[Deep Earth Carbon Degassing Project]]. The project is collecting data on the [[carbon dioxide]] and [[sulfur dioxide]] emission rates from [[Subaerial eruption|subaerial volcanoes]].<ref>{{cite web|title=DECADE Installations at Turrialba and Po\u00e1s|url=https://deepcarbon.net/feature/decade-installations-turrialba-and-po\u00e1s#.V-ltH2MomXh|website=Deep Carbon Observatory|accessdate=26 September 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== 2017 Activity ===\n\nOn April 9, 2017, National Park officials placed restrictions on visitors at Poas due to an increased volume of toxic gases at the summit crater.<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.ticotimes.net/2017/04/10/poas-volcano-gases | title=Gas, vapor at Po\u00e1s Volcano prompts preventive measures}}</ref> An explosion on April 12 caused park officials to close the popular park to visitors. The measure was termed \"temporary.\" <ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.ticotimes.net/2017/04/13/poas-volcano-eruption | title=UPDATE: Po\u00e1s Volcano eruption prompts temporary closure of national park}}</ref> Some nearby residents were also evacuated.<ref name=\"news.co.cr\"/>\n\nOn April 14, 2017, two eruptions at 07:39 and 07:57 created an over three kilometer ash and vapor column.<ref>[http://www.nacion.com/sucesos/Volcan-Poas-vuelve-erupciones-viernes_0_1627637222.html Volc\u00e1n Po\u00e1s registra erupci\u00f3n de m\u00e1s de 3 kil\u00f3metros de altura]</ref> Further explosions occurred April 16.<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://news.co.cr/another-eruption-sunday-afternoon-poas-volcano-costa-rica/59457/ |title = Poas Volcano National Park in Costa Rica will Remain Closed due to Continuous Eruptions|date = 2017-04-16}}</ref>\n\nFollowing a substantial  blast on April 22 that sent incandescent rocks over a large area which damaged park buildings and infrastructure, Costa Rica President [[Luis Guillermo Solis]] toured the surrounding towns the following two days. Business owners described the negative financial impacts the volcano park closure were causing, and Solis released a video in Spanish and English urging potential tourists to visit the nearby community shops and restaurants. He also promised emergency agencies would continue to make updated reports on the eruption.<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.ticotimes.net/2017/04/24/poas-solis-tour | title=President Sol\u00eds tours Po\u00e1s Volcano region following strong explosion}}</ref>  As of September 1, 2018, the National Park has re-opened with limited access and revised regulations.  Visitors are required to make an online reservation to enter the park and the number of visitors and time allowed at the crater is limited. Only the main crater observation area is open as of September 2018.  Adjacent trails including the trail to the Lake Botos remain closed.\n\n=== 2019 Activity ===\n* February 11, 2019: According to the Volcanological and Seismological Observatory of Costa Rica (OVSICORI), the eruption began at 1:50 a.m. Monday and sent a column of ash 200 meters above the crater.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Z\u00fa\u00f1iga |first1=Alejandro |title=Po\u00e1s Volcano registers overnight eruption, National Park closed Monday |date=11 February 2019}}</ref>\n* September 30 2019, 05:41: Eruption of ash and solid material, with a 2 kilometer column, in contrast of previous water vapor activities on September 23 2019. <ref>{{cite news |last1=Z\u00fa\u00f1iga |first1=Alejandro |title=Po\u00e1s Volcano erupts again, sends ash cloud 2 km into atmosphere |url=https://ticotimes.net/2019/09/30/poas-volcano-erupts-again-sends-ash-cloud-2-km-into-atmosphere |accessdate=30 September 2019 |date=30 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n{{Gallery\n|lines=1\n|width=550\n|height=170\n|File:Panorama 2 Botos Lake (Crater), Poas Volcano Ntl Park CRI 08 2009.jpg|alt1=Lake Botos is an inactive crater within Po\u00e1s Volcano National Park|Lake Botos is an inactive crater within [[Po\u00e1s Volcano National Park]]\n|File:Panorama4 Poas volcano crater.jpg|alt2=Fumarole activity at the Po\u00e1s crater|[[Fumarole]] activity at the Po\u00e1s crater\n}}\n\n== See also ==\n* [[List of volcanoes in Costa Rica]]\n* [[Ark Herb Farm]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Ref fill|date=March 2020}}\n{{Reflist}}\n* [http://www.volcano.si.edu/world/volcano.cfm?vnum=1405-04= Global Volcanism Program: Po\u00e1s]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110708060610/http://volcano.oregonstate.edu/vwdocs/volc_images/north_america/costa_rica/new_poas.html Volcano World: Poas, Costa Rica]\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=s4qaEjSPRcU bathymetric survey of Laguna Caliente with a drone boat]\n\n{{commons category|Po\u00e1s Volcano}}\n\n{{Volcanoes of Costa Rica}}\n{{Mountains of Costa Rica}}\n{{Central American volcanoes}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Poas}}\n[[Category:Stratovolcanoes of Costa Rica]]\n[[Category:Active volcanoes]]\n[[Category:Volcanic crater lakes]]\n[[Category:Geography of Alajuela Province]]\n[[Category:Mountains of Costa Rica]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox mountain\n| name = Po\u00e1s Volcano\n| photo = Poas crater.jpg\n| photo_caption = Po\u00e